<HEADLINE>#2.5m boost announced for Scottish Ambulance Service</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRISTOPHER REEKIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651395</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S 430 front-line ambulances are to be equipped with sophisticated new
machines to help save heart-attack victims.
The #1m, state-of-the-art defibrillators use an electric current to re-start
the heart.
They are part of a #2.5m package for the Scottish Ambulance Service announced
yesterday by Minister of State for Scotland Lord James Douglas-Hamilton on a
visit to its headquarters in Edinburgh.
The rest of the package comprises #900,000 for new vehicles, #300,000 on a new
ambulance station for Clydebank, and #250,000 to complete the service's command
and control system across Scotland.
The new defibrillators will replace existing equipment.
Lord James said they would enable the service to continue to play a vital role
in the battle to reduce death from heart disease in Scotland.
The new Clydebank station is to be fully-operational by the end of next June,
will help the service to maintain good ambulance response times.
Lord James said that last week he and Scottish Office officials had discussed
how best to redistribute #13m of capital resources which had been identified
through monitoring of slippage and capital schemes.
He had realised the benefits to be gained from approving funds for the key
developments in the ambulance service.
A Scottish Office spokesman said Lord James had talked to ambulance staff
during yesterday's visit.
Two paramedics told him they used the defibrillators three or four times a
month and assured him that they were life-savers.
</TEXT>
