<HEADLINE>Minister queries anomalies in Labour's training pledge</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651396</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR was asked yesterday to explain where the long-term funding would come
from for the training programme for unemployed under-25s announced last autumn
by Shadow Chancellor Gordon Brown.
Employment Minister James Paice asked what funding would replace the proceeds
of the windfall tax on the privatised utilities which was to launch the
programme. As a windfall tax was by definition a one-off, who would pay in the
second and subsequent years?
Mr Paice also inquired how much of the tax would be available for funding the
programme, as Opposition spokesmen, he calculated, had pledged 11 new spending
programmes that were to be paid from it.
He also raised the question of young people in the scheme pricing others out of
jobs, since employers, offered #60 a week for six months to take them on, might
substitute them for other workers.
The Minister pressed Labour to make it clear if the scheme would be compulsory.
At the launch, Labour indicated that those who failed to take up a job offer
would have a proportion of their benefit cut.
Remarks by Shadow Employment Secretary Michael Meacher in a television
interview that the scheme might offer more to employers than employees showed
he was ``embarrassed'' about it, said Mr Paice.
</TEXT>
