<HEADLINE>British Airways fires first salvo in January price war</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651397</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Airways yesterday launched its own January sales and opened the way for
a new fare war with rival Virgin.
BA slashed prices on almost 100 routes from Brussels to Brisbane for anyone
booking by January 17.
The January sales idea was first launched by BA last year under its World Offer
scheme and immediately opened a price war with Richard Branson's Virgin.
He immediately pledged to undercut BA by #1 on all the routes shared by both
airlines and he seems set to announce the same deal this year. When BA
announced their discounts yesterday, Virgin claimed they were just about to
announce their own prices.
BA's deal is designed to fill seats on otherwise quiet flights up to the end of
March.
It includes return trips to New York for #196 and Australia for #596.
BA has now sold more than 1.5 million World Offer holidays since it was started
in March 1994.
Among the 100 BA routes with discounts until January 17 are return flights to
Nice, Madrid or Vienna for #96 - saving up to #93.
A return flight to Harare in Zimbabwe is #599, saving #358 and to Dubai from
#449, saving #277. Nairobi is cut by #356 to #439.
San Francisco and Los Angeles are down by #107 to #296 and Darwin and Perth in
Australia are available from #596 - a #161 saving.
There are 60 European routes, about 20 long-haul destinations and almost as
many domestic flights, including Belfast and Manchester from #55 return.
Returns to Glasgow, Edinburgh, Aberdeen, and Inverness from London are
available from #68.
Some of the worldwide offers are available from other airports apart from
Heathrow - the #196 New York return also goes from Glasgow and Birmingham, for
instance.
A spokeswoman for BA said: ``Last year's January sale was highly successful so
we decided to do it again.
``There are some terrific bargains around on almost 100 routes for people who
want to travel early next year.''
</TEXT>
