<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Latest Belfast killing puts new pressure on the peace process</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651398</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Northern Ireland peace process was under new pressure last night after the
latest paramilitary-style killing in Belfast.
Even though no organisation admitted responsibility for the shooting of petty
criminal Martin McCrory, 3O - the sixth man murdered since April - the IRA is
being blamed for directing the campaign of attacks in republican areas of the
city.
Senior RUC officers fear there could be more deaths and, last night, Ulster
Unionist leader David Trimble said it was time the Government and the
leadership of the nationalist SDLP spoke out about the heightening scale of
terror which has left four dead this month.
He said: ``It is a matter of major concern that there now is a return to
violence after nationalists assured us of a permanent peace. The silence from
the SDLP leadership is quite deafening and obviously there is no ceasefire when
people are being murdered.
``The Government and those nationalists promoting the peace process must come
clean on this. They have got to face up to what is going on and see how they
can help the authorities bring it to an end.''
Most of the victims of the five previous killings were suspected drug dealers
and the attacks were apparently part of a so-called republican purge.
However, Mr McCrory, hit by a shotgun blast at his home at Norglen Parade, Turf
Lodge, was, according to security sources, a known car thief and burglar with
only minimal involvement in drugs.
He was shot in the legs by the IRA seven years ago in a punishment attack.
His three-year-old son, who was sitting beside him at the time of the latest
fatal shooting through a back, ground-floor window, was slightly injured in the
hand. His common-law wife and another son, aged eight, escaped unhurt.
The violence has clearly unsettled Ministers in London and Dublin at a
particularly difficult and tense time for the peace process.
Although the IRA ceasefire still stands, there is growing unease among senior
RUC officers that the shootings will continue.
One security source said last night: ``Who knows when they will stop and that's
a big concern. I can't see it getting out of control but I can't see an end in
sight either. Some of these people who believed themselves to be at risk
cleared off to England. The majority drifted back and it could get to the stage
where they (the killers) don't really want to stop.
``It's the heavy hand at work. It's a way of life. Feelings don't come into it,
certainly not the ceasefire.''
West Belfast SDLP MP Dr Joe Hendron believes the Provisionals were behind it.
He said: ``It's another phase of the onslaught against a section of the
nationalist people and if Sinn Fein want to be considered democrats, then this
campaign must be stopped.''
A group calling itself Direct Action Against Drugs (DAAD) said it was
responsible for Mr McCrory's killing.
The organisation used a recognised password in a claim to a local radio station
but police believe it is a flag of convenience for the IRA.
The group had claimed responsibility for most of the other five killings since
April.
q The terrorist ceasefires helped boost the number of tourists visiting the
Irish Republic in 1995 to a record 4.2 million, according to preliminary
figures.
</TEXT>
