<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Gloom at the bookies' when the bets are off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STARRS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651400</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT could have cost them #100,000 - but bookies would rather have seen a white
Christmas in London than faced the white-out that has confined race horses to
their stables across the country.
Boxing Day, normally one of the busiest days of the year for turf accountants,
was dismally quiet as - with the exception of one meeting in Limerick, all
races in the UK and Ireland were called off because of frozen tracks.
It was the first white-out for horse racing for 33 years.
Nearly all horse racing has been cancelled for the rest of the week - only
Wolverhampton will be offering action, with fixtures on its all-weather ground
on Saturday.
Punters have been left with the option of putting their money on dogs or South
African horse racing, which they can monitor via satellite.
Darts, American football, and rugby events are also coming up, but football -
the other main attraction for gamblers - will be devastated this weekend.
Only four games are likely to go ahead, at grounds with undersoil heating -
Rangers v Hibs, Hamilton Accies v St Mirren, Dundee United v Airdrie, and
Queen's Park v Ross County.
Horse racing fan Bob Hunter said yesterday: ``There's nothing for me to do. I'm
on holiday until January 3 and I like to punt as a hobby, but there's nothing
for me to punt on.
``South African horse racing is a joke, there's no detailed form. Punters at
the bookmaker's know the horses they're going in for, but with South Africa
it's only numbers.
``When there's been a bad winter in the past, there's always something
organised but this year it's absolutely terrible. It's bad organisation by the
British Horse Racing Board.''
Mr Jack Smith, a director of Glasgow-based John Smith Bookmakers, says his
turnover and profit are both 50% down this week. Most of the regular customers
at his betting office in West Nile Street - one of seven in Glasgow and
Coatbridge - are staying at home.
Mr Smith said:``There are so many meetings on Boxing Day that a few usually
survive if the weather turns bad.
``We need continuity so that the punters who are coming in know what they are
doing. Once you have a break, it affects profitability.''
A spokesman for Ladbrokes bookmakers said: ``Betting shops have a social
atmosphere. People are coming in for only a couple of minutes instead of 15.
``It's true that we didn't have to pay out on the white Christmas bets but we
would rather have paid out on that than lost Boxing Day.''
Mr John Smee, spokesman for the British Horse Racing Board, said it needed
three days' notice to re-arrange fixtures.
He added: ``The weather forecasts are not particularly good and a lot of race
courses were making positive noises up until Boxing Day morning.
``If we had known three days before Boxing Day that we would be faced with a
white-out, we could have had all-weather track racing.
``The only fixtures we can line up are at all-weather tracks and we have begun
to do that.
Mr Smee said additional fixtures being staged this week would not be regarded
as cost effective by the Levy Board, the Government body which collects revenue
and distributes it as prize money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
