<HEADLINE>Helicopters display big guns ready for use if force is needed to implement peace deal.  British in Bosnian show of strength</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>SEAN MAGUIRE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651401</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Nato helicopters flew big guns over the frozen fields of Bosnia to show
its former warriors they mean business.
``We want everyone to realise we have the capability to use force against force
if we have to, though we hope it will never happen. We're advertising very
visibly that we have guns,'' said British Nato spokesman Colonel David Shaw.
Two RAF Chinook helicopters swept across the deep valleys, startling children
and turning heads as the British put on a noisy show of might.
Slung beneath the helicopters were 105mm field guns and crates of ammunition
that swung out wide as the aircraft banked over the now-silent confrontation
lines that divide Croat and Muslim-led government forces from the Serbs.
The weaponry was dramatically delivered to a field just outside Sanski Most,
one of the last towns seized by Muslim and Croat forces in a summer campaign of
conquest that helped to compel the Bosnian Serbs into agreeing a peace deal.
The barrels of the six guns were pointed towards the confrontation line.
The British must ensure the two sides pull back from each other's throats by
the middle of next month.
``This has been quite an overt movement,'' said Lieutenant Alan Parks, the Gun
Position Officer. ``We're here to show Nato's strength and resolve to implement
the peace deal.''
One of his soldiers commented: ``This should impress the locals . . . it'll
scare them so they behave themselves.''
The Chinooks flew low over burnt-out houses in desolate landscapes marched over
back and forth by armies last summer. Their flight path traced a way through
some of the area's most volatile zones.
Light cloud cleared as the pair of heavy twin-rotored craft swept slowly over
the Croat-held town of Jajce, where a British helicopter was shot at three days
ago in what Nato said was a dangerous show of indiscipline. All was quiet below.
``We purposefully flew over a couple of areas today so they could see we're
here. Hopefully then there will be no messing about,'' said a sergeant, holding
his machinegun in an icy draught coming through the helicopter's gunport.
On the ground, other British units of the peace force were moving deeper into
Serb-held territory.
Armoured vehicles from the Light Dragoons regiment headed to set up a base in
Prijedor, an area that saw some of the most vicious ``ethnic cleansing'' at the
beginning of the war.
Other British troops have moved into the Serb citadel of Banja Luka, in the
deepest penetration yet of strongholds off limits to Nato's precursors, the
United Nations. The Alliance said all its forces were warmly welcomed.
With the bulk of the British peace force of 13,000 men and heavy tanks not due
to arrive for some weeks, officials concede there is an element of bluff to its
helicopter tactics.
``This is just a taster of what we've got, there's more to come,'' said one
Nato officer among the 2500 British troops so far in Bosnia.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000009</DOCNO>
