<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Survey shows breast-fed babies grow up with better brainpower</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651402</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BABIES suckled on mother's milk grow up to be brighter than their bottle-fed
counterparts, according to a medical survey released yesterday.
The study showed that university entry could depend on whether the applicant
was breast-fed in the first 10 weeks of life, and that pre-term babies fed on
mother's milk had an IQ eight points higher than those who were put on formula
or cow's milk.
About 8OO babies were followed up by Cambridge-based Dr Alan Lucas of the
Medical Research Council, who discovered the alarming difference in their
intelligence.
Professor Michael Crawford, head of the Institute of Brain Chemistry and Human
Nutrition at Queen Elizabeth Hospital for Children in Hackney, east London,
plans to present the findings to a conference on children's health next month.
He said: ``Latest research shows babies fed on mother's milk have an IQ eight
points up on those put on formula or cow's milk An IQ of 112 would not normally
be enough to qualify an applicant for a place at university, whereas an IQ of
12O would suffice. Mother's milk in pre-term babies could have provided those
vital eight points.''
Professor Crawford said: ``It was a very large study and those babies fed on
formula had a much lower IQ compared to breast-fed ones - who were also more
resistant to infections.
``There are obvious reasons for this because there are certain products in
human milk not present in bottled milk, including growth factors which may
influence brain development.
``There are also nutrients present in human milk important for the growth and
development of the brain.
``One or two formula companies are at long last beginning to put them in after
realising the differences.''
Heart disease and diabetes may also be linked to nutrition in early childhood.
And to what extent breast, colon, and prostate cancers, among the most frequent
causes of death from cancer, may also be linked to diet will be discussed at
the conference.
Research shows that people who live off a fish diet are among the least likely
to fall victim to these forms of cancer. In Japan, Africa, and Asia, such
cancers are comparatively rare compared to Europe or America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000010</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000010</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A violent sequel to Braveheart</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651403</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THREE Scots, carried away with the chauvinism of Braveheart, were less
enamoured with the sequel when police with English accents arrived at a Fife
cinema.
The three men from Glenrothes began shouting and swearing as they became caught
up in the mood of the hit film, Kirkcaldy Sheriff Court was told yesterday.
When the police officers with English accents turned up in response to a
management call, two of the men ended up struggling with them.
George Naylor, 35, of Bruce Road; John Naylor, 34, of Canmore Road; and Andrew
Mayes, 32, of Elgin Drive, were appearing before Sheriff William Christie.
George Naylor and Mayes admitted that on October 4 in the Glenrothes Cinema at
Carrickgate, they conducted themselves in a disorderly manner, shouted and
swore, refused to leave when asked to do so, struggled with police, and
committed a breach of the peace.
John Naylor admitted the same charge, with the exception of struggling with the
police.
Depute fiscal Christine Baillie said the men became very angry during the film
and shouted and swore, disturbing other patrons.
Staff called police but the men refused to leave.
``It became apparent to the accused the officers had strong English accents,''
said Ms Baillie, adding that this ``aggravated matters''.
George Naylor was handcuffed but John Naylor managed to leave the cinema during
the fracas and was arrested later, said Ms Baillie, adding that all three had
been drinking.
Defence agent Martin Collins said: ``It's not uncommon for the audience to
respond to this film in a fairly vigorous manner.
``The film, I understand, seeks as part of the oeuvre, to stimulate a
particularly chauvinistic kind of nationalism.''
When Mr Collins, who speaks with an English accent, pointed out that he
approached the matter ``from the point of view of someone who is not native to
these shores'', Sheriff Christie commented: ``I am surprised your clients
instructed you then.''
George Naylor was ordered to undertake 150 hours of community service, John
Naylor was fined #200, and Mayes was fined #150.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
