<HEADLINE>Bus crash whiplash injury cost driver his job and forced him to abandon fitness hobbies #200,000 damages for cabbie</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN Law Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651404</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A TAXI driver who suffered whiplash injuries when a bus ran into the back of
his vehicle has been awarded #204,000 damages.
The injury has forced fitness enthusiast Colin Paterson, 35, to give up his job
and his hobbies of weightlifting, karate, and swimming.
The Court of Session had heard that Mr Paterson, of Hollowglen Road, Glasgow,
had stopped his Ford Orion taxi at traffic lights in Cowcaddens, Glasgow, in
January 1991, when it was hit by a Kelvin Central bus, causing extensive damage.
Liability against Motherwell-based Kelvin Central Buses Ltd was not disputed.
In a written judgment, Lord Dawson said Mr Paterson had not initially felt the
effects of any injury.
He went to bed after being driven home and it was only when he woke up the
following morning that he felt a pain in his neck. It then became clear that he
had suffered a whiplash injury, which still affected him when the case came to
court.
Lord Dawson said Mr Paterson had suffered previous neck injuries and the main
dispute in the case was whether his persisent problems were caused by the crash
or by an earlier incident.
The bus accident happened several weeks after Mr Paterson had returned to work
following treatment for another neck injury caused by a fall.
After hearing medical evidence, the judge decided Mr Paterson had recovered
from the after effects of the fall when the bus hit his taxi and that his
subsequent problems were caused by the crash.
Before the accident, Mr Paterson had worked almost exclusively as a driver,
including a spell with an Army driving unit. He began driving taxis in 1988 and
got his own plate in 1990.
The court heard that he had tried returning to work since his accident but
suffers pain after driving for about 20 minutes and has difficulty turning his
head.
The judge added: ``He has not worked since. He considers it would be dangerous
to go back to driving.''
Mr Paterson also suffers from dizzy spells and his sleep is often disturbed.
He told the court he had tried in vain to find other work but his prospects
were hampered by having done little apart from driving. He also suffers from
dyslexia.
Lord Dawson said: ``His wife spoke to his continued frustration at not being
able to work and having to rely on her to support the family. I accepted that
evidence as credible and reliable.''
He awarded a total of #204,150 to cover past and future loss of earnings and to
compensate for Mr Paterson's pain and suffering.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000012</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000012</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chairman puts Tories on 1996 election alert</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEPHEN McGREGOR, Parliamentary Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651405</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TORY chairman Brian Mawhinney yesterday put the Conservatives on full battle
alert in case the Prime Minister is forced to call a General Election next year.
He made it clear he believed Parliament would run its full course to May 1997
but produced the first acknowledgment by a senior member of the Cabinet that a
poll in 1996 was a possibility. ``We will be ready to go whenever the Prime
Minister calls,'' he said.
In a rallying call which demonstrates the state of nervousness within the Tory
hierarchy, Dr Mawhinney told Conservatives across the country to stop fighting
one another and start thinking votes.
In a clear message to the Euro-sceptics and other warring factions, he said
there was ``no time or tolerance for internal argument or selfish
grandstanding.'' He bluntly told all constituencies: ``I am asking you to put
your association on election alert now.''
Signalling the tone of the arguments the Tories would deploy in the run-up to
the General Election, Dr Mawhinney lambasted Labour leader Tony Blair's past
nuclear disarmament links, saying: ``With Communists back in prominence in
Russia, Britain could never feel safe with a former CND member in Downing
Street.''
Mr Major has made it clear that he wants to play a long game, going to the
country at the last possible moment and certainly allowing time for another,
presumably tax-cutting, Budget next November.
However, he is operating on a wafer-thin Commons majority, which is likely to
be further reduced by by-elections in the Labour stronghold of Hemsworth,
Yorkshire, and in Staffordshire South East after the death of Tory MP Sir David
Lightbown (majority 7192). The party has not won a by-election since 1989.
If Tory MP David Ashby, who recently lost a costly libel action, were to be
declared bankrupt, he would have to quit the Commons. The Tories would have to
defend a majority of only 979 in his Leicetershire North West constituency. In
short, Mr Major could, within a few months, be facing the prospect of running a
minority Government.
It emerged yesterday that a leading firm of actuaries - Lane, Clark, and
Peacock - has predicted there are likely to be four more Tory deaths during
1996. If correct, the prediction would wipe out Mr Major's majority and his
problems could be compounded by poor local-government election results in May.
In his New Year message, Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown said that in
Government there was a divided, discredited Conservative Party that had lost
direction and was out of touch with Britain's people and Britain's needs.
He said: ``They began 1995 in a mess of sleaze and incompetence, they ended the
year in division and disarray. Riven by internal divisions, the Government can
no longer give clear leadership.
``Weighed down by their own record in office, the Government can no longer
convince people that they can deliver the change that people want or Britain
needs.
"Trapped by the consequences of their own economic mismanagement, they can only
buy their survival by undermining the nation's economy, people's jobs, and our
children's future.
``Ensnared by their own broken promises, they are finding it impossible to
regain the trust of the British people.''
Editorial comment ................16
</TEXT>
