<DOCNO>GH951229-000013</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000013</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>China upholds sentence on dissident Wei</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BENJAMIN KANG LIM</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651406</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CHINESE court today rejected the appeal of dissident Wei Jingsheng and upheld
a 14-year prison term for plotting to subvert the government.
Relatives said they would sue the courts for dereliction of duty, and France
demanded the release of the man regarded as the father of China's embattled
democracy movement.
``The appeal of Wei Jingsheng was unreasonable and had to be rejected,'' said
Chief Judge Wang Yi of the Beijing People's Higher Court.
Wei, 45, has no more appeals. ``This is the final trial,'' said court spokesman
Chen Xiong.
The 1995 Nobel Peace Prize nominee now begins his second lengthy jail term. He
was expected to be held in solitary confinement, as in the past.
Wei and his two lawyers attended the sentencing in western Beijing. Dozens of
police surrounded the court building, and foreign reporters were barred from
covering the sentencing.
The appeals bench summoned Wei on Tuesday to a hearing behind closed doors at
which he spoke for more than one hour and gave a written statement. His lawyers
presented a 2000-word defence.
``The evidence is conclusive and the facts brook no denial,'' said Wang Yi in
his judgment.
Wei will be eligible for parole after serving half of his sentence, lawyers say.
His family denounced the trial as a farce and said they planned to take legal
action against the courts for dereliction of duty.
``We are not only depressed, we are very angry,'' Wei's sister, Wei Shanshan,
said in a telephone interview from her home in Hamburg, Germany.
``The courts are shameless . . . The trial was unfair. They had no legal basis
to convict my brother . . . It was ridiculous.''
Wei's brother, Wei Xiaotao, said he would dispute the evidence used against Wei
as politically motivated.
The Beijing Number One People's Intermediate Court convicted Wei on December 13
of financing China's struggling democracy movement, whose existence is seen by
the state as seditious because it questions the Communist Party's absolute
rule.
The earlier verdict triggered international condemnation but Beijing responded
by rebuking foreign countries for meddling in its domestic affairs.
Wei was first imprisoned in 1979 for ``counter-revolutionary incitement'',
advocating democratic change and passing purported military secrets to a
foreign reporter.
He was paroled in September, 1993, six months before the end of his 15-year
sentence.
During his six months of freedom, Wei said he had no regrets and continued to
criticise the Communist Party.
HONG KONG: China has excluded local democrats from the team responsible for
steering Hong Kong through its transition from British colony to Chinese
Special Administrative Region (SAR) in 1997. Appointments to the 150-strong
Preparatory Committee cold-shouldered Hong Kong's most popular political party,
the Democratic Party, and drew heavily from the colony's business elite.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
