<DOCNO>GH951229-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dismissal complaint rejected</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651407</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CLAIM of unfair dismissal against the wife of Kilmarnock Football Club
chairman, Mr Bob Fleeting, has been rejected by a Glasgow industrial tribunal.
Mrs Ann Fleeting, who began managing the Stanecastle Hotel at Irvine earlier
this year, was accused of unfair dismissal by former hotel worker Mrs Caroline
McDonald.
The tribunal heard Mrs McDonald was working at the hotel when Mrs Fleeting
assumed management.
Existing staff were told they would be kept on but the hotel would close for 12
weeks of refurbishment. Mrs McDonald was laid off in April and the hotel was
not ready to re-open until mid-November.
Mrs McDonald's then solicitors had written to Mrs Fleeting and her husband,
raising the question of a redundancy payment but, after that, the matter
``plainly went off the rails'', the tribunal noted.
The tribunal heard the refurbishment work was delayed beyond Mrs Fleeting's
expectations but she told Mrs McDonald she was willing to reinstate her and to
take whatever steps were legally required of her.
The tribunal said the lay-off and what would have to be regarded as extensions
of that lay-off, could not be attributed to blameworthy conduct on Mrs
Fleeting's part.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000015</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000015</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cellmate tells of murder `confession'</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651408</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SELF-CONFESSED thief claimed yesterday that a man confessed to a horrific
murder while they shared a court cell.
Patrick Haggerty told the High Court in Glasgow that George Walker described
how he killed 22-year-old prostitute Leona McGovern, 22.
Haggerty, 36, claimed that Walker told him he was Leona's murderer last week.
He told advocate depute Michael O'Grady he had been put in the same cell as
Walker, 31, after being brought from Barlinnie Prison.
He said that, initially, Walker said Leona must have been killed by a
psychopath. However, he told Mr O'Grady: ``He then told me a belt was put round
her neck and pulled through a fence before she was stabbed 17 times around the
head and neck with a screwdriver.''
Haggerty added: ``He offered to take off his belt and show me how he did it but
I refused. I thought it was tragic what happened to the girl. I believe he
murdered her and that he is a bit of a psychopath.
``He said the girl owed him money for drugs.''
At that point, Haggerty began shouting: ``The man is a danger, you can't let
him out onto the streets.''
He was stopped by Mr O'Grady, who told him: `We don't want your opinions.''
Haggerty also claimed that Walker had told him months earlier, when they were
taking drugs together, that he had ``throttled'' Miss McGovern.
He denied that police had promised they would ``go easy'' on him for giving
evidence.
Walker denies murdering Miss McGovern in Washington Street, behind Strathclyde
Arts Centre, on June 2 this year.
The trial continues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000016</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000016</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Copter crash deal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651409</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COMPENSATION deal for survivors and relatives of men killed in the Cormorant
Alpha helicopter disaster is believed to have been struck after talks in the
United States, it emerged last night.
Ten oil rig workers and a co-pilot died in the 1992 crash, which happened
shortly after the Super Puma helicopter had taken off from the platform.
Lawyers have been battling for compensation from oil companies Shell, Esso, and
Exxon and it is understood that an out of court settlement has now been reached
on ``fairly favourable terms''.
Victims and survivors should receive at least #500,000, it is believed.
A total of 53 claimants, mostly from Scotland, are involved in the legal
dispute.
The latest development follows a wrangle over whether the case should be heard
in Scotland or the US. Claimants prefer US courts because payouts are higher.
A Shell spokesman said last night he could not confirm the reports. Esso UK and
Exxon were unable to comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000017</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000017</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bogus business that can fool most of the people</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651410</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EAGLE-EYED Katherine McMath was praised yesterday for not being fooled by
counterfeit goods.
The nine-year-old pupil at Nether Currie Primary School near Edinburgh was one
of only 4% of people not caught out by fake items in a consumer competition run
by trading standard chiefs.
More than 1000 people were shown a range of bogus and genuine products and
asked to differentiate between the two.
Katherine wasn't fooled once by the 10 fake products, which included a fake
Liverpool top, fake Ray-ban sun-glasses, and a fake Lion King video.
Lothian Trading Standards director Mike Drewry said the results of the survey
showed how difficult it was becoming for the public to tell the difference
between fake and brand- name goods.
Mr Drewry said: ``This survey was one of the most extensive ever undertaken in
Scotland involving consumer product counterfeiting. The findings show that
counterfeiting is no longer a small scale cottage industry type of operation.
``It is now an international trade involving major criminal organisations who
invest heavily in expensive equipment to illegally copy brand-name goods.''
``It's not just perfumes and designer clothes that are now being counterfeited,
fake car parts and aircraft parts, like brakes, are being sold and are putting
the consumer at risk.''
Councillor Brian Fallon, chairman of Lothian Region's general purposes
committee, warned people all over Scotland to be on their guard.
Councillor Fallon said: ``Walk into a lot of pubs at this time of year and
you'll get someone offering you a cheap bottle of perfume or a cut-price watch.
``However, once you get it home, you'll find it's not all that it's cracked up
to be.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000018</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000018</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cricketer on the road to fame</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651411</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
England wicketkeeper Jack Russell may have a street named in his honour in his
home town of Stroud, Gloucestershire.
The town already has a Russell Street in memory of its nineteenth-century MP
and later Prime Minister, Earl Russell. Now it is proposed to change the name
to Jack Russell Street to mark Stroud's pride in its cricketing hero.
</TEXT>
