<DOCNO>GH951229-000019</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000019</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>US company wins cruise missile deal</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ian Bruce,  Defence Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651412</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Ministry of Defence has awarded a #40m contract to the US Loral Federal
Systems company to develop and produce Tomahawk cruise missile kits for seven
of the Royal Navy's nuclear submarines.
The contract, which involves a teaming arrangement with Vickers Shipbuilding
and Engineering Ltd at Barrow-in-Furness, includes training for RN crews and
provision of guidance and fire-control equipment and computer software to allow
the British hunter-killers to launch the missiles from their torpedo tubes.
Loral is expected to oversee installation of the system in the first three
boats. The MoD then foresees putting the work out to tender on the next four.
The MoD has spent more than a year negotiating the purchase of cruise missiles
for its submarine fleet. With essential modifications, any boat with a 21-inch
diameter torpedo tube is capable of launching the Tomahawk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000020</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000020</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A bit of parley with dame of the century</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW YOUNG</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Profile</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651413</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Never shy, Stanley Baxter is retired, ANDREW YOUNG finds, despite one special
small-screen appearance
THERE is something about comedians that makes it difficult for them to retire
while there is still a laugh out there waiting to be had. An exception until
now has been Stanley Baxter. He was adamant he had retired, exit, full stop.
Others have come back, some never gone away. Jack Milroy and Rikki Fulton, as
Francie and Josie, did ``another farewell appearance'' at the Pavilion and have
booked the King's, Glasgow, for ``the best farewell season so far''. Bob Hope,
in his mid-nineties, still makes 'em laugh. George Burns says he will play the
Palladium when he is 100, and he's 99 now.
But Baxter, the ``control freak'', the dame of the century, for whom perfection
is everything, did his last Mother Goose at the King's, Glasgow, four years
ago, told his suffering agent to accept no more work, apart from radio and
television commercial voice-overs. Diminishing production values did not meet
his standards. It had already happened with his television spectaculars and he
refused to appear in lesser shows although the offers were plentiful.
Everything had to be done by the book, as written by Stanley. And neatly, at
the conventional retirement age of 65, he went back into his private life. Then
along came Michael Grade, head of Channel 4. An independent company had asked
Baxter to choose his favourite bits from 30 glorious, award-laden years of
television. Grade wanted new in-put and his charm persuaded Baxter to provide
the links.
So far as the producers were concerned, it was no longer a case of: ``If ye
want me thingmy, ring me!'' - his catchphrase from the early fifties radio
series It's All Yours in which he appeared with Jimmy Logan. So successful was
he at the retirement business that a Sunday supplement recently ran a huge
cover story based entirely on tracing Baxter, ``the invisible man''. It started
with the premise that he might have become a Howard Hughes-type recluse.
The writer had been brooding on the subject for more than a year, done masses
of research, pored over voters' rolls, gone to the wrong people for leads. It
read like Stanley (the journalist) trying to trace Livingstone. And when he
finally came face to face on a north London doorstep, he blurted out something
like: ``Mr Baxter, I presume?'' What an anti-climax it must have been then to
be told politely to go away.
The great mystery was why it was a mystery. If he regards you as a friend, he
is happy to talk until the cows come home. And sharp, witty, warm-hearted he is
with it. As an ordinary member of the public he retains the actor's chameleon
ability to melt into a crowd. To call him a comedian is perhaps a misnomer. He
is more an actor with a talent to evoke laughter.
In his shows everything had to be done by the script. Ad libs were a danger to
his kind of perfection. In private life he is happy in his own little world
with a routine that suits him very well. He keeps himself fit by swimming so
many lengths of the baths most days, plans ahead, knowing where he is going to
be at a certain time.
There is an appreciation of the good things - like the BMW, the clothes, the
restaurants. He has a select group of friends to whom he is staunchly loyal,
and has sadly seen several of them fall early from the perch, like Kenneth
Williams, LWT producer David Bell, director/choreographer Bruce McClure. Out of
the costumes, he cuts a natty dash. Just now it is the calf-length tweed coat,
the gloves, scarf tied neatly, hat at the right angle. His Mammy would have
been proud of him. He carries with him an air of excitement that is infectious.
As a performer he has always hated the sound of his own voice. His
impersonations of Judy Garland, Marlene Dietrich, Shirley Bassey and HM have
been refinements of his panto dames, caught with an accuracy some have
described as cruel, but there has always been affection there, too.
In his teens he saw Lena Horne in a film at the Ascot, Anniesland. Then he
caught a tram out to the Boulevarde, Knightswood, to see Meet Me in St Louis,
not knowing what it would be like. It was the one in which Judy Garland sang
The Trolley Song. ``And I came out absolutely walking on air,'' he said. ``That
must be the greatest musical I've ever seen, and, although I've seen many
since, I haven't altered that opinion.'' Many of the pastiches to follow were
inspired at that time.
The Baxter household was in Wilton Street, on the edge of gentility, the bit
that could be called North Kelvinside, before it ran into Maryhill. Young
Stanley would be despatched to Jaconelli's Cafe, which was, and still is, in
Maryhill Road, to return with a big jug of ice cream. It was a cosy, cheerful
household. Father was an assistant manager with an insurance company, Mother
had been an aspiring actress. His sister became an actress, stage name Alice
Dale.
Artist Bet Low was a war-time art school student when she became part of a
coterie of friends that included emerging writer Jack Gerson and artist Bill
Henry. He was ``well into theatricals then''. They were to get a preview of
things to come. Stanley would appear from behind the curtains on the big
aureole window of the top flat in Wilton Street, full of confidence, and do his
turns.
Timing was all and, as Bet Low recalls, he would never turn up anywhere unless
he thought the scene had been set. Even going to the left-wing Unity Theatre he
worried that the right people would be there. ``We sparked off each other. He
was always great company.'' He had been so impressed with the Kurt Joost
ballet, Green Table, at the Theatre Royal that he and Low cooked up a ballet of
the life of Buddha for Joost. Baxter now squirms at the conceit, but still
treasures the costume and stage designs done by Low.
There were his years at Hillhead High School. He might not have excelled
academically but he was the tops in writing, producing, and starring in school
pantos and plays. He was on the wireless, too. Aunt Kathleen Garscadden of
Children's Hour put him on a box so his head would come up to the same
microphone level as the others.
Robert Louis Stevenson and a middle-ear infection were, indirectly, to put him
on the road to stardom. As a ``child artiste'' he had been evacuated to
Millport. Returning to Glasgow to play David Balfour in Kidnapped on the
wireless, the unheated train broke down in a snow storm resulting in the
infection.
A sequence of unlikely events then played their part. The Second World War was
still running when, at the age of 17 and three-quarters, he was called up as a
miner, a Bevin Boy (named after Ernest Bevin, then Minister of Labour and
National Service). He was downgraded from A1 when the ear infection came back.
Accepted by the Army, he became a storeman on Rangoon Race Course, thence to
Combined Services Entertainment in Singapore where the first person he met was
Kenneth Williams. They did the complete It Aint Half Hot, Mum bit all over the
Far East and he rates this as the best time he ever had in showbusiness because
he had all of the fun and none of the responsibility.
Bet Low still has the hilarious letters he sent her at that time, full of black
marks contributed by the censor.
Back in Civvy Street everything fell into place, his talents matching the
opportunities. He was in Tyrone Guthrie's Edinburgh Festival production of The
Thrie Estaites, and he was there in time to be part of what he described as the
Camelot years of the Citizens'. He met his wife, actress Moira Robertson.
Working with legendary characters like Duncan Macrae in their Christmas show,
The Tintock Cup, took him on to the Fabulous Five Past Eight shows and pantos
at the Alhambra and the King's, Glasgow. The award-winning television specials
followed.
He had a great affection for Alex Mitchell, who he called ``faither'', a Weekly
News journalist and writer of much of his material, including the Parliamo
Glasgow sketches.
Looking at least 10 years younger than his age, there are many Shakespearean
roles in which he could excel. His comedy overshadowed his serious acting
abilities, like starring in Joe Orton's What the Butler Saw. But he insists it
is radio only, is currently being heard on Radio 2 reading extracts from
Compton Mackenzie's Whisky Galore!
Within a few months of his 70th birthday, he is enjoying every minute of normal
retirement which has now been resumed. Stanley Baxter is back in control.
n Stanley Baxter is Back, is on Channel 4 on Thursday, at 9pm.
Timing was all, Stanley would never turn up anywhere unless he thought the
scene hadbeen set
</TEXT>
</DOC>
