<DOCNO>GH951229-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Master of fairways retires</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651414</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WALTER Woods, one of the most renowned men in the world of golf greenkeeping,
retired yesterday after 21 years at St Andrews.
In that time, Mr Woods prepared the Old Course for four Opens - won by Jack
Nicklaus, Seve Ballesteros, Nick Faldo, and John Daly - as well as 11 Alfred
Dunhill Cups.
As well as masterminding the maintenance and presentation of the six courses at
St Andrews - involving a staff of greenkeepers and engineers totalling more
than 50 - he is a founder member and former chairman of the British and
International Golf Greenkeepers' Association.
A former scratch golfer, he began his career in greenkeeping at the age of 15
in his home town of Tillicoultry.
In a career spanning 45 years, Mr Woods, 61, has received recognition from all
over the world for his skills, including the British Empire Medal in 1991.
He is a former chairman of the advisory committee on greenkeeping at Elmwood
College, Cupar, whose reputation in the field is now recognised throughout the
world.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000022</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000022</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Job fears grow as `fat cats' lap up cream</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Roy Rogers</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>974651415</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Roy Rogers examines the growing gulf between directors and workers
AN UNSAVOURY dichotomy of increasing job insecurity for most workers alongside
continuing ``fat cat'' pay and pensions for many directors is highlighted in
two new               surveys.
Job fears are slowing economic growth, warns the TUC, commenting on a study
showing that 50% of employees throughout the UK - 56% in Scotland - expect
their position to be less secure in the coming year.
Three-quarters (74%) expect to be under more pressure at work in the coming
year and, once again, Scots show greater-than-average anxiety, registering 83%,
which is topped only by the 89% fear rating in the English West Midlands.
The job situation made 73% less likely to move house next year, and nearly
two-thirds (60%) said they were less likely to make major household purchases
or boost their pension payments (64%).
Commenting on the survey, which was commissioned from Harris, TUC general
secretary John Monks said: ``The survey shows that people's insecurity at work
is now a serious brake on economic growth.''
It was restraining the recovery in consumer spending and the return of any real
``feel-good factor'' he said.
The TUC survey of 675 people in current employment found 52% agreed with the
statement ``I expect jobs in my workplace will become less secure in the year
ahead than over the last two years.'' Only 30% disagreed.
The Government's economic forecasts hinge on strong growth in consumption and
the TUC argues this new evidence linking job insecurity and consumer spending
points to weaker economic growth and slower job creation during 1996 than the
Chancellor predicted in last month's Budget.
``The Government have made a rod for their own back by removing many of the
basic protections for people at work,'' said Mr Monks. ``Giving employers a
free hand has done little to boost economic prosperity but it has hit much of
middle-Britain very hard indeed.''
Job insecurity now reaches deep into the country's core workforce, as the TUC
survey reveals levels of concern are highest among professional and
white-collar workers and those in the prime years (35-55) of their working
life. Employees are most worried in London, the West Midlands and Scotland.
``These are key groups which the Conservatives must win over before the next
election,'' said Mr Monks. ``But their programme to scrap basic rights at work
is doing the opposite. Thoughtful Conservatives now recognise this, and see
that people are more concerned about having a job next year than tax cuts.
``Concerns about greater security and fairer treatment at work are set to
become a defining political difference in the year ahead.''
Meanwhile, mounting public concern over job insecurity seems not to have
troubled too many board rooms where a forthcoming Labour research department
survey will show many company directors are still receiving huge pension
contributions on top of already high salaries.
A report in the January issue of the Labour Research magazine finds that more
than a quarter of top directors in the FT Stock Exchange 100 companies were
given contributions of #100,000 or more in one year alone and that just over
half received #50,000 or more.
Topping the league is Jim Fifield, American-based director of the EMI Music
Division of EMI, with a pension contribution of #869,000 - even higher than
most of the directors' salaries. He is followed by Sir Neil Shaw, chair of the
Tate &amp; Lyle sugar group, who was provided with #756,000.
Executives generally do very well in percentage terms, with a third of those in
the survey receiving pension contributions equivalent to more than 20% of their
pay, whereas workers tend to get about 10% of earnings paid into their pension
schemes - just over #1700 a year for those on average earnings.
Sir Neil Shaw's contribution amounted to more than 165% of his #456,000 salary
while the #257,120 contribution received by Blue Circle chief executive Keith
Orrell-Jones represented more than 80% of his #320,320 salary.
A comparison between the two surveys would appear to suggest that Britain's top
directors may well have a monopoly on that ``feel good'' factor which continues
to elude the vast majority of the population.
</TEXT>
