<HEADLINE>Daughter in appeal to her father's killer</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651416</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE daughter of a man stabbed more than 20 times in a Christmas morning street
murder yesterday made an emotional appeal to the killer - ``Tell me why.''
Mrs Vikki Bannon said she could see no reason for her father John Trinder's
killing.
She said: ``They've taken my Christmas, my dad's life, and mine and my family's
with it.''
Mr Trinder, 55, a distant cousin of the comedian Tommy Trinder, died within
yards of his south-east London home after being attacked as he walked back
after a Christmas Eve drink at his local pub.
A smartly-dressed white man in his late 20s was seen running off and getting
into a waiting Ford Fiesta after the murder at 12.30am in Solway Road, Peckham.
Police believe the driver may not have been aware of what happened because the
car was parked around the corner.
Detective Superintendent Gordon King, leading the inquiry, said: ``I'd like
that driver to come forward because he may not know that his passenger stabbed
Mr Trinder over 20 times in a quite vicious, senseless and, as far as I can see
at the moment, motiveless attack.''
Mrs Bannon, 24, an office clerk from nearby New Cross, appealed to the driver,
saying: ``If he didn't know and now he does and he's frightened for some
reason, just come and talk to somebody.''
Mr Trinder, a divorced unemployed scaffolder who lived alone, was a happy
family man, his daughter said.
``He lived for being our dad, mine and my brothers. That's what he had in
life,'' Mrs Bannon said at a police news conference in Peckham.
She said she could think of no incident that could have led to his murder.
She had been with her father in the days before his death and he had spent
Christmas Eve with her godparents.
He had gone to the Rye Hotel that evening for ``an amicable drink'' and there
had been no cross words.
``I can't see any reason. He left the pub on good terms with everybody. He even
borrowed some bread so he could go home and have some supper.
``He wasn't looking for trouble. You don't try to defend yourself with a loaf
of bread.''
Mr King said police did not believe the motive for the attack was robbery
because Mr Trinder had nearly #80 on him and nothing was missing.
Also, a robber would have been unlikely to have stabbed him more than once or
twice.
``As far as I am aware, Mr Trinder was not involved in any illegal activity. He
was not a local criminal.
``He was a bit of a local character. He was Mr Average, Mr Ordinary, minding
his own business, who was set upon by this man for apparently no reason
whatsoever. The sheer ferocity of the attack is almost beyond belief.''
Mr King said the Ford Fiesta either followed Mr Trinder on his five-minute walk
home or was waiting for him.
He described the man seen running from the murder scene as 5ft 9ins, of slim
build, with darkish hair and wearing denim jeans and a white or cream-coloured
top.
</TEXT>
