<HEADLINE>`Fear is the key' to fall in drink-driving figures</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651417</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PEOPLE have a greater fear than ever of being caught drink driving, according
to police chiefs.
Police believe this is supported by a fall in the number of drivers whose tests
have proved positive in the five weeks up until yesterday.
A total of 880 drivers provided positive tests, 18 drivers fewer than the same
period last year, according to figures released by the Association of Chief
Police Officers in Scotland (Acpos).
The decrease comes against a background of a huge rise in the number of drivers
stopped by Scotland's eight police forces. A total of 67,592 have been stopped
since the start of the Scottish Police Forces campaign launched on November 24
- a rise of 60% on the same period last year.
Mr Ian Mackinnon, secretary of the traffic standing committee of Acpos, and
Strathclyde assistant chief constable (traffic), welcomed the continued trend
but pledged that forces throughout Scotland would continue their efforts
against drink-drivers over the New Year holiday period and beyond. ``I am
heartened to see a decrease in the number of positive tests and I think it
reflects a greater fear of being detected drink-driving this year than ever
before,'' he said.
However, he also warned drivers to take extra care in the current icy condition
which ``make for very dangerous driving conditions even without a driver taking
a drink''..
</TEXT>
