<RECORDNO>974651418</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Britons' trial
faces fresh delay
BANGKOK: The trial of two Britons charged with trying to smuggle heroin out of
Thailand was adjourned yesterday as a witness for the defence again failed to
appear.
Sandra Gregory, 30, from Sowerby Bridge, West Yorkshire, and Robert Lock, 30,
from Cambridge, have been in prison since their arrest at Bangkok airport in
February 1993. Miss Gregory, whose family live near Aberdeen, has admitted
trafficking but Mr Lock denies the charges.
Skydiver lives
ALLENTOWN: A skydiver who couldn't open his parachute survived a 3000ft plunge
into a snowy field. Bruce Charles's back-up parachute partially opened just
before he hit the ground. That and a foot-deep cushion of snow saved his life,
said fellow skydivers in Allentown, Pennsylvania. Charles, 56, was in hospital
with injuries to his legs, hips, and back, but was expected to jump again.
Poll date set
MADRID: Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez of Spain announced a General Election on
March 3, signalling what could be the end of his 13-year Socialist rule. The
poll, at least a year early, looks likely to bring the centre-right Popular
Party to power.
Flu hits Ukraine
KIEV: Two million Ukrainians, one-third of them children, have fallen ill with
flu in an epidemic which has claimed five lives. Although the outbreak appeared
to be winding down, doctors have been unable to find a vaccine to combat the
rare and virulent strain. Meanwhile, at least 99 people have died of frostbite
after blizzards hit northern Kazakhstan.
Pilot saved
ATHENS: A Greek rescue helicopter picked up a Turkish pilot who had ejected
with his co-pilot when their Phantom fighter aircraft developed mechanical
problems near the Greek island of Lesbos yesterday. A search continued for the
second pilot.
Tribute to Martin
LOS ANGELES: Frank Sinatra and his wife Barbara, Shirley MacLaine, and former
comedy partner Jerry Lewis were among friends expected to attend a private
service in Los Angeles for Dean Martin. Several Las Vegas hotel-casinos were
dimming their lights for 10 minutes in honour of the legendary performer, who
died on Monday.
Stowaways safe
PARIS: Five Moroccans who stowed away in a container on a cargo ship bound for
Rotterdam were saved from death after the captain heard their cries for help.
French authorities had at first refused the Saarbreda permission to unload the
container when the ship docked in Brest, but later relented.
Suspect held
CAPE TOWN: South African police have arrested an armed robber wanted in
connection with the murder of a British winemaker and several other violent
attacks over the last year. Steven Rainbird, from Sussex, was killed at
Goedvertrouen Farm near Stellenbosch, where he was on an exchange programme.
Flood alert
DURBAN: Hundreds of people have been evacuated from their homes in South
Africa's Zulu heartland after swollen rivers again rose to dangerously high
levels. Police, fearing a repeat of the flood that killed at least 124 people
living on the banks of the Umsunduzi river, used loudhailers to urge people to
leave.
Bomb suspects
RENO: Two men from Gardnerville, Nevada, have been arrested for allegedly
planting a powerful bomb at the Reno office of the US tax agency on December
18. The fuse of the bomb had been lit, but it went out. Investigators have
refused to confirm reports that it was packed with the same fuel used in the
Oklahoma City blast that killed 169 people.
</TEXT>
