<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Homeless boy scam leaves Utah well and truly hoaxed</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651422</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE saddest story this Christmas has ended happily. It concerns a 12-year-old
boy called Michael Ross who was abandoned at a bus station in Salt Lake City
last week. His parents gave him a note saying that they could no longer care
for him, that they were throwing themselves, or him, on the mercy of strangers.
Michael wandered the streets for hours, at last presenting himself and his sad
little note at a social services office. He showed his birth certificate, and
reported that he had never been to school as the family led a nomadic
existence, moving from city to city, always homeless.
The good citizens of Utah took the waif to their hearts. The boy was pampered
and indulged for Christmas, and offers of help
poured in from all over the country. Kind people sent money or offered to
adopt
him. Officials set up a trust fund to administer the donations, and the local
paper set up a fund for him.
All very touching, all very sad. Who could have abandoned the lovely boy? Now
comes the denouement: the boy is a woman, aged 25, who has played the same
trick in at least 11 other states.
The great state of Utah feels rather foolish, but everyone else is grateful
for
this moment of seasonal merriment. A further delight is that the culprit's
real name is Birdie Jo Hoaks.
The hoax was exposed when newspapers in Vermont published the story. Local
authorities there called Salt Lake City. They had heard the story before.
Indeed, Ms Hoaks had spent a few days in jail in Vermont on the charge of
lying
to officials.
Then other states called in. She had been sentenced to nine months for
deception in South Dakota. She had been caught in Kansas when doctors examined
her. Other states, as far apart as Texas and Maine, also reported that she had
tried the same scam. A Boston newspaper reported in 1993 that Ms Hoaks had a
twin sister, Becky, and that they roamed the country claiming they were lost
boys.
Ms Hoaks called a Utah TV station to defend herself: she said that a
young-looking homeless woman was in constant danger, and was better off posing
as a boy.
We have now seen her on television, and she does not look at all like the girl
disguised as a boy in The Swiss Family Robinson. Those very dense Swiss boys
had no excuse, but all those people in Utah, Vermont, and everywhere else can
be forgiven: Ms Hoaks looks just like a rather pudgy teenage boy.
She has been charged with lying and sent to jail. She could be sentenced to 15
years. The only remaining questions are why she kept trying the same scam,
after repeated failures; and which TV network will be first with The Birdie
Hoaks Hoax.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
