<RECORDNO>974651423</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH'S six-day Hogmanay celebrations kicked off last night with a warning
to revellers taking part in the festivities.
Hundreds of thousands of people are expected in the capital over the next few
days to take part in events like the open-air fair at the east end of Princes
Street.
Assistant Chief Constable Tom Wood warned people attending late-night events
over the next few days to be wary of the dangers of the freezing winter
temperatures.
Mr Wood said that, particularly on New Year's Eve, when 200,000 people are
expected in Princes Street, special precautions should be taken.
Police in Lothian also appealed to relatives and friends of the elderly and
infirm to check up on them regularly.
</TEXT>
