<HEADLINE>`In last year's mild winter, 239 Scots died of hypothermia - a cold statistic and a damning indictment' SNP plans cold payments Bill</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent GRAEME SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651424</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE were renewed calls yesterday for a complete overhaul of the Government's
cold-weather payment scheme.
Mrs Margaret Ewing, parliamentary leader of the Scottish National Party,
announced she would be introducing a new Cold Climate Allowance Bill in the
next parliamentary session.
She said: ``The winter chaos and discomfort this year has been compounded by
the Government's ramshackle cold-weather payments system. This system, which is
manifestly unfair, given the need for sub-zero temperatures for seven
consecutive days before payments are triggered, has been shown to be totally
inadequate by the extreme conditions over recent days.
``Last year, during what was a relatively mild winter, 239 Scots died of
hypothermia - a cold statistic which is a damning indictment of the negligible
support provided by the UK Government.''
As the controversy raged, a soup kitchen was set up at Cliasmol School by a
band of worried volunteers on Harris. Soup and food was being handed out to
shivering locals and electricity company workers battling to restore power to
50 homes on the island.
The SNP proposes weekly payments in southern Scotland from December to March of
#7.40, and #11.15 in northern Scotland. ``The total cost of such a system in
Scotland would be #170m per annum - less than 6% of the expected #3000m in
North Sea revenues next year,'' said Mrs Ewing.
Meanwhile, Mr David Logan, convener of the Campaign for Cold-Weather Credits,
called for a system to ensure that people on benefit could afford to burn
enough fuel to keep warm during the winter months.
Ross, Cromarty, and Skye MP Charles Kennedy yesterday joined Western Isles MP
Calum Macdonald in demanding action from the Prime Minister and Social Security
Secretary Peter Lilley over the failure of Stornoway and Tiree weather
monitoring stations to trigger cold-weather payments.
The Tiree station acts as the trigger for a large part of central and Wester
Ross and Mr Kennedy said that he would now be writing to Mr Lilley asking for a
joint meeting when Parliament resumes. Mr Macdonald has already written to the
Prime Minister.
Mr Kennedy said: ``For years, I have been campaigning in Parliament for this
trigger point to be changed. It is clearly insane that Tiree should be used as
a guide for areas and communities like Garve, Torridon, and Ullapool.
``Successive Social Security Ministers have tried to maintain the nonsensical
proposition that Tiree could be regarded as indicative for these parts of my
constituency. That never was a remotely tenable argument and this latest
breathtaking revelation kills it stone dead once and for all.
``I fully endorse Calum's call for a prime ministerial intervention and I am
working with him on this twin-track approach involving Peter Lilley as well.
The immediate crisis must be put right by urgent ministerial intervention.
Thereafter, we need a complete reassessment of the weather station monitoring
map, self-evidently a discredited fiction.
``This entire fiasco would have been turned down as an episode for Yes Minister
on the grounds that it would be too far-fetched. It would be funny if it wasn't
so serious and downright unjust for people losing out in such a blatant
fashion.''
Shetland communities yesterday were continuing to help each other to cope with
the severe storms, which have left many homes isolated. In spite of further
snow falls, the situation was improving.
A Hydro-Electric spokes-woman said last night all electricity supplies on
Shetland had been restored.
She added that work was still being done to restore power to about 50 homes in
the Western Isles.
As food convoys left Lerwick to remote areas, Shetland Islands Council was
monitoring the situation to decide whether or not it would need to accept
external offers of help, including the use of troops.
Yesterday, Shetland coastguard continued to take over the role of the local
ambulances unable to operate on snowbound roads by airlifting two elderly
women, one from West Burra and the other from Sandwick, to hospital in Lerwick.
They also carried out a number of other medical evacuations.
Mr Derek Cox, the director of public health, urged the elderly to keep their
heating on to ensure they were warm.
He said one of the dangers was that some elderly people were not aware of how
cold they were becoming and because they didn't shiver they didn't have the
sensation of being cold and could slip into hypothermia.
However, he said the network of GPs, health workers, and home helps throughout
the islands were being very successful in checking on the welfare of anyone who
might give cause for concern.
Mr Bill Bennett, the council's director of social work, echoed that message. He
said: ``Those on income support should not worry about fuel bills but should
contact the social work department for assistance.''
Chief Inspector William Murray, of Northern Constabulary, said the response to
the emergency had been a co-ordinated effort and public safety remained of
paramount concern. The police urged people in rural areas to make contact with
neighbours to ensure they had adequate warmth and food supplies.
They also issued a warning that people should not travel unless absolutely
necessary to leave roads clear for the snow ploughs.
Shetland Islands Council is concentrating on clearing the main spine roads
throughout Shetland and yesterday they were passable by four-wheel-drive
vehicles. The worst hit area is to the west, where some areas are still
inaccessible.
Mr Joe Gray, director of roads and transport, said the council was doing its
best to deal with all inquiries. The isles of Skerries and Whalsay had supplies
delivered by ferry and arrangements have been made for similar deliveries to
Yell and Unst today.
Yesterday, a convoy of essential supplies from wholesalers in Lerwick was
delivered to rural shops with snow ploughs leading the way to clear any hazards.
This morning, 1500 propane and butane gas cylinders will arrive by ferry from
Aberdeen to help ease the shortage caused by the weather. Sumburgh Airport was
open yesterday and the local bus company was able to operate between Lerwick
and the airport.
</TEXT>
