<HEADLINE>Junior art on subscription</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARCLAY McBAIN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651425</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO operas originally produced in Theresienstadt, a Nazi transit camp in
Czechoslovakia, are among several arts projects to have benefited financially
from the main teachers' union this school session.
The one-act works received #1000 from the Educational Institute of Scotland
(EIS), which each year gives up to 0.5% of its income from members'
subscriptions to arts projects.
To qualify for assistance, projects must involve school pupils as participants
or have them as their target audience.
One of the operas, Brundibar, involves 40 central region pupils aged between
eight and 14. Other projects supported this session include:
q The Scottish Southern Counties Burns Association, which received #500 for the
forthcoming Burns for Bairns event involving Dumfries pupils;
q TAG Theatre Company in Glasgow, #900 to cover the cost of a teachers' pack
for the play Scottish Women Artists of the Twentieth Century;
q Inverness Festival Association, #1000 for non-competitive events for the
forthcoming festival such as the gala evening concert or classes in clarsach,
accordion, fiddle, and music making.
</TEXT>
