<DOCNO>GH951229-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP to raise case of ambulanceman who lost his job</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651426</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE case of an ambulanceman who lost his job on Christmas Day is to be raised
in Parliament.
Father-of-two Allan Bruce, 44, had been serving one of the most remote corners
of the Highlands from the depot at the fishing port of Kinlochbervie, in
north-west Sutherland.
His contract was terminated on December 25 but his MP, Mr Robert Maclennan, has
now had questions to the House of Commons accepted by speaker Betty Boothroyd.
The move comes as Mr Bruce prepares for an industrial tribunal, which has been
set for January 30.
Local GPs are also backing his fight to be reinstated. Dr Brian Fitzsimons
said: ``We have lost a very capable and efficient driver. There is no way we
will get anybody better. The whole thing is a disgrace.''
Mr Bruce has been employed by the Scottish Ambulance Service on a contract
basis, covering north-west Sutherland, since 1991. He has twice taken the
service to industrial tribunals in the past as he attempted to be made up to
employee level.
Mr John Drummond, a spokesman for the Scottish Ambulance Service, said: ``We
reserve the right to pick and choose the right people for the right job. Mr
Bruce did not meet the standard required. It is as simple as that.''
Mr Maclennan, Liberal Democrat MP for Caithness and Sutherland, said: ``I
regard this as a scandalous case. I have spoken to local doctors, who say Mr
Bruce is a dedicated and competent public servant. I will put forward the
strongest possible case for him to be reinstated to Scots Health Minister Lord
James Douglas-Hamilton.''
Mr Bruce, his wife, Cathy, and their two children, Donna, 16, and Ewan, 12, now
face an uncertain future.
The ambulance service in the more remote parts of the Highlands was usually
provided by self-employed contractors. More recently, the Scottish Ambulance
Service has been employing staff men to do the job.
</TEXT>
