<HEADLINE>`Lost' stories turn up in Swiss cellar</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JACK WEBSTER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651427</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SEARCH in the cellar of Alistair MacLean's mansion on the shores of Lake
Geneva has produced three short stories that were unknown to anyone but the
author - and a complete screenplay that could yet take its place alongside The
Guns Of Navarone and Where Eagles Dare.
The discovery was made by MacLean's friend and literary executor, Mr David
Bishop, of London lawyers Baileys Shaw and Gillett, when he went to visit the
late author's first wife, Gisela, who has continued to live in the magnificent
Villa Murat since they were divorced in 1972.
The short stories date back to the 1950s, when MacLean was a young
schoolteacher at Gallowflat School in Rutherglen. It was in 1954 that he first
burst into print as the winner of The Glasgow Herald short-story competition,
chosen from nearly 1000 entries.
His story was seen by Mr Ian Chapman of Collins the publisher, who persuaded
him to try his hand at a novel. A reluctant MacLean finally delivered a
manuscript, which turned out to be HMS Ulysses, destined to sell 250,000
hardback copies within six months and become one of the best-selling books of
all time.
``Around that period, Alistair had been reeling off short stories,'' Mr Bishop
told me. ``But with the excitement of the Herald prize - and his immediate
success as a world-class novelist - he obviously forgot about the other short
stories.
``I knew nothing about them. My main reason for going to his old home at the
village of Celigny, overlooking the lake, was to see if I could find the
missing screenplay, which was written by MacLean in 1968 and taken up as an
option by Elliott Kastner, the film producer of Where Eagles Dare and When
Eight Bells Toll.
``It had been lost in Kastner's office, apparently thrown out by a secretary
when they were moving premises. I thought there must be another copy somewhere.
``Some years ago, I asked Gisela MacLean if she could search the house but she
had no success. Convinced there must be a copy there, I then decided to go to
Geneva, where she agreed that I could make my own search.
``MacLean's old papers had been flung into the rather damp, evil-smelling
cellar, most of them untouched since Alistair and Gisela arrived from Britain
in 1969. With MacLean's son Alistair, I began to search the cellar, came across
proofs of most of his novels - and then found those unknown short stories.''
The good news for readers of The Herald is that we have decided to take this
literary romance full circle. Back where Alistair MacLean's phenomenal career
started nearly 42 years ago - the pages of the Weekend section - we are
publishing two of the new-found stories tomorrow and next Saturday.
The Black Storm and The Good Samaritan clearly belong to the 1950s, all the
more interesting as a study of the early efforts of a quiet schoolmaster who
would break out of the Scottish classroom to earn #20m between 1955 and his
death in 1987, when he was 64.
To complete the fruitful visit to Switzerland, Mr Bishop did indeed find the
missing screenplay of The Swashbuckler, which owed its origins to hell-raising
Hollywood producer Kastner, who played a vital part in MacLean's success in
films.
For it was Kastner who, in the mid-sixties, persuaded the Scottish author to
try writing a screenplay before turning the film into a novel. He even gave him
the idea for the first one, Where Eagles Dare, though literary purists reckoned
that this reversal of the process led to a deterioration in MacLean's novels.
Kastner nevertheless produced When Eight Bells Toll (introducing Anthony
Hopkins in his first major film) and commissioned MacLean to write two old-time
screenplays - Breakheart Pass, which became a major movie with Charles Bronson,
and the pirate story, which was titled The Swashbuckler before it was
carelessly thrown out.
Now American film agents are taking a look at this piece of unexpected MacLean
writing to see if it fits alongside his other major movie successes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000035</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000035</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Anonymous woman may know who killed Mhairi `Please contact us' urges detective</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651428</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MOTHER stricken by conscience may hold a vital clue to the identity of the
killer of Kilmarnock schoolgirl Mhairi Julyan.
The detective leading the murder inquiry yesterday disclosed that a letter,
apparently written by a concerned mother, had been received by the Julyan
family at their home in the town's Samson Avenue.
Detective Chief Inspector Bob Lauder said the letter had been posted in the
Kilmarnock area earlier this week and had been received by Mhairi's parents on
Wednesday morning.
He declined to discuss the contents of the anonymous letter in detail but said
there were ``very clear indications'' that the letter came from a concerned
mother who had important information about the identity of the killer.
Mr Lauder added: ``It is vital that the author of this letter gets in touch
with me at the incident room as soon as possible in order that I can discuss
the contents of the letter with her.
``I assure this person that the information will be treated in the strictest
confidence and I will be happy to meet her anywhere at any time to have a
discussion about what she has written and what she knows.
``My message to the woman who wrote this letter is clear - it is important that
the person who carried out this awful crime is dealt with and while I know it
is a major hurdle, you must force yourself to get over it and contact us at
once . . . it will give you peace of mind as well as helping the Julyan family
and the entire community to come to terms with the loss of a young girl.
``It will not bring her back but I believe it will help if we can bring this
inquiry to a conclusion.''
Meantime, the murder squad, boosted by detectives from every division of
Strathclyde as well as the Major Crime Resource Unit, will assess the
information contained in the letter and follow up other important leads.
Mr Lauder conceded there was a possibility the letter was not genuine and
added: ``If that is the case, it would be a quite dreadful hoax to perpetrate
on a grieving family.''
He said it was unusual for such a communication to be received by the victim's
family, although sympathy cards and messages of support had come from the
immediate area and beyond.
Mr Lauder said another possible sighting of Mhairi - this time at the junction
of London Road and Nursery Avenue - on the evening of December 16 had been
reported.
He again urged anyone with the slightest piece of information to get in touch.
``No-one should think they are cluttering up the inquiry by making a call.
Their small piece of information could be vital.
``We are not going to go away. We are here until the person is found and the
inquiry closed.''
Mhairi, a fifth-year pupil at Kilmarnock Academy, disappeared on December 16
while on her way home from a pantomime at the Palace Theatre.
Her body was discovered in the Stagecoach bus depot in McKinlay Place, a few
hundred yards from her home, the next afternoon.
q A father yesterday made an emotional appeal for the safe return of his
teenage daughter who disappeared after a Christmas Eve disco.
Delivery driver Robert Smith, 49, pleaded for news of his daughter Louise, 18,
at a police news conference.
In a personal message, he said: ``Louise, we all love you. Please get in touch
by any means. We want you back.''
She disappeared early onChristmas morning following the disco at Spirals
nightclub in the heart of Yate, near Bristol.
Police are investigating the possibility that she was sighted shortly after 2am
in the passenger seat of a blue Ford Escort driven by a female friend called
Emma. Police are still trying to trace the friend and the car.
</TEXT>
