<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mideast talks find positive reception</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651429</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jerusalem, Thursday.  ISRAEL reported a ``positive atmosphere'' at its first
talks with Syria in six months, saying that Syrian peacemakers appeared to be
freer to negotiate than before.
Despite a news blackout on the closed-door talks at a remote conference centre
an hour's drive from Washington, Israeli Cabinet Ministers were quick to
describe the atmosphere as ``truly good'', ``positive'', and ``business-like''.
``It's the feeling of our people that the Syrian delegation to the talks is
coming with a broader mandate than in similar talks in the past,'' said Yossi
Beilin, spokesman for Prime Minister Shimon Peres.
He said it was too soon to know whether the talks would lead to a breakthrough.
``What it's posssible to speak of now is a positive atmosphere, a feeling that
there is a mandate there for serious negotiations.''
Shortly before the talks started, Syria said it was optimistic about the
negotiations and hoped they would break a four-year impasse.
``We can't predict the results of the talks now, but we are optimistic,''
Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara told reporters in Damascus last night.
Peres said today that peace with Syria would open the door for the Jewish state
to end decades of hostility with the Arab world.
``If we achieve peace with Syria and Lebanon there is absolutely no reason for
a state of enmity, threat, or boycott to remain. I believe this is the
appropriate opportunity to put an end to 50 years of blood and hatred,'' Peres
told the London-based Al-Hayat newspaper.
A second round of talks in Maryland is scheduled next week and US Secretary of
State Warren Christopher will meet leaders in Israel and Syria next
month.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
