<DOCNO>GH951229-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Milestone for lottery brings new betting plea</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651430</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS sales of National Lottery tickets topped #5000m since being launched 13
months ago, bookmakers made a fresh plea for changes in the law to help them
fight for a bigger share of the gaming market.
Weekly jackpot ticket sales have reached #3700m, while sales of the nine
Instants scratch card games have totalled #1300m since the lottery started in
November 1994.
Camelot communications director David Rigg said: ``This is a fantastic
achievement, in just over a year, which demonstrates the huge appeal and
popularity of the lottery.''
It has become so much part of the daily lives of a vast number of Britons that
it is having an impact on our language.
More than 292 million people have won a total of #2300m on the lottery and
#1346m has been raised for the five good causes.
The Treasury has taken #600m in tax and #250m has been paid in commission to
the 28,000 retailers who sell the tickets.
Camelot hopes to boost its lottery success with the launch of a 10th Instants
scratch card today.
The Yellow Instants, with a top prize of #50,000, follow on from the blue, red,
and green designs.
Since the launch of Instants games last March, 224 people have won the top
prize - and 32% have said they would blow their winnings on a dream holiday.
However, bookmakers are unhappy because the rising popularity of the lottery
has been accompanied by a downturn in the fortunes of the bookmaking industry.
Turnover has been hit heavily and although Chancellor Kenneth Clarke softened
the blow with a 1% reduction in betting duty in the Budget last month, William
Hill spokesman Graham Sharpe has reiterated the call for further concessions to
be made to enable the bookmaking industry to redress the balance.
``I have nothing against the National Lottery, and I am very glad it has been
such a success,'' he said, ``but what we want is for the Government to allow us
to compete on equal terms.
``While bookmakers have had to obey a set of tight regulations since being
permitted to open in 1961, the National Lottery has had the advantage of a
large number of concessions that have been denied to us, along with the pools
and bingo industries and casinos.
``The National Lottery has the advantage of radio and television advertising,
not to mention the draw on Saturday night. Now there are talks of a midweek
draw.
``At first, the Government tried to pretend that the Lottery was not gambling
and its age limit was put at 16. We believe the age limit should be 18 and,
although there have been problems with under-age players of the lottery, that
has not been a problem in betting shops, where the age limit is 18.
The concession made by the Chancellor in the Budget, though welcome, is
insufficient, argued Sharpe.
``We originally wanted a 2% cut in betting duty, to allow us to regain some of
the balance. In 1995, we have taken 20 million fewer betting slips than we did
in 1994 and that is just William Hill. It is a very serious matter for the long
term.
``The National Lottery will always be a success, so why should Camelot be
concerned just because we are permitted to compete on equal terms?''
Mr Tom Kelly, chairman of the Betting Office Licensees' Association, echoed Mr
Sharpe's call for a further reduction in betting duty: ``This is a serious
situation which will get worse before it stabilises. The National Lottery has
changed the gambling culture in this country.''
It has also changed the language. New words associated with the lottery and
those which have new meanings derived from it are to be included in new
editions of dictionaries.
Chambers and the other two main dictionary publishers, The Oxford English and
Collins, have said their next full editions will contain ``lotteryisms'' such
as ``instant'', ``Oflot'' and ``rollover''.
q DUMBARTON District Council has scooped #220,000 from the Sports Lottery Fund
to redevelop Posties Park at Levengrove.
The red blaes track will be converted into a six-lane synthetic layout with a
grassed central area for field events.
The council also picked up #80,000 from the National Lottery, which will help
with the refurbishment of the town's Denny Civic Theatre. The money will be
used to upgrade the foyer area with the creation of a new box office and bar.
</TEXT>
