<DOCNO>GH951229-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Minister moves to cut planning delays</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN MacCALMAN Municipal Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651431</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOUGH measures to reduce delays in processing planning applications were
announced yesterday by Mr George Kynoch, Scottish Local Government Minister.
The changes, detailed in a review of the town and country planning system,
include performance targets along with tighter timetables for dealing with
planning applications and appeals.
\Performance targets will cover the progress of structure plan reviews,
national guidance and advice, decisions on individual cases as well as the work
of the Scottish Office Inquiry Reporters' Unit.
According to the Scottish Office, good progress has been made in this area and
work will continue towards meeting the target of 28 weeks for public local
inquiry cases by the end of 1996.
Once met, it is intended to tighten further the target for written submission
cases to 26 weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Searches draw a blank on missing French student</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651432</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROADSIDE searches have failed to yield any clues in the search for missing
French student Celine Figard.
Police from three counties yesterday spent a second fruitless day combing halts
where heavy goods vehicles might stop - but Celine's father Bernard has refused
to give up hope of finding his daughter alive.
The 19-year-old accountancy student was last seen on Tuesday, December 19, at
the Chieveley Service Station on the junction of the M4 and A34 near Newbury,
Berkshire.
Celine, who was travelling to Fordingbridge, Hampshire, to spend Christmas with
her cousin, was given a lift in a white Mercedes truck which was pulling a
refrigerated trailer.
She has not been seen since and police now fear she has been murdered.
Police are are still trying to trace the driver who, despite appeals, has
failed to contact them.
The latest search has concentrated on routes leading from the service area to
Salisbury.
Hundreds of calls have been taken at the police incident room in Southampton
since an emotional plea for help on Tuesday by Mr Figard, a 44-year-old farmer.
He said yesterday: ``I can never give up hope. If the lorry driver would only
come forward, it is possible she may be found.''
Celine had been given a lift from her home in the small village of
Ferrieres-Les-Scey, 200 miles south-east of Paris, to Folkestone by a lorry
driver friend of her family. He put her in the care of another French driver
who took her to the Chieveley service area.
A new likeness of the Mercedes driver was issued yesterday. It shows him
without the previously described ``chin strap'' beard. The move came after the
second French driver who gave Celine a lift said he may actually have been
clean shaven.
Last night, police said the total number of calls offering information had
risen to more than 1250 but there were still no clues to Celine's whereabouts.
A spokesman said there had been more calls than they could cope with and added:
``We are keeping an open mind on our enquiries at the moment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>How a sick `baby' bucked up in hospital</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651433</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
West Plains, Thursday
RUSS COCHRAN was not telling the whole truth when he told hospital workers in
West Plains, Missouri, that the tightly wrapped bundle in his arms was a
seriously ill baby.
When doctors at Ozarks Medical Centre peeled back the blankets, they discovered
Buck, Cochran's two-month-old pet chimpanzee.
However Buck was critically ill, and the medical staff decided to help him.
``This definitely is not our policy, treating animals,'' said hospital
spokeswoman Cathy Stahl. ``It was an isolated incident and a judgment call.''
Buck, who had developed breathing problems after milk got into his lungs when
he was being fed, was given oxgen and a chest X-ray.
Later he was being cared for in St Louis by a vet and a paediatrician.
Cochran, who had taken the chimp to hospital after his condition worsened while
waiting for a vet, said: ``He's healthy. He's strong.''-AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Winter worst enemy of Nato troops</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KURT SCHORK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651434</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE first week of Nato's Bosnia mission ended on a high note today after
warring parties pulled back from Sarajevo front-line flashpoints on time.
However the Alliance encountered a setback from ``General Winter'' as rain and
melting snow threatened to slow deployment of the main body of peace troops,
eventually to number 60,000.
Serb and Muslim-led government forces withdrew from all 40 designated hot spots
on the Sarajevo front-line by a deadline of midnight yesterday, seen as a first
test of their willingness to honour the Dayton peace agreement.
Nato today confirmed that both sides had complied 100% with the pull-back in
the Bosnian capital.
Diplomats cautioned against early euphoria, however, saying other forthcoming
deadlines, particularly one for the return of Serb-held suburbs of Sarajevo to
government rule within 90 days, could be testing for both sides.
``We are in early days, it is a honeymoon period,'' said the commander of Nato
ground forces, Lieutenant General Sir Michael Walker.
President Bill Clinton suspended US sanctions against Serbia and Montenegro,
but warned that they could be re-imposed if terms of the Bosnian peace accord
were violated.
Across the Bosnian border in Croatia, floods today burst into a camp for US
troops building a pontoon bridge to bring in thousands of their compatriots, in
a second weather-related blow to the mission in 24 hours.
Yesterday French helicopters had to rescue scores of Foreign Legionnaires when
floods swept through their tented camp near the divided city of Mostar in south
Bosnia.
US officials vowed to complete the bridge near the Croatian town of Zupanja, a
key link in a corridor bringing 20,000 American troops from rear bases in
Germany to their planned headquarters at Tuzla, north-east Bosnia.
However further delays looked likely after floods swept into a riverside camp
at Zupanja.
``The water broke through the levee (banks) and flooded the camp. The camp was
evacuated overnight. Everybody got out safely,'' Colonel Timothy Lamb told
reporters.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Woman's body found in woods</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651435</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Woman's body
found in woods
THE body of a young woman who disappeared at about the same time as her
estranged husband was found dead in a fume-filled car - with a note suggesting
he had harmed her - has been found in woods, say police.
Detectives believe the body to be that of 26-year-old Jacqueline Phillips, who
disappeared from her home in Doncaster, Yorkshire, in August.
Plea bargain
THIEVES who took George Formby fan David Edelston's ukuleles have made sure he
got them back after his public plea, by phoning and telling him they were in a
rubbish skip near his Leeds home. He found the #1000 instruments undamaged.
Widow's post
THE widow of Falklands VC hero Colonel ``H'' Jones, Mrs Sara Jones, is to head
the Royal British Legion's Poppy Factory.
Red tape offer
THE Government yesterday invited voters to tell it which bits of official red
tape they would like to see scrapped in 1996 - the year for tackling burdens on
small business.
Robber jailed
AN Edinburgh man was jailed for 18 months at the city's sheriff court yesterday
when he admitted a knifepoint robbery, assaulting a policeman, and carrying an
offensive weapon. David Pentland, 23, of Viewcraig Gardens, Edinburgh, had been
released from psychiatric hospital two days before the robbery.
Net awards
STORNOWAY skipper Calum Campbell of the Northern Star won two out of the four
annual awards at the town's fisherman's ball. Other winners were Donald
Morrison of the Scalpay boat Agate, and Stornoway's D C MacLeod of the Sharon
Rose.
Knife attack
KNIFE attacker Raymond Boyd, of Methven, in Perthshire, has been sent to the
High Court for sentence following his assault on a fellow body-builder who,
Boyd had been told, had been seeing his girlfriend.
Top names
JACK and Jessica were the most popular names for babies born in 1995. Both
names rose from third place in 1994 to claim top spots in the boys' and girls'
lists as last year's favourites Thomas and Rebecca slipped back to third.
Hunt for girl
A 16-year-old girl who has been missing for 19 days from her home in Edinburgh
was being sought by police last night. Lisa Blyth was last seen at her home in
the Howdenhall area of the city in the early evening of December 9. Police have
appealed for information from anyone who knows of her whereabouts.
Village boost
FIFE'S former mining villages are getting a #1.5m facelift aimed at attracting
new business investment throughout Dunfermline and Kirkcaldy districts.
Poverty claim
THE number of children receiving free school meals has risen by more than 90%
in parts of England and Wales over the past five years, figures show today.
Labour said the figures were evidence that child poverty had made dramatic
inroads into the south in the 1990s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000043</DOCNO>
