<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>NHS and councils hit staffing problems</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ROY ROGERS, Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651437</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL health and local authority employers are experiencing increasing
difficulty in recruiting certain professional grades, according to the annual
public-sector labour market survey by Incomes Data Services.
The shortages have been particularly acute in certain sectors of the health
service, where the most common problem was the lack of sufficient
physiotherapists, occupational therapists, and psychologists. Specialist
qualified nursing staff were also in short supply in some parts.
Out of 76 NHS organisations (together employing 170,000), 62 said they had
difficulties recruiting and retaining certain types of staff.
This continues a sharply rising trend, evident over the past two years, which
respondents put down to:
q A continuing national shortfall of staff being trained;
q The spread of fixed-term contracts which mean the NHS is no longer seen as a
``job for life'';
q Improved economic services leading to a tighter labour market and increased
turnover.
A recent Institute of Personnel and Development survey showed that staff
turnover in NHS trusts stood at 19.1% compared to an average of 13.8%
throughout the rest of the public sector.
Of 56 councils, together employing about 400,000 staff, which took part in the
IDS survey, one third said they had problems of recruitment and retention of
certain groups compared with a quarter last year.
Recruitment problems were appearing in a wider number of occupational groups,
with a number of councils mentioning difficulties in filling low-paid part-time
posts, where previously problems had been confined to professional and
technical groups. Shortages occurred in groups as diverse as civil engineers,
cleaners, information technology specialists, cooks, solicitors, and gipsy site
staff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots a pale shade of green</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651438</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTS are the least concerned about the environment, while people in East
Anglia are the most worried, states a new survey.
More than one in five Scots were not even ``slightly concerned'' about the
environment and only 39% were either extremely or very concerned, according to
the survey from Friends of the Earth.
In contrast, people in East Anglia were the most worried about green matters,
with 52% being either extremely or very concerned and a further 42% being
slightly concerned. This meant only 6% were not worried at all.
For the purposes of the survey, Britain was divided into television company
areas. The survey showed that across England, Wales, and Scotland, 54% of
people were either extremely or very worried about the environment and a
further 34% were slightly concerned.
The survey also showed that 91% of people agreed that pollution from cars was a
very or fairly serious problem and three-quarters of the people questioned felt
that the Government should be responsibile for solving environmental problems,
with 63% feeling that it was not doing a lot to help.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000046</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Foulkes hits out at powerlink `farce'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LACHIE KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651439</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE #3m public inquiry into plans by ScottishPower to build an electricity link
between Scotland and Ireland was attacked last night as ``a complete farce''.
The criticism came from Mr George Foulkes, Labour MP for Carrick, Cumnock, and
Doon Valley, after he had read a 250-page draft report of the five-month-long
public inquiry held earlier this year.
Mr Foulkes said: ``The Scottish Office Reporter has swallowed the ScottishPower
case hook, line, and sinker. The so-called findings of fact and related
conclusions all point in one direction, and clearly indicate that the
application will be approved.''
He added: ``It is increasingly clear this inquiry has been a farce and a total
waste of time and money.''
If the plan gets the go-ahead from Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth it would
result in a 40-mile line of pylons cutting through some of the most picturesque
countryside in Scotland.
Mr Foulkes vowed: ``The fight will go on and we will be challenging the
conclusions we consider to be incorrect.
``Apart from that, this report has been overtaken by recent events around the
Beaufort's Dyke munitions dump.''
Mr Foulkes maintains that munitions which have been washed up on Scottish
beaches were disturbed by the laying of a gas pipeline between Scotland and
Ireland. The new electricity link is due to be laid about four miles from the
gas line.
Mr Foulkes said: ``We now know that the dangers from dumped munitions and
chemicals extend well beyond the permitted dumping zone in Beaufort's Dyke.
None of this was considered at the inquiry or at the parallel one held in
Northern Ireland. This is something that will now have to be seriously
considered.''
</TEXT>
