<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Princess shakes off paparazzi in Barbuda triangle</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651440</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Princess of Wales was relaxing last night in the Caribbean but precisely
where was the unanswered question.
The princess, who will no doubt ponder her impending divorce while unwinding in
the sunshine, was thought to be staying at the K Club hotel on Barbuda, near
Antigua, in the West Indies.
However, staff at the #4000-a-week holiday complex said the princess was not a
guest.
They also insisted other known guests at the hotel were staying elsewhere,
perhaps at Coco Point, another hideaway club-hotel on the island, or at a
private villa.
It seemed, according to the K Club, the princess had disappeared in a ``Barbuda
triangle''.
A holidaymaker staying in one of the K Club's 28 cottages, the creation of
Italian fashion designer Krizia, can enjoy two miles of private, white sandy
beach under blue skies and temperatures rising to 90F.
The hotel, which takes a maximum of 89 guests, boasts that it aims ``to give
total bliss to just a few, a special few''.
There are two floodlit tennis courts, a nine-hole golf course, windsurfing,
snorkelling, water skiing, scuba diving, and fishing.
Cuisine is a mixture of French and Italian, with wines costing up to #230 a
bottle.
The princess ended her lonely Christmas at Kensington Palace to jet away to the
sun with personal assistant Victoria Mendham.
Meanwhile, the Prince of Wales, and sons Prince William, 13, and Prince Harry,
11, were at Sandringham, the Queen's Norfolk estate, where they have been
pheasant shooting.
They are due to leave for Klosters in the Swiss Alps on New Year's Day for a
skiing holiday.
As the princess flew via Antigua to Barbuda, new controversy erupted over her
husband's close friend Camilla Parker Bowles, with claims that she was now
determined to be Charles's wife and his official consort with the title Her
Royal Highness.
However the claims, reported in the Daily Express, were dismissed as ``fanciful
nonsense'' by sources close to the Prince of Wales.
</TEXT>
