<HEADLINE>Researcher accused of misleading patients</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651441</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MEDICAL researcher was accused yesterday of misleading elderly patients by
playing down the risks involved in experimental operations.
Dr Srimathi Murali was alleged to have ignored a plea from one of his
colleagues to spell out more clearly the dangers involved in a project designed
to prevent hip fractures in elderly women.
The criticism was levelled at Dr Murali on the final day of a fatal accident
inquiry into the death of 70-year-old Mrs Phyllis Moffitt.
The inquiry at Aberdeen Sheriff Court was told Mrs Moffitt died while
undergoing an experimental operation at the city's Woodend Hospital in August
last year.
A post-mortem examination revealed she had died of a heart attack after being
given a sedative to ease discomfort during the operation.
Solicitor Reg Christie, representing the dead woman's family, claimed potential
volunteers were given inaccurate and misleading statistics about the associated
risks.
An information sheet stated volunteers would be given only a local anaesthetic,
that the work would be of great benefit, and that the operations would not be
painful.
However, Mr Christie said, Mrs Moffitt had to be given a sedative because of
the pain she was suffering.
In his summing-up, he told Sheriff Peter Hamilton: ``Insufficient care was
taken by those conducting this research to see that the statistical information
about the risk factor was accurate.
``There may have been a desire to increase or enhance the rate of take-up from
those who received the sheet.''
He said research assistant Fiona French had spoken to Dr Murali about the
``inaccuracy of the sheet''.
``She had become increasingly concerned because she was having to recruit the
people and explain, and she felt she was misrepresenting the people,'' he said.
Mr Christie claimed Dr Murali responded by telling her no amendment would be
made to the information sheets.
He added: ``Dr Murali must have been perfectly, consciously aware that these
people were suffering pain and discomfort and he refused to make an alteration.
``That amounts to Dr Murali engaging in a deliberate misrepresentation to
people he was asking to volunteer and help with his research project.''
Mr Christie said that if the dangers had been spelt out to Mrs Moffitt, who had
a known heart condition, she might not have taken part in the experiment.
Dr Murali's agent, Mr Robert Leith, said his client had tried to make sure Mrs
Moffitt knew all the risks involved before the operation began.
``I would submit that Dr Murali did his best to ensure that Mrs Moffitt had
read all she had signed for,'' he said.
``He sat down with her and asked her if she had any questions. By the time she
was in the hospital, she had no illusions about what was involved.
``The tragedy is that Mrs Moffitt suffered from a serious and significant
defect which was virtually undetectable, certainly by any reasonable means.''
Mr Leith told Sheriff Hamilton that hip fractures were a major and growing
problem which were costly to treat and caused suffering.
He asked the sheriff not to issue a judgment which would cause difficulties for
projects which necessarily involved the participation of elderly people.
The sheriff will issue his determination in due course.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
