<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pleasure sailors keep the RNLI busy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651442</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Royal National Lifeboat Institution said yesterday that 1995 had been its
busiest year yet.
Provisional data compiled from its stations across the UK showed that boats had
been launched on more than 6000 occasions, compared to about 5400 in 1994. The
number of people saved from probable death fell slightly, to about 1400.
In Scotland, where the RNLI operates 42 lifeboat stations, the number of
launches remained virtually unchanged, at slightly more than 700. The number of
lives saved was 141,compared to 193.
An analysis of the UK total showed that incidents involving all types of
pleasure craft accounted for 56% of call-outs, while fishing vessels prompted
only 12% of all responses.
However, an RNLI spokeswoman declined to criticise pleasure sailors for any
irresponsibility.
She said: ``Incidents can happen for a variety of reasons: sometimes people may
be ill-prepared, equipment can malfunction, or the weather deteriorates.
``But we are not in the business of criticising people. We do not question why
our boats are called out, we just do it.''
The spokeswoman said, however, that the RNLI was putting continued effort into
its sea safety initiative, launched this year in conjunction with the
Coastguard Agency, the Marine Safety Agency, the Royal Yachting Association,
and other maritime groups.
More than one million booklets of safety guidelines have already been
distributed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
