<HEADLINE>Country on the skids Kirsty Scott investigates how Scandinavian countries cope with Arctic conditions when sub-zero temperatures here cause chaos</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kirsty Scott</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<FLAG>Features</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651444</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT REACHED -24 in Helsinki yesterday, but the chances are you wouldn't have
found any power lines down, any trains delayed, any blue-skinned, gloveless
pedestrians stamping their ill-shod feet against the biting cold.
Where Britain is prone to collapsing under a welter of ``Big Freeze''
headlines, Scandinavia apparently takes sub-zero temperatures in its stride;
roads stay open, railways run on time, heads stay covered, and feet stay firmly
in warm boots.
``Of course, the Scandinavian countries experience this sort of climate every
year, therefore they are prepared to deal with it,'' says Alan Small, a
lecturer in geography and expert on Norway at Dundee University. ``They have
all the investment and equipment for clearing the roads and railways.
Meanwhile, we struggle with the occasional difficulty. We aren't really
prepared to cope with situations that occur once every 50 years or 100 years.''
In Norway and elsewhere, cold-weather contingencies include double or
triple-glazing as standard, robust and comprehensive heating systems,
compulsory winter tyres, powerful snow blowers, permanent car headlights and
appropriate clothing.
``They use the snow blowers on the railways as well,'' says Alan Small. ``And
the railways stay open. Maybe one or two roads are just allowed to close, some
of the mountain links they just write off for several months of the year.
``Also, people dress for the weather. That's one contrast with here which is
very marked. Here people don't seem to look at the temperature before they go
outside. Almost every Norwegian, however, has a thermometer and he looks at it
every day and sees that it's going to be -10 or -20, and he will have the
right kind of clothing on.''
Unlike many parts of Britain, remote areas of Norway are not always the first
to suffer when a cold snap sets in. Alan Small says they know they are liable
to be cut off for a spell in winter and will have stockpiled adequate supplies.
``The rural areas also have a very strong voice in parliament and they do much
better. For example, many of the mountain roads have been replaced with tunnels
which are much easier to keep open in the winter.''
Dr Thomas Munck, a Dane who teaches modern history at Glasgow University,
acknowledges that the Scandinavians are used to the Arctic conditions which
have caught us on the hop, but thinks the problem may go deeper.
``I suppose part of it is the usual question of investment in infrastructure.
The power supply system in Scotland is 40 to 50 years old and there has been a
lack of investment in infrastructure, at least until a few years ago. I'm not
suggesting that the Scandinavian countries are models of their kind but they
probably have a better infrastructure support because the assumption is that
the state provides a public transport system which is fully integrated and
regulated.
``In Denmark the trains don't freeze to the tracks; they don't get the wrong
kind of snow. Danish winters are much more severe on a regular basis and you
will not see what you are seeing now in Glasgow - roads that have not been
snow-ploughed as a matter of course. They have equipment ready and are
expecting that kind of weather.
``It's absurd that railway carriages should be frozen to the tracks. In
Copenhagen the commuter lines run at 10-minute intervals, and right through
winter. I can set my watch by the trains. You can predict to within one minute
when you will get to your station because everything always operates like
clockwork.''
A spokesman for the Automobile Association, meanwhile, insisted that it would
be wrong to look to Scandinavia for all the answers.
``We often think that on the continent, in Scandinavia, it is so much better,
but that's not necessarily true. Unless you have snow chains you can't get
about. The effect of snow and ice is that no matter how good a system you have,
if you have huge ice crystals hanging off your tram lines they're not going to
be able to run.
``We have found that when you look at the Alpine regions of Europe in terms of
snow fall when they have a blizzard there is chaos for the first 24 hours just
as there is here and it takes a while to adjust.''
However, those with experience of both cultures and climates say there is no
doubt that the Scandinavians do it better.
``They are just so much more geared up for it,'' said one Scottish businessman
who travels frequently in Finland, Sweden and Norway. ``They dress for it, they
drive for it, they build their homes for it, they plan for it. But above all
else they enjoy it. They go in for saunas in a big way, they have cross-country
skiing. They like getting out into it. They don't just sit indoors and complain
about it like we do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
