<HEADLINE>Costly drive to find the answer in the battle of the sexes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651445</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MOTORING experts are spending #145,000 to solve one of the world's longest
standing arguments - are women or men the better drivers.
The Automobile Association has commissioned a three-year study by psychologists
at Reading University into the behaviour patterns of male and female motorists.
While more women take to the road as teenagers and company car drivers, the
motoring group wants to find out if the driving habits of the population are
changing.
According to the latest figures, men have more accidents per licence held,
while women have more crashes per mile driven.
The study is being funded by the AA's Foundation for Road Safety Research in
the hope of developing specific training schemes for men and women drivers.
Foundation manager Brian Langer said: ``The number of women holding driving
licences has doubled to more than 12 million, while their age profile has
changed dramatically.
``It used to be that women learned to drive after their family had grown up and
they were looking for a job.
``Nowadays, young teenage girls are just as keen to get behind the wheel as
boys.''
Mr Langer said statistics proved that the most accident-prone road users were
young men, but he said that, as more teenage girls began to drive and found
themselves involved in accidents, that figure was changing.
``There is anecdotal evidence that teenage girls are taking on the driving
characteristics of young men.
``They are more aggressive and reckless behind the wheel than other groups of
women drivers. We want to find out if this is true.''
Psychologists at Reading University will take to the road with men and women of
different ages to assess their driving habits.
They will look at how they respond to road hazards, which routes they favour,
what bad habits they have, how they overtake, and the speed at which they drive.
Professor Frank McKenna, of the university's psychology department, said: ``The
study will look not only at the differences in driving style between men and
women but also the influences that affect driver behaviour.''
Mr Kenneth Faircloth, chairman of the AA foundation, said: ``This research will
focus on the key differences between men and women drivers and will help
develop specific training programmes.''
q INCREASING numbers of ``road rage'' incidents and assaults have created fear
among women drivers in Scotland, according to the results of a survey released
yesterday.
The results showed that two-thirds of women lock their doors when driving due
to fear of attacks.
One woman in 10 is afraid of parking in the street, while three in five are
scared to park in multi-storeys. It also showed that one in five supports
women-only parking spaces.
The survey was carried out by Norwich Union as part of its annual Safe Car Park
Award Scheme, which highlights women's safety issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
