<RECORDNO>974651446</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EL PASO: A man has died in hospital after being shot in the head on Christmas
Day while driving on a Texas highway, allegedly by a 13-year-old boy in search
of more toys.
Ricardo Soto, of Fort Hancock, was charged as a juvenile with deadly conduct in
the death of 41-year-old Alberto Tarango.
The suspect's nine-year-old brother told investigators that his big brother
wanted to shoot out the tyres of a tractor-trailer he thought was carrying
video games. Instead the shot hit Tarango's nearby pick-up truck.
However a newspaper later reported that the younger boy disclaimed this.-AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Thousands  of skiers take to Scotland's icy slopes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651447</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SIX thousand skiers and snow-boarders enjoyed superb conditions on Scotland's
slopes yesterday.......the busiest day of the festive break so far.
Temperatures at the five Scots winter sports centres remained well below zero
all day, while clear blue skies, with hardly any winds, were the order of the
day.
Road access was clear to all centres. However, some resorts still do not have
as much snow as they would like and the White Corries Centre in Glencoe has yet
to open for the season.
The excellent skiing conditions will continue today and operators of all
resorts are keeping their fingers crossed that the settled but bitterly cold
spell of weather will continue beyond Hogmanay.
Not so the homeless and those working to keep them off the streets during
Scotland's big chill.
Shelter in Scotland director Ms Liz Nicholson said homeless people in the
larger cities had a wide range of hostels to choose from but those in smaller
towns were less fortunate.
In Glasgow, emergency accommodation is being provided through the city
council's Winter Watch Campaign between December and March. Under the scheme,
now in its third year, a number of places in hostels across the city are kept
for those who need accommodation in an emergency.
The campaign is run through the Hamish Allan Centre, a hostel in Centre Street,
which links to other hostels in the city to provide beds.
The centre itself has 24 emergency places available.
Operations director Brian O'Hara said: ``We have had 62 presentations since the
beginning of the campaign and we have been able to accommodate them all.''
He said Glasgow did not need an emergency shelter for when the weather turned
bad: ``We do not have a homelessness problem on the scale of that in London.''
Ms Margaret Stevenson, director of the Talbot Association, a hostel also
involved in the campaign, agreed. ``Glasgow is unique as it has an adequate
number of places,'' Ms Stevenson said. ``There tends to be a place for everyone
who needs and wants it. There are small groups of people that just won't come
in and we take food and blankets to them.''
Major Raymond Ward, team leader for the Glasgow Homeless for the Salvation
Army, said: ``At this time of year, we get people who would normally sleep
rough. There aren't actually a big proportion of these in Glasgow.''
However, he does believe a large emergency accommodation centre would help.
Meanwhile, it became clear yesterday that the major problems in the storm-hit
parts of northern Scotland have arisen in areas where the original power-lines,
dating back 40 years, are still in use.
Hydro-Electric are spending #20m a year on replacing old lines. About 1000
miles of overhead lines will be replaced each year out of a total of 30,000
miles of cables carried by electric poles in the whole of northern Scotland.
In the Western Isles alone the privatised company has spent #41m on line
renewals during the past five years. A Hydro-Electric spokesman said: ``We are
seeing a clear link between the age of the lines and problems with cuts in
power supply during the present emergency.''
He said almost all the areas which suffered serious power supply problems were
still served by the network erected when the Highlands and Islands were
electrified in the late 1940s and 1950s.
Earlier this year, the company was the only privatised electricity utility in
Britain to refuse an order from the Government's Electricity Regulator to cut
power costs by 10% over a three-year period.
Hydro-Electric's chairman Lord Wilson of Tillyorn argued then that his company
was a special case because of the very long mileage of rural supply lines which
needed to be replaced.
He won his case in an appeal to the Government's Monopolies and Merger
Commission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>DSS sleuths save #46m in Scotland</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CALUM MACDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651448</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BENEFIT fraud investigators in Scotland were praised yesterday for saving the
taxpayer more than #46m this year.
Social Security Fraud Minister Oliver Heald said almost #500m had been saved
across the UK this financial year, ahead of targets laid down by the Department
of Social Security.
In Scotland, the savings figures were: Glasgow and Paisley, #17m; north,
central, and west Scotland, #15m; and east Scotland, #14m.
Mr Heald said: ``I congratulate our investigators but there is more to be done
if we are to put an end to this fraud and I would ask them to redouble their
efforts in 1996.''
A Benefits Agency spokeswoman said social security fraud covered a wide range
of offences, from individuals misrepresenting facts about themselves, to
organised criminal groups involved in large-scale fraud.
The main areas affected are income support, housing benefit, unemployment
benefit, and incapacity benefit.
A number of innovative methods for detecting fraud have recently been
introduced by the agency, including the world's largest data matching system,
which allows computerised cross-checks to spot anomalies in claims.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000056</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000056</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SNP urges Irish-style tax breaks for film makers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALLAN LAING Entertainments Writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651449</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE introduction of Republic of Ireland-style tax breaks and the establishment
of a single organisation to oversee policy and strategy were among proposals
put forward yesterday by the SNP to boost Scotland's post-Braveheart film
industry.
The plans, which will be contained in a consultation document to be published
in the new year, have been formulated after discussions with the country's
major film organisations and leading industry figures.
Ms Roseanna Cunningham, the SNP's parliamentary spokesperson on film, said:
``Future success depends on a sustainable level of domestic production that
will result in regular success for low and medium-budget films and the
attraction of international films to be shot in Scotland. Our consultations
have led us to propose two essential first steps.
``The first is the introduction by Government of tax breaks for production,
which must be modelled on the highly successful `Section 35' Irish scheme.''
Film investment from private sources, which Ms Cunningham also regarded as
vital, would not be forthcoming to any significant degree unless these tax
breaks were in place.
In the Republic, as a means of encouraging new work, a film company is allowed
to write off tax for new investment. To qualify, it has to prove that the
project is worthwhile, that a proportion of the budget will be spent on
training, and that the film will employ an Irish crew.
The policy has met with startling success. At present, there are 80 movie
projects in development in Ireland. In Scotland, there are 20. The tax breaks
were in part responsible for Mel Gibson's decision to move filming from
Scotland to Ireland for the huge battle scenes in Braveheart.
Though the eventual tax advantages did little more than cover the costs of
moving location, Gibson admitted that the Irish had been enormously helpful,
providing thousands of extras from the ranks of the Irish army and around 600
horses. It is this climate of assistance, as much as the tax breaks, which the
SNP wants to create in Scotland.
To this end, the Nationalists' chief executive, Mr Mike Russell, disclosed that
the second essential step would be the establishment of Scottish Screen, a
federated organisation which would bring together existing bodies such as the
Scottish Film Council, the Scottish Film Production Fund, Scottish Screen
Locations, and the Scottish Broadcasting and Film Training Trust. It would be a
``one-stop shop'' for film-makers.
It would also include a new department, responsible for marketing and
distributing Scottish films at home and - more importantly - abroad.
Further down the line, the party also proposed the establishment of a Scottish
Film School and the creation of a major sound stage for film and television
production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000057</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Maximum fine levied for `a catalogue of neglect' Solicitor to pay #10,000 penalty</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE McKAIN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651450</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LAWYER has been fined the maximum #10,000 by the Scottish Solicitors
Discipline Tribunal for professional misconduct.
The fine on 55-year-old Stranraer solicitor Andrew Murray for ``a catalogue of
neglect and delay'' follows an #8000 penalty imposed on him by the tribunal in
February 1994 for similar failures.
This time the tribunal, which gave serious consideration to striking Mr Murray
off the roll of practising solicitors, has also ruled that, for the next 10
years, he will be limited to practising as a qualified assistant.
In a written judgment, the the tribunal stated that Mr Murray had been a
solicitor since 1966 and practised on his own under the name of Hunter and
Murray at Lewis Street, Stranraer, and Victoria Street, Newton Stewart.
It found him guilty of ``unconscionable delay'' in carrying through the
administration of four estates, failure to respond to reasonable inquiries by
the Bank of Scotland in connection with a trust, failure to respond to
inquiries by the Law Society, and misleading the society by informing it that
an inventory had been signed when it had not.
Mr Murray failed over a period of more than three and a half years to respond
to reasonable inquiries by the Bank of Scotland.
He was also found guilty of failure to comply with the solicitors' accounts
rules.
In January 1989, he paid #12,500 to a former client in compensation for
mistakes in a conveyancing transaction and withdrew a cheque for that amount
from a trust fund.
This created a shortage on his client account, in breach of the accounts rules.
The tribunal found that in acquiring a hotel on behalf of a client, Mr Murray
had overlooked the fact that the title to part of the property was on a 99-year
lease. Subsequently, #12,500 had to be paid to acquire a feudal title.
Mr Murray had accepted responsibility for the error and the compensation of
#12,500 represented his personal liability.
However, Mr Murray ``regrettably'' withdrew that amount on a cheque from a
trust he was administering.
In due course, he received a cheque for #10,500 from the solicitors'
professional indemnity insurance policy and credited it to the trust.
Nevertheless, the outstanding balance of #2000 created a succession of
shortages in his client account.
In the case of three other estates, the tribunal decided that unconscionable
delay on Mr Murray's part had not been established, nor had it been established
that interim fees charged on two of them were excessive.
Summing up the case, the tribunal stated: ``Mr Murray had previously been
before this tribunal on February 16, 1994, in relation to a number of similar
matters, and on that occasion he was censured and fined #8000.
``The present findings of this tribunal demonstrate a further catalogue of
neglect and delay.
``Additionally, the tribunal takes a most serious view of Mr Murray's actings
in withdrawing monies from an ongoing trust to meet a personal liability.
``It is clear from the circumstances of this complaint that he cannot be
permitted to continue in practice and, indeed, serious consideration was given
to suspending him or striking his name from the roll.
``However, having regard to his lengthy period of service to the profession,
the tribunal marginally draws short of making such an order.
``Nevertheless, it is appropriate that the tribunal should stigmatise Mr
Murray's overall conduct in a significant manner and it is with these
considerations that the maximum fine has been imposed.
``As it is not appropriate that Mr Murray should continue in practice as a
principal, a restriction has been placed on his practising certificate for a
period of 10 years.''
The tribunal also ordered that publicity should be given to its decision.
</TEXT>
