<DOCNO>GH951229-000058</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000058</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stadium plan hit by new delay</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651451</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A PLAN to build a #3m stadium for Clydebank Football Club has received another
setback.
Clydebank District Council's planning committee has decided to continue the bid
to sell Kilbowie to English company Vico, a property developer - which means
another month's delay.
Planning convener Jim Doherty said: ``We have decided to seek a valuation of
the site involved because of a difference of opinion in the value.''
The council, which owns part of the site involved, may not sell public land
below the valuation.
The club needs the money from the sale of Kilbowie to push ahead with
developing the 8000-seat stadium on a 15-acre site just off Great Western
Boulevard, near Drumchapel.
The planning application submitted by Vico involves the construction of four
retail outlets.
It is likely that the stadium will be named after former Clydebank star Davie
Cooper, who died after a brain haemorrhage.
</TEXT>
