<DOCNO>GH951229-000060</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000060</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trigger-happy Texans warned against John Wayne syndrome</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JEFF FRANKS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651453</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TEXAS returns to its Wild West roots on Monday when a law goes into effect
allowing citizens to carry concealed weapons for the first time in 125 years.
Opponents fear the law will unleash more violence on the streets. Proponents
say it will enable law-abiding Texans to defend themselves in an increasingly
dangerous society.
``All I want to do is put innocent people, those who are potential victims, in
a position of being able to protect themselves,'' said Democratic state
Representative Ron Wilson, who represents an inner-city Houston neighbourhood
and was one of the sponsors of the new law.
Sherri Deatherage-Green, spokeswoman for the Texas Department of Public Safety,
said 171,000 people had requested permit applications and 35,000 had applied.
Only 1200 had been approved so far, but that number will grow in coming weeks.
The law requires citizens to take a 15-hour gun-handling course and pass
background checks to show if they have a criminal past or a history of mental
illness. Instructors, who began offering the course in September, said most
customers were elderly people concerned about personal safety.
Florida has had a similar state law since 1987. According to Alan Thompson, a
police officer and doctoral student in the criminal justice department at Sam
Houston State University in Huntsville, Texas, only about 1.5% of Florida's 14
million residents have obtained a permit and the effects, either positive or
negative, have been hard to measure.
``The numbers are so small it's difficult to interpret what's happened there,''
he said.
A survey of Texas police officers found that most do not welcome the new law
because of concerns about their own safety and a feeling that it will put more
guns on the streets with little or no deterrent effect on crime.
In 1871, the Texas Legislature, tired of Wild West gunslingers' violence,
outlawed the carrying of concealed weapons. However it overturned the ban last
spring with a Bill quickly signed into law by the state governor then,
Republican George Bush.
The law has been diluted by a rash of local government decisions forbidding
guns in everything from public parks to city buses. The state Department of
Public Safety, in charge of administering the law, will forbid guns in its own
buildings and has ordered its officers to ask all drivers pulled over for
traffic violations if they have a permit and are carrying arms.
As January 1 approaches, many Texans are wondering how the gun law will affect
their everyday lives.
``Do you still shoot someone the finger if you're in your car and they cut in
front of you? My daughter has warned me to keep my hands on the steering
wheel,'' said a Houston editor who frequently admonishes bad drivers with an
obscene gesture.
Thompson cautioned gun holders not to get too carried away with their new-found
power. ``It's like a new police officer who gets a gun and suddenly feels 10ft
tall and bulletproof - what is commonly referred to as the `John Wayne
syndrome'.''
Thompson advised: ``Be reasonable and understand that no situation is without
alternatives . . . familiarise yourself with the limits of deadly
force.''-Reuter.
</TEXT>
