<DOCNO>GH951229-000061</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000061</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>US buy-out rumours over Devonport Final Trident secret may go in sell-off</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN BRUCE Defence Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651454</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government could be handing its last major military secret to the United
States on a platter if the #5000m Trident submarine refit deal goes ahead at
Devonport.
Despite an exchange of strategic intelligence unparalleled between any of the
other Western nations, Britain has always kept details of its
Rolls-Royce-designed power plant for nuclear submarines from even its closest
ally.
No US naval officer is allowed near the reactor compartment on any of the Royal
Navy's current 16 strategic or hunter-killer boats and the specifications for
the compact and efficient PWR2 nuclear steam-raising plant developed by RR's
Industrial Power Group remain classified.
However, the current Devonport Management Ltd, the consortium operating the
Plymouth yard on behalf of the Defence Ministry, includes the British
subsidiary of Brown and Root, part of the American Halliburton International
Corporation.
There are now unconfirmed rumours that Brown and Root may be about to bid for
outright ownership of the yard under Government plans to privatise both
Devonport and its Scottish rival at Rosyth.
The first Trident submarine, the 16,000-ton HMS Vanguard, is due for refit and
replacement of its nuclear fuel rods in the year 2000.
If a US-owned company takes charge of the operation, it would be naive to think
that the Pentagon and its Defence Intelligence Agency offshoot would hesitate
to take advantage of technology which British sources say is more advanced than
the reactors fitted to the US Navy's 14-strong fleet of Ohio-class Trident
boats.
As reported exclusively in The Herald last April, Devonport is currently unable
to obtain a safety licence from the independent Nuclear Installations
Inspectorate because of the potentially unstable nature of the limestone base
on which it is built.
Reinforcing former battleship docks at the site to meet the strict safety
regulations could cost anything between #500m and #700m and would make
Devonport's winning bid for the lucrative Trident work a commercial nonsense
and a political embarrassment for the Government.
There is also the question of the safety aspects of the yard's application for
an expansion of the nuclear refitting docks to within yards of a
densely-populated area of Plymouth.
The Government was understood to have been ready to make a compromise
announcement on the issue just before Parliament rose last week. The options
available included having the missile submarines refuelled at Rosyth and
refitted at Devonport, or a complete U-turn to reassess the financial aspects
of the contract and its re-assignment to the Fife yard.
There is a widely-held belief that the original bids were assessed more on the
fact that the Conservatives have four marginal Parliamentary seats in the West
Country than on commercial viability.
It is also understood that consideration was given to approaching the US Navy's
Trident boat refitting yard at Puget Sound in Washington State to carry out the
work to avoid having to make a politically-damaging choice in the UK. This
option was discarded in the face of naval objections.
The Cabinet is now hoping that it can delay a decision until the issue of
outright sale of the sites can be addressed in the New Year, despite pressure
from both management teams and unions representing workforces concerned about
their long-term future.
A Defence Ministry spokeswoman said last night: ``There are no new moves on the
refit plans. As far as the design and security of the Royal Navy's reactors is
concerned, it is MoD policy not to discuss nuclear issues in detail.''
An industry source said: ``The Americans gave the UK its first submarine
reactor, designed by Westinghouse, back in the 1960s. It was a gift aimed at
bringing the Royal Navy into the Cold War to tip the scales against a very
powerful Soviet fleet at that time. It went into HMS Dreadnought.
``Since then, there has been almost no reactor co-operation technologically.
The US has gone its own way and the UK has pursued a policy of improvement in
efficiency and reduction in size. The Rolls-Royce design is perhaps the UK's
last great secret.
``The Americans have opted for long-life cores in their reactors, which are
larger, which means longer intervals between replacement of fuel rods. They do
bring their subs back in for maintenance, however, at King's Bay in Georgia and
Brenerton in Washington State at regular intervals.
``This involves general maintenance and upgrading of sensor and weapons
systems. It has nothing to do with the reactor, which can be handled only at
Puget Sound.''
Rosyth, which has handled the bulk of the UK's nuclear refits over the last 25
years, was supposed to cease nuclear work in 1997. Because of Devonport's
upgrading and safety problems, this has now been extended.
</TEXT>
