<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000063</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000063</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Health trust suspends consultant for elderly</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN MacDERMID Medical Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651456</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A CONSULTANT involved with the care of elderly patients has been suspended by
his NHS trust employers.
Dr Kenneth McAlpine is believed to have been involved in disagreements with
colleagues. Now he has been told not to come to work pending an inquiry by
Renfrewshire Healthcare Trust.
Although he works mainly at Royal Alexandra Hospital, Paisley, Dr McAlpine is
employed by the Healthcare Trust, which provides long-stay elderly and
psychiatric services in the area.
At his home in Kilmacolm yesterday, Dr McAlpine refused to confirm or deny his
suspension.
``I have no comment to make. I have no wish to see anything published,'' he
said.
A hospital colleague said Dr McAlpine had been at odds in the past with other
geriatricians.
The chairman of the trust, Dr John Moffat, said: ``There is a matter of concern
which we are looking into and, as is common practice in the NHS, he has been
told: `Please stay at home meantime.' The suspension is not a disciplinary
matter.
``As the person who has to receive whatever report emerges from this, I cannot
say too much but I gather this is not over something that patients or relatives
need be alarmed about. It is more to do with internal affairs than with
anything directly affecting patients.''
Dr McAlpine is a graduate of St Andrews University and previously worked in
geriatric medicine at Glasgow Royal Infirmary and Lightburn Hospital.
He was involved in controversy earlier this year as joint author of a review
which led to sweeping changes at East Park Home and School for infirm children
in Glasgow.
The changes included the dismissal of the matron, Mrs Eleanor McCreadie, and -
in effect - her replacement with administrator Mrs May Henderson, a divorcee
who was involved in a relationship with Dr McAlpine.
</TEXT>
