<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MacLean manuscripts are found in a cellar</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW MULLINS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651457</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EIGHT years after Alistair MacLean's death, three new short stories and a
missing screenplay have been discovered in his mansion by Lake Geneva.
Villa Murat is still the home of the writer's first wife - they divorced in
1972 - and the manuscripts are thought to have been lying in the corner of the
house's damp cellar since then.
Mr David Bishop, the author's friend and executor, knew of the screenplay, The
Swashbuckler, when he began the search together with Mr Alistair MacLean Jr.
The three stories were a complete surprise. Two of them, The Black Storm and
The Good Samaritan, will appear in this paper tomorrow.
It is fitting that they should: it was winning The Herald's 1954 short-story
competition that launched a 37-year career that earned MacLean #20m.
The excitement of his prize and his propulsion to best-selling author - his
first book, HMS Ulysses, sold 250,000 hardback copies in its first six months -
meant the stories were forgotten. They were written while MacLean was still a
school teacher.
The screenplay, a pirate adventure, was written in 1968 and a copy had once
been owned by Elliot Kastner, the hell-raising Hollywood producer who had an
enormous influence on MacLean's writing. It was Kastner who convinced MacLean
to write the screenplay of a story before the novel, a technique that critics
felt harmed the quality of the books.
The screenplay is currently being examined by American producers to see if it
could stand alongside the other films written by MacLean.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>War of words on park plan</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES FREEMAN Home Affairs Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651458</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BEN Lomond and the Rowardennan Estate on its flanks is to become a national
park dedicated to the memory of those who served the country in the Second
World War, Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth announced yesterday.
In his New Year message to Scotland, Mr Forsyth said the park will be based on
conservation principles ``giving priority to landscape, nature conservation,
and quiet recreation''.
Plans for the area, which belongs to Forest Enterprise and the National Trust
for Scotland, will include a project for increasing the area of native woodland.
The second major plank in his New Year message was that leaders of the other
major political parties in Scotland are to join him in a Scotland Against Drugs
campaign.
Both initiatives, however, attracted immediate criticism.
Mr George Robertson, Labour's Shadow Scottish Secretary, turned on Mr Forsyth
for hijacking the plan for the drugs campaign. It was clear last night that Mr
Robertson had expected a joint announcement with the other political leaders.
Of the Ben Lomond Memorial Park plan, Mr Robertson said: ``How much more
imaginative it would have been to declare the whole of Loch Lomond and the
Trossachs as Scotland's first national park.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Winter death toll rises as woman retraces a boyfriend's footsteps to death.  Three die in plunge at icy lake</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALISON DANIELS and ROB ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651459</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE cold weather has claimed another four lives with the deaths of a homeless
man in Scotland and two men and an 11-year-old girl in a lake in West Yorkshire.
The lake victims died after they were trapped under ice for two hours in a
water park in Hamsworth, Kinsley, near Pontefract, West Yorkshire.
The accident happened after Tracy Patterson, 11, of Wortley Place, Hemsworth,
tried to rescue a dog. She got into difficulties and fell into the water. A
passer-by, Jack Crawshaw, of Wrenthorpe, near Wakefield, jumped into the water
but he was soon in difficulties himself.
Mr Mike Mee, 48, a fire officer who was walking in the park with his wife,
attempted to rescue the pair by spreading a tarpaulin sheet over the ice. But
the ice gave way and he too disappeared under the water.
Emergency fire services were on the scene in minutes but had to abandon their
rescue attempt and call in a police underwater search unit. The three were
found at a depth of three metres and had drifted seven metres from the bank of
the lake.
All three were taken to Pontefract General Infirmary and placed on ventilator
machines even though none had any heartbeat or pulse. Doctors attempted to
raise their body temperatures by using cardiac massage and injecting warm
fluids into their bodies. After five hours, however, the battle was called off
and they were pronounced dead.
In Bathgate, a 54-year-old man sleeping rough died as he huddled for shelter
against the winter blasts in a vennel. Mr John Murphy became the first homeless
person in Scotland to die in the severe winter. His death prompted calls for
more action to ease the plight of the homeless.
Mr Murphy's body was found in an alleyway between two houses in the West
Lothian town's Marina Road early on Wednesday morning as temperatures plummeted
to -15C. Police said he was found wearing a light jacket and trousers and had
no blankets covering his body.
It also emerged that the freezing temperatures claimed an elderly victim in
Renfrewshire on Tuesday night. Widow Elizabeth Donaldson, 77, was discovered
frozen to death in an industrial estate in Linwood by a teenage girl.
Police said the pensioner had decided to go out for a walk, possibly became
disorientated and had succumbed to hypothermia. She was found dead behind a
baker's store in the Mossedge goods yard. The pensioner, of Watson Avenue,
Linwood, lived alone but had been reported missing by a neighbour.
Mr Murphy's death prompted a call from Shelter, the homeless action group, for
more accommodation for those sleeping rough on Scotland's streets as weather
conditions looked set to worsen.
The organisation said it would be contacting Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth
today in the wake of the death. It is estimated that between 500 and 1000
people have been sleeping on Scotland's streets over the Christmas period.
The organisation's Kate Caskie said: ``We believe that Mr Murphy's death
highlights the problems they face over Christmas and I will be contacting the
Scottish Office today to try and find a way of setting up temporary
accommodation centres for the homeless people during the cold weather.
``I accept that needs new cash but surely the Scottish Office with its
resources could find places to help the people on the street at least in the
short term.''
The Scottish Office later confirmed it was pressing ahead with a study into the
homelessness problem. When asked about Shelter's calls for temporary
accommodation for the homeless, a spokeswoman said: ``We regret the death of Mr
Murphy but it is up to the housing authorities to pinpoint their local needs
regarding homelessness.''
Ms Caskie described the Scottish Office response as ``a cop-out''.
She added: ``The Government has spent thousands of pounds through the years
finding places for homeless people in London. So far in Scotland they haven't
spent a penny which is appalling.''
Ms Donaldson's death brought a warning from Age Concern Scotland that many
pensioners would suffer severe health problems because of the drop in
temperature.
However, a spokeswoman for Strathclyde Regional Council's social work
department said the region's 75,000 elderly people appeared to have been coping
remarkably well with the cold weather but said there were concerns if the cold
spell continued.
Police forces said there had been a number of sudden deaths over the last few
days but only Lothian and Borders said that the deaths of seven people over a
24-hour period could be linked to the cold weather.
Officers were called to investigate the deaths of a 69-year-old woman in
Bathgate; a 21-year-old man in Dunbar; a 69-year old woman in Penicuik, a
91-year-old in Livingston; and a 78-year-old in Blackburn.
Two 54-year-olds also died at different addresses in Edinburgh. All the victims
died in their homes and there were no suspicious circumstances.
Assistant chief constable Tom Wood said: ``The deaths have obviously been due
to a number of factors but the cold is exacerbating it.''
Across Scotland emergency services reported a spate of frozen and burst pipes.
Strathkelvin District Council's housing department opened three emergency
centres for residents in Kirkintilloch to provide running water.
Mr Fraser Millar, who fell through ice at Threipmuir Reservoir, Balerno, on
Christmas Eve, was last night in a ``serious but stable'' condition in the
Royal Infirmary, Edinburgh.
Mr Millar, 29, of Bughtlin Park, Corstorphine, Edinburgh, had been trapped for
an hour in the reservoir after ice gave way beneath him as he tried to rescue
his dog.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Family's double tragedy</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651460</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
THE family of 16-year-old John Colquhoun, who froze to death on Christmas Day,
revealed last night it was the second tragedy to strike them in as many years.
The dead youth's sister, Lorna, was left grieving the death of her boyfriend
early last year.
Like John, unemployed builder Martin Coia, 18, of Auchinleck, died from
hypothermia after trying to walk home early in the morning.
He walked out of the Colquhoun family home in Barbieston Avenue, Drongan, at
1am after a row with Miss Colquhoun. The couple had been together for 18
months.
He decided to cut across fields and failed to return home. He was found four
days later.
John Colquhoun, who also died after trying to walk home, was a passenger in a
car that slid off the road at 3am. He and the driver, Mr Ronald Paterson, 21,
walked off in different directions and John's frozen body was found the next
day under a bridge two miles from the scene of the accident.
Last night, Miss Colquhoun, 18, said: ``What happened to John has brought it
all back. I can't believe this has happened. We are all devastated.''
Miss Colquhoun explained why Mr Coia tried to walk home in bitterly cold
weather. She said: ``He had left my house early in the morning after we had
fallen
out. He had been drinking and he just decided to walk home to Auchinleck.
``He must have fallen asleep after stopping for a rest.''
Mr John Colquhoun Sr, 41, said: ``My advice to anybody in the same position
would be to stay off the back roads in weather like this and stick together if
anything happens. Don't be afraid to ask for help.''
He added that Mr Paterson, who was driving at the time of the accident, should
not feel guilty about what had happened.
He said: ``Although Ronald is a few years older than John, they hung around
together all the time. He was here last night and he was in an awful state.
He's
not letting himself come to terms with it and he's blaming himself, but he
shouldn't. We understand what happened and it could easily have been the other
way round.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000068</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000068</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Border Grain enjoys record throughput</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT ROSS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651461</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BORDER Grain Limited, the Berwickshire-based farmers' co-operative, had a
record throughput of just under 31,000 tonnes this year.
``We have had an extremely good year and are now examining a number of measures
which will enable us to build on our success next year and beyond,'' said
chairman Gareth Baird.
``While it is immensely satisfying to be able to base our operation on more
than 30,000 tonnes of grain for the first time in our 16-year history, we want
to convert as much as possible of the uncommitted tonnage which we attracted
this year into pre-harvest commitments next year.
The 17-strong co-operative group is also keen to add to its membership,
believing that its record over the past two years would stand comparison with
any similar grain-sector business.
``We are definitely performing at a high level and producing consistently good
results for our members,'' said Mr Baird. ``The combination of good yields and
good returns this year has given all cereal growers in Scotland fresh
opportunities to improve their long-term prospects.
``In keeping with others in the grain sector, therefore, we are determined to
use some of our 1995 gains to achieve greater trading strength in the future.''
As part of its development plan the co-op has decided to retain all of the
1994-95 profit of #28,500 in the business to cover the cost of the on-going
refurbishment and upgrading of Border Grain's drying, storage and distribution
base at Charterhall, Duns.
``When you consider that we haven't increased drying charges since July 1990,
our #28,500 profit is an indication of our current strength,'' said Mr Baird.
The Charterhall complex can dry up to 60 tonnes an hour and has a total storage
capacity of 30,000 tonnes. It also has a ``futures-approved'' store which
allows grain to be traded on the futures market without the imposition of
additional haulage charges.
The co-operative has a strong malting-barley base but also trades soft wheat,
milling wheat, milling oats, oilseed rape, high erusic acid rapeseed, protein
peas and beans, and linseed.
In addition to handling both committed and uncommitted grain from members,
Border Grain takes grain from non-members and provides contract drying and
storage services.
</TEXT>
