<DOCNO>GH951229-000069</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000069</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Ordinary duty turned to  horror for first medic</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>974651462</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE first medic on the scene was 22-year-old George McIlwraith, a volunteer
with St Andrew's Ambulance Corps.
The opening 15 minutes of the match were even more run-of-the-mill than usual.
He treated one man with a nose-bleed and another for a knee injury.
Bizarrely, both were to re-emerge from the terraces later - with one in
particular playing a crucial role in Mr McIlwraith's sudden appearance on
Stairway 13 just as the tragedy unfolded.
Close to the end of the game, the man with the nose-bleed returned for more
treatment. Then the man with the sore knee fell in an area close to where
dozens would topple to their deaths moments later.
Mr McIlwraith went into the crowd and patched up the man before taking him on a
stretcher to the trackside.
While there, Mr McIlwraith was ordered by another first aid officer to go to
the back of the stadium because of rumours that ``a gate had collapsed''.
Mr McIlwraith was adamant he subsequently asked a policeman on the terraces
where the gate had collapsed but was told only that he had no knowledge of it.
Speaking at length about his experiences for the first time - and also
expressing surprise that he was never called to the fatal accident inquiry - Mr
McIlwraith, now 47, and duty officer for first aiders at Hampden Park, recalled:
``I had gone up Stairway 14, spoke to the policeman, then went to Stairway 13.
I did not see, as everyone described in the press, a heap of bodies on the
stairs . . .
``But I did see a grass embankment covered in bodies and a lot of people lying
at the bottom of the embankment.
``A lot of people were injured, a lot were unconscious. Because there were so
many, I could not spend time with one particular person.
``Once I had established someone was breathing and had a pulse, I moved on to
the next. If the person was unconscious, I placed them on their sides to
prevent the risk of choking.
``I was on auto-pilot, in a mode I had never experienced before. Everything
clicked,'' Mr McIlwraith said.
However, he admits, his overall experience of the event was ``nothing short of
chaos''.
That is not a criticism, more a reflection on what was happening: ``No-one had
anticipated such a tragedy would every occur and it is possibly a reaction to
the horror of it all.''
At the time, Mr McIlwraith was an apprentice metallurgist and had been a corps
officer for about eight months.
He is now commandant of a Rutherglen corps and works full time for St Andrew's
Ambulance Association, involved mainly in health and safety in the workplace.
</TEXT>
