<HEADLINE>Dutch report new Brown Rot cases</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By COLIN LEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651463</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE number of confirmed cases of Potato Brown Rot in the Netherlands has
advanced to 60 after remaining on 46 for more than two months.
The 14 new cases were identified during the final phase of a special testing
programme designed to screen the 250 farms deemed to be most at risk.
Spread throughout the Netherlands, the high-risk farms were identified as
having used seed from the same clonal source as was planted on the farm which
produced the first Brown Rot case in Holland. That case, discovered at the end
of September this year, led to a #3m testing programme which gave priority
attention to all clonal contact farms.
All potatoes grown on these farms were examined for evidence of Brown Rot
infection. Bacteria collected from any sample which gave cause for concern were
put through a growth test using tomato plants. The 14 new cases all failed the
growth test.
With all 250 of the high-risk farms now screened, the result is that 190 are
clean and have been freed to operate as normal, while the 60 diseased fields
have been put on a strict five-year non-potato production regime.
All infected fields must be put to grass for the next three years, after which
they can either be left in grass or used to produce a non-potato crop for a
further two years. The next available potato season therefore cannot be begin
until the year 2001.
Ministry of Agriculture officials in the Netherlands have still not reached a
decision on whether or not to allow potatoes to be grown on clean fields within
a farm which has a confirmed Brown Rot field.
EU plant health inspectors have visited the Netherlands during the past few
weeks and will be reporting their findings to the EU Plant Health Standing
Committee early in the New Year.
Meanwhile, both seed and ware potatoes grown on farms within a three-kilometre
radius of an infected field have to be tested and declared clear of Brown Rot
before they can be offered for sale.
All seed potatoes have to be tested and declared clear of Brown Rot before they
can be issued with a plant passport for export.
As an additional health protection measure, all cyclists, walkers and hunters
have been warned, through their various clubs and associations, to avoid
crossing any of the 60 diseased fields to halt the spread of Brown Rot.
</TEXT>
