<DOCNO>GH951229-000073</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000073</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Safety in the old numbers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651562</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KEITH BRUCE gets a special preview of the new season at the Citizens' Theatre
THE characteristic combination of imagination and thrift is evident in a
slimmed-down spring season at Glasgow's Citizens' Theatre. As he acknowledged
publicly for the first time at the theatre's 25th anniversary celebrations,
artistic director Giles Have
rgal is proud of his reputation for tailoring the drama to the cloth available.
Havergal has been outspoken over the past year about the dangers to arts
funding inherent in local government reorganisation and in the run up to the
effecting of that change at the end of March, the Citizens' programme is an
acknowledgment of the uncerta
inties that lie ahead. While nothing is a bankable certainty on the stage, in
the Gorbals there is clearly an attitude of ``safety first'', with all bar one
of Citz spaces spending time ``dark'', and three of the six productions being
revivals.
While he denies that financial considerations outweighed artistic ones,
Havergal admits the problems.
``Every playlist is a balance of what we want to do and what resources are
available and the spring season is always a tricky slot, because it is time to
hit that target.''
Although neither of the autumn's Edinburgh Festival transfers - Don Carlos or
TAG's adaptation of Alasdair Gray's Lanark - produced the hoped-for audiences
in Glasgow, Havergal insists that the Citizens' is ``doing OK at the moment'',
with healthy receipt
s from the Christmas production, Pinocchio.
It is followed on to the main stage by Havergal's adaptation of Graham Greene's
Travels With My Aunt, a three-hander performed by himself, Patrick Hannaway and
Derwent Watson - last seen at Mayfest in 1990 before transfering to the Lyric
in London. Its su
ccess was originally born of economic pressures when Havergal staged it as an
inexpensive end to a season of lavish productions. ``I'll just do something
myself in a pullover,'' he is quoted as saying. The revival runs from January
26 to February 17.
The next production in the same space is Harry Gibson's eagerly anticipated
follow-up to Trainspotting, his adaptation of Irvine Welsh's Marabou Stork
Nightmares, from March 1 for three weeks.
During the same period Citizens' head of design Kenny Miller follows up his
directorial debut (Look Back in Anger this year) with the stalls studio's only
spring show: Jean Cocteau's The Human Voice. This short piece consists entirely
of a woman talking o
n the telephone to her lover, an initially cordial conversation which
degenerates.
The Circle Studio is the theatre's busiest spring space, and houses two
familiar pieces and one intriguing rarity. Don't Start Me was a hit at the
Edinburgh Fringe for CPT (formerly Castlemilk People's Theatre). Ford Kiernan
and John Paul Leach's two-hand
er about Scottish stand-up Tasty McDade was described as ``memorable and richly
characterised'' by The Herald's Sara Villiers.
Lookout theatre's date rape play, Easy, by company founder Nicola McCartney,
returns to the theatre after a successful run in Mayfest last year and before
being made into a film by director John McGrath.
During March the studio sees what may be the British premiere of a late and
rare Tennessee Williams' In the bar of a Tokyo hotel.
n Booking for the Citizens' new season opens on Thursday January 4, Box Office
0141 429 0022.
</TEXT>
