<HEADLINE>Anonymous woman may know who killed Mhairi `Please contact us' urges detective</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID STEELE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651567</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A MOTHER stricken by conscience may hold a vital clue to the identity of the
killer of Kilmarnock schoolgirl Mhairi Julyan.
The detective leading the murder inquiry yesterday disclosed that a letter,
apparently written by a concerned mother, had been received by the Julyan
family at their home in the town's Samson Avenue.
Detective Chief Inspector Bob Lauder said the letter had been posted in the
Kilmarnock area earlier this week and had been received by Mhairi's parents on
Wednesday morning.
He declined to discuss the contents of the anonymous letter in detail but said
there were ``very clear indications'' that the letter came from a concerned
mother who had important information about the identity of the killer.
Mr Lauder added: ``It is vital that the author of this letter gets in touch
with me at the incident room as soon as possible in order that I can discuss
the contents of the letter with her.
``I assure this person that the information will be treated in the strictest
confidence and I will be happy to meet her anywhere at any time to have a
discussion about what she has written and what she knows.
``My message to the woman who wrote this letter is clear - it is important that
the person who carried out this awful crime is dealt with and while I know it
is a major hurdle, you must force yourself to get over it and contact us at
once . . . it will gi
ve you peace of mind as well as helping the Julyan family and the entire
community to come to terms with the loss of a young girl.
``It will not bring her back but I believe it will help if we can bring this
inquiry to a conclusion.''
Meantime, the murder squad, boosted by detectives from every division of
Strathclyde as well as the Major Crime Resource Unit, will assess the
information contained in the letter and follow up other important leads.
Mr Lauder conceded there was a possibility the letter was not genuine and
added: ``If that is the case, it would be a quite dreadful hoax to perpetrate
on a grieving family.''
He said it was unusual for such a communication to be received by the victim's
family, although sympathy cards and messages of support had come from the
immediate area and beyond.
Mr Lauder said another possible sighting of Mhairi - this time at the junction
of London Road and Nursery Avenue - on the evening of December 16 had been
reported.
He again urged anyone with the slightest piece of information to get in touch.
``No-one should think they are cluttering up the inquiry by making a call.
Their small piece of information could be vital.
``We are not going to go away. We are here until the person is found and the
inquiry closed.''
Mhairi, a fifth-year pupil at Kilmarnock Academy, disappeared on December 16
while on her way home from a pantomime at the Palace Theatre.
Her body was discovered in the Stagecoach bus depot in McKinlay Place, a few
hundred yards from her home, the next afternoon.
q A father yesterday made an emotional appeal for the safe return of his
teenage daughter who disappeared after a Christmas Eve disco.
Delivery driver Robert Smith, 49, pleaded for news of his daughter Louise, 18,
at a police news conference.
In a personal message, he said: ``Louise, we all love you. Please get in touch
by any means. We want you back.''
She disappeared early onChristmas morning following the disco at Spirals
nightclub in the heart of Yate, near Bristol.
Police are investigating the possibility that she was sighted shortly after 2am
in the passenger seat of a blue Ford Escort driven by a female friend called
Emma. Police are still trying to trace the friend and the car.
</TEXT>
