<HEADLINE>Minister moves to cut planning delays</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN MacCALMAN Municipal Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651568</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TOUGH measures to reduce delays in processing planning applications were
announced yesterday by Mr George Kynoch, Scottish Local Government Minister.
The changes, detailed in a review of the town and country planning system,
include performance targets along with tighter timetables for dealing with
planning applications and appeals.
\Performance targets will cover the progress of structure plan reviews,
national guidance and advice, decisions on individual cases as well as the work
of the Scottish Office Inquiry Reporters' Unit.
According to the Scottish Office, good progress has been made in this area and
work will continue towards meeting the target of 28 weeks for public local
inquiry cases by the end of 1996.
Once met, it is intended to tighten further the target for written submission
cases to 26 weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000080</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000080</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Thousands  of skiers take to Scotland's icy slopes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651569</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SIX thousand skiers and snow-boarders enjoyed superb conditions on Scotland's
slopes yesterday.......the busiest day of the festive break so far.
Temperatures at the five Scots winter sports centres remained well below zero
all day, while clear blue skies, with hardly any winds, were the order of the
day.
Road access was clear to all centres. However, some resorts still do not have
as much snow as they would like and the White Corries Centre in Glencoe has yet
to open for the season.
The excellent skiing conditions will continue today and operators of all
resorts are keeping their fingers crossed that the settled but bitterly cold
spell of weather will continue beyond Hogmanay.
Not so the homeless and those working to keep them off the streets during
Scotland's big chill.
Shelter in Scotland director Ms Liz Nicholson said homeless people in the
larger cities had a wide range of hostels to choose from but those in smaller
towns were less fortunate.
In Glasgow, emergency accommodation is being provided through the city
council's Winter Watch Campaign between December and March. Under the scheme,
now in its third year, a number of places in hostels across the city are kept
for those who need accommoda
tion in an emergency.
The campaign is run through the Hamish Allan Centre, a hostel in Centre Street,
which links to other hostels in the city to provide beds.
The centre itself has 24 emergency places available.
Operations director Brian O'Hara said: ``We have had 62 presentations since the
beginning of the campaign and we have been able to accommodate them all.''
He said Glasgow did not need an emergency shelter for when the weather turned
bad: ``We do not have a homelessness problem on the scale of that in London.''
Ms Margaret Stevenson, director of the Talbot Association, a hostel also
involved in the campaign, agreed. ``Glasgow is unique as it has an adequate
number of places,'' Ms Stevenson said. ``There tends to be a place for everyone
who needs and wants it. Th
ere are small groups of people that just won't come in and we take food and
blankets to them.''
Major Raymond Ward, team leader for the Glasgow Homeless for the Salvation
Army, said: ``At this time of year, we get people who would normally sleep
rough. There aren't actually a big proportion of these in Glasgow.''
However, he does believe a large emergency accommodation centre would help.
Meanwhile, it became clear yesterday that the major problems in the storm-hit
parts of northern Scotland have arisen in areas where the original power-lines,
dating back 40 years, are still in use.
Hydro-Electric are spending #20m a year on replacing old lines. About 1000
miles of overhead lines will be replaced each year out of a total of 30,000
miles of cables carried by electric poles in the whole of northern Scotland.
In the Western Isles alone the privatised company has spent #41m on line
renewals during the past five years. A Hydro-Electric spokesman said: ``We are
seeing a clear link between the age of the lines and problems with cuts in
power supply during the pres
ent emergency.''
He said almost all the areas which suffered serious power supply problems were
still served by the network erected when the Highlands and Islands were
electrified in the late 1940s and 1950s.
Earlier this year, the company was the only privatised electricity utility in
Britain to refuse an order from the Government's Electricity Regulator to cut
power costs by 10% over a three-year period.
Hydro-Electric's chairman Lord Wilson of Tillyorn argued then that his company
was a special case because of the very long mileage of rural supply lines which
needed to be replaced.
He won his case in an appeal to the Government's Monopolies and Merger
Commission.
</TEXT>
