<HEADLINE>SNP urges Irish-style tax breaks for film makers</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALLAN LAING Entertainments Writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651570</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE introduction of Republic of Ireland-style tax breaks and the establishment
of a single organisation to oversee policy and strategy were among proposals
put forward yesterday by the SNP to boost Scotland's post-Braveheart film
industry.
The plans, which will be contained in a consultation document to be published
in the new year, have been formulated after discussions with the country's
major film organisations and leading industry figures.
Ms Roseanna Cunningham, the SNP's parliamentary spokesperson on film, said:
``Future success depends on a sustainable level of domestic production that
will result in regular success for low and medium-budget films and the
attraction of international film
s to be shot in Scotland. Our consultations have led us to propose two
essential first steps.
``The first is the introduction by Government of tax breaks for production,
which must be modelled on the highly successful `Section 35' Irish scheme.''
Film investment from private sources, which Ms Cunningham also regarded as
vital, would not be forthcoming to any significant degree unless these tax
breaks were in place.
In the Republic, as a means of encouraging new work, a film company is allowed
to write off tax for new investment. To qualify, it has to prove that the
project is worthwhile, that a proportion of the budget will be spent on
training, and that the film wi
ll employ an Irish crew.
The policy has met with startling success. At present, there are 80 movie
projects in development in Ireland. In Scotland, there are 20. The tax breaks
were in part responsible for Mel Gibson's decision to move filming from
Scotland to Ireland for the hug
e battle scenes in Braveheart.
Though the eventual tax advantages did little more than cover the costs of
moving location, Gibson admitted that the Irish had been enormously helpful,
providing thousands of extras from the ranks of the Irish army and around 600
horses. It is this climat
e of assistance, as much as the tax breaks, which the SNP wants to create in
Scotland.
To this end, the Nationalists' chief executive, Mr Mike Russell, disclosed that
the second essential step would be the establishment of Scottish Screen, a
federated organisation which would bring together existing bodies such as the
Scottish Film Council,
the Scottish Film Production Fund, Scottish Screen Locations, and the Scottish
Broadcasting and Film Training Trust. It would be a ``one-stop shop'' for
film-makers.
It would also include a new department, responsible for marketing and
distributing Scottish films at home and - more importantly - abroad.
Further down the line, the party also proposed the establishment of a Scottish
Film School and the creation of a major sound stage for film and television
production.
</TEXT>
