<DOCNO>GH951229-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN MacCALMAN Municipal Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651571</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRIVATE sector tenants in the south and west of Glasgow have won a battle to
stop their landlord imposing a #1450 rent increase.
The Western Heritable Investment Company failed to convince the Rent Assessment
Committee that the rents of 539 properties in Kings Park, Croftfoot,
Hillington, Cardonald, and Kelvindale should be increased from the #2150
suggested by the Rent Officer to
#3600.
The tenants were represented by Aitkenhead councillor Louise Fyfe, who said
last night: ``These properties are occupied mostly by elderly tenants and tend
to be in a poor state of repair. Many of the tenants have great difficulty
getting their landlord to
carry out repairs efficiently, yet there is a move for this massive increase.''
It is the tenants' second victory against Western Heritable. A 1992 decision by
the Rent Assessment Committee to restrict rents for the same properties to
#1860 was upheld in the Court of Session last June.
At a recent hearing concerning the latest rents proposals, Western Heritable
claimed tenants had no grounds for complaint about repairs.
The company argued that similar properties were being rented for #3600 on the
open market. It also argued that it was not part of the company's function to
look after elderly tenants.
However, tenants' evidence suggested that many of the properties were in a poor
state of repair and that many tenants suffered from water penetration, poor
sound insulation, unsafe wiring, crumbling steps and pathways, and leaking
doors, windows, gutters,
and roofs.
The committee visited a sample of the houses and expressed ``concern'' about
the condition of some of the properties.
Councillor Fyfe said the #3600 rents proposed by Western Heritable were kept
artificially high by the Housing Benefit system and by the shortage of rented
housing in the area.
She said similar properties in the area, including Housing Association
properties, had rents set at #2150.
Mr Tom Rowlands, manager of Western Heritable's Glasgow Office, said: ``We are
disappointed. We feel we presented enough evidence to show that a market rent
was #3600.
``However, it was not sufficient to convince the committee that it was the way
to go about making their decision on rents. They decided they would prefer to
use comparable rents, which other rent officers had already set.''
A company decision on the possibility of an appeal to the Court of Session will
not be made until the board of directors has considered the decision in detail.
Tenants'
victory
in rents
battle
</TEXT>
