<HEADLINE>CBI in upbeat mood</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651572</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ECONOMY
THE CBI yesterday described prospects for the economy over the next two years
as ``generally encouraging''.
It believes economic growth, following on from November's Budget, will be 2.5%
next year, rising to 2.8% in 1997.
In a New Year message to members, chairman Sir Bryan Nicholson said: ``We are
cautiously optimistic about the prospects for the economy following the prudent
Budget and the early interest rate cut.
``We now seem on track for sustainable non-inflationary growth over the next
two years. We expect consumer spending to be the mainstay of this economic
growth as real incomes rise and the inflation outlook remains positive.''
Sir Bryan said the CBI is forecasting that underlying inflation, which excludes
mortgage interest payments, will stand at 2.8% by the end of 1996, falling back
to 2.7% by the end of 1997. This is close to the mid-point of the Government's
1% -4% target ra
nge.
``Providing we are able to maintain firm control of costs, we should see
unemployment fall very close to the psychologically important two million mark.
``By the end of 1996 we expect unemployment to be 2.19 million, falling to 2.07
million by the end of 1997.''
However, Sir Bryan warned of some uncertainties facing the economy in the short
term. ``Our latest monthly trends survey shows that UK manufacturers expect a
slowdown in output growth in the first part of the new year and that stocks of
finished goods are
at their highest level since November 1992.''
He said the CBI was also concerned about key European export markets, where it
predicts demand will continue to remain weak into the new year.
On interest rates, he believes the time might soon be right for a further
reduction. ``We are keeping a close check on the moderating pace of growth
among manufacturers.
``If this continues and inflation remains under control, we would support a
further cut in interest rates to provide a stimulus to business growth.''
</TEXT>
