<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000084</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000084</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Abbey Life disposes of German subsidiary</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicola Reeves</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651573</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LLOYDS Abbey Life, the life insurer owned in part by Lloyds Bank, is selling
its German life subsidiary, Transleben for #50m cash. The buyer is a German
company, writes NICOLA REEVES.
The purchase price, payable after a final injection of DM5m (#2.2m) for
solvency purposes to Transleben by Abbey Life, represents a deficit against
book value of #35m.
Transleben, whose primary markets are personal and small businesses in Germany,
has been loss-making in recent years. In 1994, it made a pre-tax loss of #13.6m
but is thought to have reduced this year's deficit to #5m. It was Abbey Life's
only non-UK fina
ncial services business.
City analysts believe that the disposal is at a reasonable price and is broadly
positive for Abbey Life. The disposal had been expected for some time. News of
the sale at a substantial discount knocked Abbey Life's shares down 4p to 449p.
However the disp
osal is expected to be slightly earnings enhancing next year.
While Lloyds Abbey Life is getting out of European markets Royal Insurance is
expanding its overseas network with the opening of its first Italian office on
January 1, outside Milan. The group already employs 22,000 people in 90
countries. The Italian off
ice will offer direct car insurance seven days a week.
The move illustrates Royal's confidence in southern Europe. It already has an
Italian subsidiary, Lloyd Italico, offering personal lines insurance with a
market share of about 1%. In addition it has a substantial share of the direct
Catalan motor market t
hrough Regal of Barcelona.
Following liberalisation of the Italian motor insurance market there has been
increased interest in direct services in what is a relatively under-developed
sector. In contrast, the UK motor insurance market remains highly competitive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000085</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000085</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>ELECTRONICS Rogers quits Amstrad post</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651574</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AMSTRAD'S chief executive David Rogers is to leave the computer and consumer
electronics group in January after only 17 months in the post, it was announced
yesterday.
Mr Rogers was recruited from Philips, the Dutch electronics giant, principally
to beef up the group's traditional consumer electronics business after chairman
Alan Sugar decided to withdraw from high street price wars by selling personal
computers and bus
iness equipment direct to customers. The reorganisation of the consumer
electronics business - including video recorders, stereo systems and satellite
- was part of a wholesale restructuring undertaken by Mr Rogers.
In a brief statement Amstrad said: ``Following a strategic review of the future
prospects of Amstrad's traditional business, Amstrad Consumer Electronics, it
has determined to alter the structure of ACE's activities with a view to
reducing its cost base i
nto line with its sales potential.
``Mr Rogers joined the board in August 1994 with a part of his brief to take
forward the business of ACE.
``In view of the decision taken by the board, Mr Rogers has indicated that he
wishes to step down from the board of Amstrad.''
Earlier this year, Mr Rogers promised ``a whole range of new products'' from
ACE in the near future, including fax machines, bubble-jet printers and a
pocket-size organiser.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000086</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000086</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lloyds TSB Group plays down speculation that it is poised to sell merchant banking operation Merged bank makes strong debut</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAN McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651575</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LLOYDS TSB Group yesterday became the largest company registered in Scotland,
when the #15bn merger of its two constituent banks became effective.
Shares made a strong debut on the Stock Exchange, with brokers James Capel and
SG Strauss Turnbull taking ``buy'' stances.
The shares closed 4!sp above the notional Wednesday closing price of 339p set
by the London Stock Exchange, at 343!sp. More importantly, they were up 30!sp -
nearly 10% - on their ex-special dividend price of 313p. In an extremely quiet
London market, vol
ume was more than nine million shares.
John Tyce, banking analyst at SG Strauss Turnbull, believed the effective stock
split for Lloyds shareholders, who received 2.704 Lloyds TSB shares for each
Lloyds share previously held, was responsible for much of the strength of the
new shares.
He said: ``I think it (Lloyds TSB) is very strong for a variety of quite silly
reasons, like there is no business (in other stocks) and everybody loves a
share split.''
However, Mr Tyce sees benefits for the merged bank and is particularly
encouraged by Lloyds TSB's promise to cut annual costs by #350m by 1999.
The enlarged group's new registered office at TSB Bank Scotland's Edinburgh
headquarters was yesterday inaugurated by Gordon Anderson, the chairman of TSB
Bank Scotland who will sit on the board of Lloyds TSB.
Even though Lloyds TSB is now registered at Henry Duncan House in Edinburgh,
close to TSB's old registered office in Charlotte Square, Scotland accounts for
only 3300 of the enlarged group's nearly 90,000-strong workforce.
TSB envisages no net job losses in Scotland, where there is little duplication.
It also pledged not to axe any branches north of the Border next year, having
closed about 35 this year.
The enlarged group will be looking to reap benefits from the powerful
combination of TSB's extensive Scottish branch network and Lloyds' commercial
banking expertise, although it will no doubt be expecting a reaction from Bank
of Scotland, Royal Bank and
Clydesdale Bank.
A Lloyds TSB official said yesterday: ``We are aiming to be a very effective
competitor in Scotland, particularly in the commercial market.''
Emphasising the merged bank's focus on small and medium-sized Scottish
businesses, he added: ``I hope during 1996 we will be coming out with some
stuff which shows we are cutting the mustard in that market.''
Meanwhile, Lloyds TSB yesterday steered clear of rumours that it had made
approaches to potential purchasers of its Hill Samuel merchant banking
subsidiary.
It said it was ``far too early to say'' what its plans for Hill Samuel were.
Lloyds chairman Sir Robin Ibbs will chair the enlarged group, with TSB chairman
Sir Nicholas Goodison and Lloyds deputy chairman John Davies serving as his
deputies.
Sir Brian Pitman, chief executive of Lloyds, has assumed the same role at the
helm of the enlarged bank. Lloyds chief financial officer Kent Atkinson also
retains his role in the merged operation.
A 68.3p special dividend will be paid to TSB shareholders only on January 18.
</TEXT>
