<HEADLINE>ACQUISITIONS Barings tops the league with deals worth #19.5bn</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Nicola Reeves</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651576</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BARINGS, now part of the Dutch ING banking group, had a good year in terms of
corporate finance despite its well-publicised problems concerning Nick Leeson
and the subsequent collapse of the company and rescue by ING.
Baring Brothers has traditionally had a strong list of corporate clients and
managed to hold on to most of them amid its internal and external turmoil.
It topped the 1995 Acquisitions Monthly magazine's combined league table of
public and private transactions, ranked by deal value. Barings had 26 deals
worth an impressive #19.5bn. Eight of them, together worth #16.8bn, were public
takeovers.
Early in the year Baring Brothers was a co-adviser to Wellcome in its
high-profile #9100m takeover by rival drugs firm Glaxo - the largest
transaction of the year. Barings was also present on the second biggest deal,
advising Lloyds Bank in its #5900m tak
eover of the TSB Group.
It also advised on one of the few hostile utility bids so far, ScottishPower's
#1100m takeover of Manweb, the Chester-based regional electricity company.
There were 14 public bids over #1000m announced during 1995, compared with only
one in 1994. This was also ahead of the 1989 record when there were 11 such
deals.
Second in the corporate finance league table was Lazard Brothers with 30 deals
valued at #14.7bn. It advised Glaxo in its bid for Wellcome and is currently
working on two large deals: advising Granada in its #3100m hostile bid for
Forte, as well as acting
for National.&amp;.Provincial in its proposed #1300m takeover by Abbey National.
US banks did well in 1995 benefiting from the turmoil affecting several
domestic UK banks. Four of the major US banks, Goldman Sachs, JP Morgan, Morgan
Stanley and Lehman Brothers, were in the mergers and acquisitions (M.&amp;.A) top
20.
Acquisitions Monthly estimates that the City earned about #950m in fees from UK
takeovers in 1995. In 1989, the previous record year, this figure was estimated
at about #800m.
Philip Healey of Acquisitions Monthly believes that 1996 could be just as good
a year as 1995 for M.&amp;.A activity. The year will start with Granada still
battling to acquire the Forte hotels group.
</TEXT>
