<HEADLINE>MONETARY POLICY Bank minutes show caution at the helm</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS STONE, City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651577</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MINUTES of the monthly monetary meeting held on November 1, 1995, between the
Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke and the Governor of the Bank of
England Eddie George show both agreeing that there was no justification for a
change in interest rates
.
But it is clear that the Governor still had doubts on inflation at that time,
though both men agreed on a quarter-point reduction at their next meeting on
December 13 - the minutes of which will be released on Wednesday, January 31.
At their November 1 meeting the Governor said that the data received since the
last meeting were uncomfortable - the cost and price figures were somewhat
stronger than would have been hoped, while the activity and survey data were
somewhat softer. Uncerta
inty about both future prices and activity had increased.
Listing some of the more positive and some less positive features of the cost
front, Mr George said it was possible to make caveats about all these numbers.
In particular, both input prices and retail prices were probably affected by
the unusually warm we
ather. But he said there was also some evidence of continuing attempts to pass
on cost increases and to rebuild margins at the retail level.
Overall, the Governor said that the main issue was whether the current
indications of weakness in the economy were temporary, or whether they were
likely to persist. The Bank's central projection remained that demand and
activity were likely to pick up in
to next year, but there were also downside risks.
For his part, the Chancellor said that most commentators expected the recovery
to remain on track. Consumer demand should pick up in due course, once the
impact of the earlier increases in taxes started to wear off. There was also
now less concern that in
terest rates would be raised significantly. The housing market was still weak,
although there were some tentative signs that it had bottomed out.
Mr Clarke considered that the behaviour of the labour market would be very
important for the future course of inflation. Falling unemployment did not
appear to have put upwards pressure on earnings, in part because of the labour
reforms the Government had
put in place.
On inflation, the Chancellor conceded it had picked up a little more than
expected in September, but this could be explained by the hot weather in the
summer. He continued to expect inflation to return to its downward path in the
near future. Producer pri
ce inflation was receding, particularly the growth in manufacturing output
prices, and commodity prices had also eased.
Mr Clarke said that ``the monetary data continued to give mixed and confusing
signals, which were difficult to interpret.''
</TEXT>
