<HEADLINE>Food team aims to build on European triumph and pursue new markets in North America and the Far East Scottish beef reaps export success</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT ROSS, Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651578</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Breeding success ..... Alan Stevenson (left) and Dr Martin Grantley-Smith
checking on export quality at Low Boydston Farm, Ardrossan
SCOTLAND'S meat exporters can claim to be one of the success stories of the
1990s with a 162% increase in overseas sales in the past five years. That
growth has coincided with the formation of Scotmex - the Scottish meat export
initiative - which is spons
ored by Scottish Enterprise.
In 1989 meat exports were worth about #80m to Scotland. The most recent figures
show that sales of Scotch lamb alone now account for #94m and total meat
exports are worth #210m. The biggest contributor is beef, with sales of #108m.
At the other end of the
scale, pig meat comes in at #8m. Scottish food exports in 1994-95 totalled
#425m, an 11% increase on the previous year.
Dr Martin Grantley-Smith, chief executive of Scotmex, attributes the massive
growth in meat exports to two factors. He said: ``First of all, the
establishment of the single market led to greater access to European consumers.
``And the setting up of our own organisation and the efforts of the Scottish
Enterprise food team have greatly assisted Scottish meat producers in getting
into export markets all over Europe including advice and assistance with
exhibitions.''
Another factor has been the keen competition among supermarket groups which had
kept wholesale prices very low. That squeeze on margins had forced suppliers to
look to new markets and Scotland's reputation for quality produce had been a
major advantage in
penetrating export markets.
British beef didn't have a strong image in Europe but Scotch beef did have a
reputation for quality which had been built up over the years.
``In recent years we have seen a growing desire in restaurants across Europe to
stock the best ingredients and Scotch beef in particular is seen as the best -
along with our salmon and whisky,'' said Dr Grantley-Smith.
That perception has been encouraged by the setting up of the Scottish Beef
Club, which now has 600 restaurant members throughout Europe. In order to gain
membership restaurants must use Scotch beef and identify it as such on their
menus.
``The idea is that customers will enjoy their beef, notice that it is Scottish
beef and subsequently buy it themselves for home consumption,'' said Dr
Grantley-Smith. ``Beef has been our area of biggest growth - so it must be
working.''
Alan Stevenson, senior project executive with the Scottish Enterprise food
team, said: ``Scotland produces the best food in the world, but until fairly
recently we were not telling the rest of the world clearly enough that this was
the case.
``That is why we are now working hard to get the message across loud and clear
that Scottish meat is the best. We have met with a lot of success so far
through a programme of exhibitions, through our sponsorship of Scotmex and our
European Food Express sc
heme which works with companies wishing to get into export markets.''
The food team's aim now is to build on the European success and to pursue new
markets in North America and the Far East.
</TEXT>
