<HEADLINE>Table d'oat</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEEDEE CUDDIHY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651579</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n IT'S hard to believe but the humble oatcake is ``hot'', humble only because
it's made with the simplest of ingredients: oatmeal, a small amount of fat,
baking soda, salt, and hot water; ``hot'' because suddenly the range and
variety of oatcakes availabl
e at your local supermarket has increased to such an extent that the shopper is
truly spoiled for choice.
There are little ones, big ones, finger shapes, triangles; thick ones, thin
ones, traditional and farmhouse; rough ones, fine ones, Highland ones and
English ones. Organic and bran, mixed herb and cheese, honey and - wait for it
- garlic!
The rising popularity of the oatcake can be attributed to a number of factors
including an increasing awareness of ``heritage'' foods which are not only
nutritionally sound but low in calories and price.
Manufacturers must be rubbing their hands in glee for, unlike scones and
pancakes, a decent looking oatcake is not easily produced at home owing,
according to the late F.Marian McNeill, ``to the stickiness of the dough and
the tendency of the edges to bre
ak''.
In her famous book The Scots Kitchen, first published in 1929, she writes that
oatcakes have been around for 1500 years.
Six hundred years ago the Scottish soldier always travelled with a plate which
could be heated in a fire and then spread with an oatmeal and water paste to
form a cake of sorts.
After Culloden (according to Ms McNeill who heard the tale from someone else)
an old woman who lived near the battlefield ``carried her table, her girdle,
and a quantity of oatmeal down to the roadside, lit a gipsy fire, and baked for
all she was worth; w
hen presently Charlie's men came by, speeding to the hills for safety, each
seized an oatcake from the pile''.
By comparison, the twentieth-century oatcake taste test that The Herald
conducted recently with a group of Glasgow's senior citizens, was a laid-back,
low-key affair.
Elizabeth, Agnes, Virginia, Mary, Isa, and Violet belong to a group which meets
once a week at Oakbank Primary School. All said they ate oatcakes from time to
time but not in any great quantity. One member said she recalled oatcakes being
served with stov
ies, which sounded an awfully dry combination. Violet was appalled at the
notion of putting anything sweet on an oatcake and reeled in horror at talk of
jam, marmalade, and honey. Marian McNeill certainly approved of marmalade,
however, and also stated th
at oatcakes were improved by being heated shortly before serving.
Our testers who had to make do with absolutely plain, stone-cold samples were
surprised at the variety of oatcakes on the market these days. They tasted
Nairn's Traditional, Paterson's Farmhouse, Stockans Thin Original, Wooleys of
Arran Original, Walkers
Cocktail plus Simmers cheese, and Stockan and Gardens Garlic. The prices ranged
from 20p per 75g packet to 87p for a 250g box.
The results showed that although one brand emerged as a clear favourite,
there's not much to be said about oatcakes.
Stockans thin original was thought by the majority to be too dry. The Nairn's
was nice and crispy, according to some, and too hard, according to others.
Everyone likes the Paterson's although the testers, apart from Mary, preferred
the bitesize Walkers co
cktail oatcakes which, according to the tartan box they came in, are very nice
with smoked salmon, caviar, and champagne.
Nobody had a good word to say about the thick Arran oatcakes (among my personal
favourites) which were described by some as being ``too coarse''.
Despite misgivings, everyone was pleasantly surprised by the Stockan and
Gardens garlic oatcakes apart from Mary who hates garlic and wouldn't eat one.
But of the two flavoured varieties the Simmers cheese oatcakes got the better
response.
Overall our testers preferred the Walkers cocktail oatcakes mainly because, due
to their softer texture and small size, they were easier to eat than the others.
</TEXT>
