<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000091</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000091</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Taking a shine to the brass balls</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Beverley Lyons</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651580</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Britain's pawnbrokers have polished up their shabby Dickensian image to become
successful players in the finance sector of the nineties, stealing middle-class
customers from banks and building societies. Beverley Lyons investigates
WHEN the rich were rich and the poor were poor, it used to be said that the
only place where you could borrow money was from the church or at the
pawnbrokers.
While it is argued that the former's stature may well have crumbled with
modernisation, the position of the latter is positively flourishing.
Within the past decade membership of the National Pawnbrokers' Association has
doubled and the UK organisation now has 140 members who are accountable for 230
shops. In Scotland, four new outlets have opened in the past year; and
longstanding establishmen
ts, including Glasgow's Robert Biggar Pawnbrokers (est. 1830), are being
refurbished.
Of course, pawnbroking has transformed itself since the days of dealing with
``divers persons of ill fame and repute who live in garrets, cellars and other
obscure places''. The three brass balls may still be there, serving as a
reminder of Florence's Med
ici family crest (originally featuring three blue discs) but nowadays they
represent a different form of the trade.
Historically known as the poor people's bank, the Dickensian image of the old
boy in fingerless mittens greeting you with an avaricious grin has disappeared
along with the ``wee wimmen from the steamie'' and the ``hackitt rag and bone
man''. In the nineti
es, pawners are likely to be greeted by a slick server in a smart suit who will
ask you to come into his office and sit on a Chesterfield.
The reason for this renewed interest in an industry as old as the olden days is
the emergence of our recession-based credit culture, claims Nathan Finch, a
spokesman for the National Pawnbrokers' Association. Finch explains: ``People
are not so reticent a
bout borrowing cash in the nineties, but the obstinacy of banks to extend
short-term overdrafts and credit limits has led them to look elsewhere.''
He says the processing fees which the banks and building societies charge can
often make a small loan a frightening prospect. ``Over the past five years
banks have been reticent about doling out the cash as they used to in the
eighties. If you're in a reg
ular job with a regular wage and have overextended yourself by the end of the
month, why should you be penalised for wanting an extra hundred quid to tide
you over?''
Isobel Lindsay, lecturer in sociology in the department of government at
Strathclyde University, is in no doubt that the credit-card boom of the late
eighties altered public perceptions towards borrowing money, an activity once
restricted to the ranks of
the poor and feckless.
Lindsay says: ``As long as you have high levels of insecure employment and a
growth in the number of short-term work contracts the problem of debt is one
which is unlikely to diminish. The changing balance of power in employment has
created a new kind of
credit customer whose expectations have been high in the past but who may be
experiencing hard times through redundancies.''
According to social observers, the ``newly insecure'' find it harder to cope
with irregular incomes and yet refuse to put their lives on hold and wait for
better days.
Lindsay adds: ``This middle-class group who need money to furnish their homes
and maintain their lives actually have possessions of some worth to pawn.''
This type of customer joins two traditional categories of client affected by
debt in Scotland - the ``permanently poor'' and ``social problem'' groups.
``Undoubtedly there has been a substantial extension of the `permanently poor'
over the past 15 years as a result of the economic decline, yet they have
little to pawn and their expectations are low,'' says Lindsay.
Traditionally, those who need to fuel their alcohol or gambling habits (namely
the ``social problem'' category) have been the pawnbroker's best customers.
However, while our propensity to gamble remains among the highest - Scots spend
more per capita on t
he National Lottery than the rest of our UK counterparts - it is evident that
the birth of the ``newly insecure'' implies a different attitude towards
borrowing. One of the most obvious changes has been the type of item which is
now being traded to the pa
wnbrokers.
Times have changed since the days when clothes were accepted as part of the
pawning, when wives used to queue at the pawnbroker's door on a Friday evening
to retrieve the brown paper bags carrying their husbands' suits.
``Nowadays it's cars, deeds for houses, and even share certificates which
qualify as capital,'' says Edward Fox, owner of Robert Biggar Pawnbrokers, who
has been offered everything ``from Rolls-Royces down''.
The kind of people Fox caters for are just as likely to come from Newton Mearns
or Bearsden as housing estates in the city. Why they should go to a pawnshop
rather than a building society or bank remains a subject of debate. It is clear
that the pawnshop
is a feasible short-term option when it comes to cash in your hand or a secure
place to leave your belongings when you go on holiday.
Alan Scott, secretary of the Committee of Scottish Clearing Banks, recognises
the appeal of pawnbrokers. He says: ``In some respects they are providing a
service in a niche market - for particular people in particular
circumstances.'' Such as when you don
't want to explain to the bank manager that you need #30 for putting a quick
bet on the dead cert on the 3.10 at Newbury.
However, Scott is keen to point out that the services which banks and
pawnbrokers offer should not be equated. ``It's like comparing apples with
coconuts in that bank loans are unsecured whereas pawnshops require security
before they pay out.''
Scott agrees that today's financial client has more options than ever and that
attitudes towards moneylenders have changed. ``It used to be said that the
cloth-capped worker went to the pawnbroker and the bowler-hatted chap entered
the bank. Thankfully th
e stereotypes have now changed and nobody has to fit any preconception to get a
loan.''
Kings and countrymen, whatever their faith, are welcome to take a pledge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
