<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A mite clever</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651581</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n IT'S an ill wind . . . and the sub-Moscow blast afflicting Scotland is good
news alike for gas and electricity companies and the house dust mite.
Turning up the central heating a few notches and draught-proofing doors in
double-glazed homes creates a haven for the thousands of unseen guests, whose
microscopic droppings are blamed for triggering asthma, eczema and other
complaints.
How to maintain a comfortable, yet allergen-free, environment is the challenge
boffins at ADM Indux claim to have met - with an air-brick size unit that
extracts domestic pollution and moisture while warming incoming air with a
money-saving heat exchanger
.
Humidity is reduced and with it the threat of dust mite infestation. Single
room to whole-house ducted air systems are available.
An ingenious appendage to the popular Dirt Devil hand-held cleaner expels dust
from mattresses through a tube hung from the window, preventing mite pellets
from recirculating indoors.
For details of ADM Indux heat recovery ventilation phone 01274 690094.
n SINCE a student who disturbed rail passengers by playing loud pop music was
fined #300, trains seem to have become somewhat quieter.
But what happens if it's the driver of your coach who's responsible for the
din, by relaying a commercial radio station over the audio system?
Don't gurn and bear it is the advice of Scottish Citylink, some of whose
passengers were subjected to such an ordeal between Edinburgh and Glasgow.
Drivers have been given orders not to inflict their personal preferences in
music on others, said Citylink after Check-Out complained on behalf of a
customer. That's good news for the increasing number of commuters who welcome
the company's fare deals but
don't want to be force-fed Bjork and the Beatles, hear testimonials to turkey
and Toblerone and are totally indifferent to Hazel and Gary's love life in East
Kilbride.
n MONKS at Fort Augustus Abbey on Loch Ness have adopted the plastic habit,
joining 25,000 traders in the Countdown scheme that offers cardholders
discounts and special offers.
Part of the Abbey that housed pupils now boasts an impressive
computer-controlled historic exhibition, featuring the '45 uprising and the
story of the Great Glen. A modern restaurant, souvenir shop and residential
courses are part of the new look at the a
ncient Benedictine community.
Countdown are at 1 Hurlingham Business Park, Sulivan Road, London, SW6 3DU
(0171-610 9088).
n HOGMANAY message to revellers who get in a tight spot snagging their nylons -
don't flush your stockings down the loo!
Most domestic waste water pipes are no more than four inches wide and can
become blocked by discarded hosiery.
Bag It &amp; Bin It, the environmental pressure group, says even if you don't need
a plumber, flushed tights and stockings can still be a nuisance.
Discarded items ending up on beaches or riverbanks attract inquisitive wildlife
that can become ensnared, often with fatal consequences. The message from the
campaigners: put a sock in it!
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000093</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000093</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hammer falls on broken pledges</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LIZ TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>20</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651582</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIZ TAYLOR discovers what happens when the chips are down for the middle
classes and there's no hope of redemption
WHEN I was a junior reporter a long time ago there was a crisis in the office
after it was discovered there were not enough typewriters to go round.
First one vanished, then another, to be followed by a third and a fourth.
Eventually it was discovered that another reporter was pawning them, and our
forgiving editor sent someone round to the local pawnshop to redeem the tools
of our trade.
This memory came back when I saw a sale of unredeemed pawnbrokers' pledges was
to be held at Christie's, South Kensington.
A bored-sounding gentleman in Christie's jewellery department told me the
saleroom held four such sales a year and the majority of the lots were
jewellery or watches. It doesn't accept anything for sale that is valued at
less than #25. ``We get a lot of R
olexes and occasionally things like Cartier rings, but few surprises,'' he said.
Wondering what happens to more humble unredeemed pledges - typewriters for
example - I contacted the National Pawnbrokers' Association. Spokesman Harvey
Bell-Roberts said that when something was pawned, the broker lent money against
its value and could ke
ep it for six months if it was not claimed. Then 14 days' notice of intention
to sell the pledge had to be sent to the original owner. If it was still not
claimed the pawnbroker could sell the goods at auction, by tender, or by
private treaty.
If the sum raised by the sale was more than the original pledge, efforts had to
be made to return the balance to the person who pledged the goods originally.
If that person was untraceable, the pawnbroker could not claim the surplus
money for six years.
It is rare for a customer to vanish, he said, because most people who availed
themselves of pawnbrokers' services today were repeat customers, and usually
affluent middle class. Gone are the days of Charles Dickens when poor families
hocked their boots or
their blankets to get through the week. That sort of poverty is generally
taken care of by the social services now and today's pawnbroker lends money on
expensive golf clubs, good watches, or diamond rings.
Sometimes people try hocking their cars or the deeds of their houses. Every
pawnbroker has stories of the sort of things well-off customers attempt to
pledge in return for money to take expensive holidays, satisfy the mortgage
company, or pay the fees for
private schools. When the crisis is past and the cash flow has recovered, they
return and redeem their goods.
If pawnbrokers are suspicious about a customer and have doubts about how the
goods being offered have been obtained, they ask for receipts and can refuse to
take the suspect item.
Bell-Roberts said that for several years, because prices raised in auction
sales had tended to be low, pawnbrokers had not been sending much to the big
auction houses. Recently, however, things had improved and they were now using
auction sales again. Som
etimes items, particularly jewellery, were entered for sales as single lots,
but usually pawnbrokers used a saleroom in their own locality for shifting
unredeemed stock in bulk.
At the Glasgow Pawnbroking Company in Bath Street, Archie Crocket, who is an
NPA council member representing Scotland, said his company used Arthur Collins
saleroom at 114 Trongate to dispose of unredeemed pledges. Collins holds
pawnbrokers' auctions thre
e days a week, with goods being entered from all over Scotland. They sell
everything from television sets to silver and paintings and another two days,
Tuesdays and Thursdays, are set aside for selling jewellery.
Mr Crocket said about 7% of all pledges taken in his establishment were
unredeemed. People tried to pawn such disparate objects as their false teeth,
driving licences, and guitars. The oddest pledge he has accepted was a gipsy's
crystal ball, complete wit
h a book of instructions. The person who brought it in claimed it back within
the six months.
Another pawnbroker, Edward Fox, who has premises in Edinburgh and Glasgow, said
that 10% of his pledges ended up unredeemed. In the past he had been offered
such things as a skeleton from a medical student and a Lamborghini car (which
he did not accept);
gold discs by a failing pop star (which he did accept); and souvenirs of a
glorious past by a descendant of the Russian royal family who brought in
imperial cuff links, a red ceremonial sash, and some icons. They were not
redeemed but Mr Fox has kept them
, more for sentimental reasons than anything else. He thinks the Russian might
come back for them one day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000094</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000094</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Business Comment Changing with the times</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651583</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Stock Exchange faces a critical year in 1996 which could see a radical
change in the way shares are traded in the UK.
To start with the exchange will be reminded of its humiliating failure to
develop a modern electronic settlement system as Crest gets under way. The task
was taken away from it following the failure of its own Taurus development and
given to the Bank of E
ngland.
Crest has proceeded on schedule and to cost to the extent where detailed trials
involving all users will start shortly and it is due to be fully operational on
July 15.
Then the exchange will have a battle on its hands in trying to reconcile the
conflicting demands of the institutions which provide its members with their
business and the market-makers which provide the dealing system.
Institutions want to cut out the middleman and deal directly with each other by
using an order-driven trading system where buyers and sellers are matched
electronically, the system used in newer exchanges in other countries. This
contrasts with the tradit
ional quote-driven system where market-makers post the prices at which they are
prepared to buy and sell on an electronic bulletin board.
For once the exchange has sided with the modernisers and its own order-driven
system is due to begin in August. Market-makers fear they will be gradually
squeezed out and are fighting against change. This is hardly surprising since
their very existence is
under threat and with it an important part of the culture of the City of
London.
In reality the exchange has little choice if it is to avoid being outflanked by
rival share-dealing systems. An independent order-driven operation run by
Tradepoint is already in existence and others are likely, including attempts by
European markets to m
uscle in on London's business.
If the City is to retain its pre-eminence the exchange has to change with the
times in a more positive and committed way than it has in the past.
New route
ROYAL Insurance's expansion in southern Europe is the latest example of the
increasing internationalisation of the insurance market. This mirrors trends
seen in other financial services.
The impetus for these changes is coming from both the demand and supply side of
the industry, and are being made possible by the lowering of international
trade barriers in insurance and developments in information technology.
Within Europe the EC Insurance Directives, starting with the Reinsurance
Directive of 1964, have created for all classes of life and general insurance a
single market embracing all European Union (EU) and European Economic Area
(EEA) member states.
Since July 1994, an insurer authorised in any member state has been free to
enter into direct insurance contracts with a resident of any other member
state, this is subject to transitional arrangements for a few countries.
The UK motor account faces a particularly tough time with intense competition
from direct writers. These include the Royal Bank of Scotland's market-leading
Direct Line with over two million accounts representing over 12% of the market.
Therefore motor in
surance is a natural choice for the traditional composite insurers looking to
expand overseas. In 1995, private motor is expected to have accounted for
between 4% and 9% of worldwide general premiums.
The fact that there is so much competition in the domestic motor insurance
market with over 20 direct writers, means that insurance premium rates are
likely to remain soft as companies seek to increase their market share.
The prospect of this difficult trading background continuing for some time has
prompted Merrill Lynch to confirm its long-term underweight recommendation on
the sector.
Royal Insurance in particular, along with Sun Alliance, is thought to be
vulnerable to a cyclical downturn in the UK and structural change in the market.
Rule bending
MOVES by Carlton Television and Granada Television to get around their
excessive shareholdings in ITN - the news supplier to the independent networks
- look suspiciously like an attempt to bounce the Independent Television
Commission into accepting arrang
ements which fall short of complying with the rules.
The problem arose when the two companies took over Central and LWT
respectively. This resulted in them both doubling their holding in ITN to 36%
when the 1990 Broadcasting Act laid down a maximum holding by any one
shareholder of 20%.
The companies were given to the end of 1995 to reduce their holdings pending a
review by the Government of various ownership issues. The 20% limit was upheld
and the ITC expected them to comply by the end of the year.
Then at the end of November they came up with a scheme whereby the excess
holding would be parked into a separate entity where Carlton and Granada would
not be able to exercise the extra votes.
After taking legal advice, the ITC has now ruled that technically this would
not breach the provisions of the Act. But it does say it goes against the
spirit of the ownership rules and regrets the way the companies have
interpreted the Act. Furthermore it
will press for ``avoidance mechanisms'' to be dealt with in new broadcasting
legislation.
Carlton and Granada will no doubt argue that they can find no takers for the
shares, particularly given the way the television companies are trying to
negotiate better deals with ITN. However, they have had a whole extra year to
dispose of the excess shar
es and there must surely have been a price at which they could have been sold.
The whole episode is yet another example of the way in which the broadcasters
are constantly pushing against the rules which are rightly designed to prevent
market dominance.
</TEXT>
