<HEADLINE>Business Digest</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651584</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Land Rover drives
to new record
THE Land Rover company built a record number of 127,287 vehicles in 1995, 35%
more than the previous record set last year, it was announced yesterday.
Production of the utility Defender range rose from 22,234 to 27,670, while
nearly 70,000 Discovery vehicles were built, compared with 54,424 last year.
The company, based at Solihull in the West Midlands, said weekly production had
risen from 2600 in January to more than 3000 by the end of the year. A further
1200 employees had been taken on this year taking the total to 11,900.
Meanwhile, with just a few days to go, total UK new car sales for 1995 are
expected to finish at around the 1,920,000 mark achieved in 1994.
The last official published figures showed sales for the first 11 months
totalling 1,873,826 - a 1.97% increase on the comparable 1994 total.
Property purchase
PEMBERSTONE is buying the first, second and third Roman property trusts for a
total of #11.7m. They own residential property let predominantly on assured
tenancy and assured short-hold tenancies for the purpose of sheltered housing.
Tamaris trio
TAMARIS has entered into operating leases in respect of three new,
purpose-built nursing homes, bringing the total number of homes under its
management to 15.
Lockout over
TATE &amp; Lyle's US subsidiary AE Staley announced that union members had voted to
accept the company's latest contract proposal, bringing to an end the 30-month
lockout of union employees at its Decatur plant.
Car scheme
BARR &amp; Wallace Arnold Trust has disposed of its VAG business in Leeds to a
subsidiary of Sytner Group for #1.4m. Part of the site is being let to Sytner
and the rest is being converted into a major used car sales operation.
</TEXT>
