<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Mixed news on business failure rates</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Chris Stone</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651585</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
REPORT
THE annual rate of business failures in the UK in 1995 fell by 5.3% to 41,303
from 43,598 in 1994, according to business information service Dun &amp;
Bradstreet, writes CHRIS STONE.
The drop is considered disappointingly small when compared with the 16.3%
recorded between 1994 and 1993. In Scotland the number of companies going to
the wall actually increased by 22.4%, but the bankruptcy law differs from the
rest of the UK and so no d
irect comparisons can be made.
A breakdown of the Scottish figures shows that at 3388, bankruptcies increased
by 22.8%, while liquidations were up 19.8% at 704, still the biggest percentage
increase apart from London. Overall, business failures in Scotland accounted
for 9.9% of the UK
total.
For all of Britain there was a 4.6% increase in larger company liquidations
(from 16,335 to 17,280), the first rise for three years. More than 6000 larger
companies in London were liquidated compared to 4700 in 1994, an increase of
28%. This upsurge was l
argely compensated for by a 20% decrease in smaller business bankruptcies. But,
overall, business failures in London grew by 14%.
Dun &amp; Bradstreet's senior analyst Philip Mellor points to ``worrying signs'' in
the figures that liquidations are rising again in Scotland and the North of
England as well as in London. He says that in the past nine months there has
been a rise in company
liquidations in London which has spread to other parts of the UK.
It remains to be seen what impact this will have on smaller companies.
Wales emerges as the area with the biggest decrease in business failures.
During the year they dropped by 19% and there were also big falls in South-west
England (18.5%) and South-east England (16.6%).
</TEXT>
