<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>25 years ago today the Copland Road end erupted in joy as Rangers equalised in the Old Firm match. . . How I gave up ticket to tragedy terracing</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jack  Webster</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651586</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NATURE gives little warning of the tragedies which unfold before our
disbelieving eyes. Yet, in the course of that Rangers-Celtic match at Ibrox
Park on the fateful day 25 years ago, I did experience a strange shiver which I
was later to put down to premo
nition.
No hint of it could be found, however, as the 80,000 people streamed towards
the Rangers ground on what I described at the time as ``a fine afternoon of
winter-red sun, always threatened by the haze which would eventually close in
around four o'clock.''
What else would happen before the twilight hour was still in the lap of the
gods.
I had made my way to Ibrox that day, partly in the hope of seeing a good
football match (neutrals actually did such things in bygone days) and partly
with the vested interest of an Aberdeen supporter, whose team was then at the
top of the league.
As reigning Scottish Cup holders, the Dons were being hotly pursued in the
league by the reigning champions, Celtic, then in the midstream of their
phenomenal run under the great Jock Stein.
Rangers' championship hopes that year were pretty remote but, as always, a
victory over Celtic would make the perfect start to 1971.
Without a ticket for the all-ticket match, I knew I had to get there early if I
were to pick up a spare. Parking the car half-a-mile away, I walked briskly
towards the red-bricked facade of Ibrox, arriving just after two o'clock.
For an occasion which was hailed in the official programme that day as ``the
greatest club game in the world'', I remember being surprised by an incredible
hush for that time of the afternoon.
Belatedly, however, the atmosphere did build up, generating that pre-match
electricity as players and well-known personalities rolled in for the game,
exchanging New Year greetings and craning necks in search of friends who had
tickets to collect.
I looked for the spare voucher and landed lucky at 2.45pm. Someone's friend had
not turned up and he could sell his ticket - for what was to become the
disaster end of the terracing, adjacent to Copland Road. Gate 13.
I paid him the six shillings (30p today) and hurried towards the fatal
passageway. But the gods were on my side.
Halfway there, I bumped into fellow-journalist Bill Aitken, who was duty
reporter for the Sunday Express that day, poised for any news stories which may
arise. Bill must have been the only man around Ibrox with a spare grandstand
ticket.
I gladly accepted it and soon found a willing buyer for my terracing ticket.
The man was delighted. I shall never know if I sold him a ticket to tragedy.
As I took my place at the right-hand end of the main stand, I was looking
directly across towards the corner of the terracing where I might have been. It
was in that traditionally Rangers end of the ground that death would soon run
riot.
For the moment, however, this ``greatest club game in the world'' was simply a
desperate struggle for pride as well as points. It was one of the best-behaved
Old Firm crowds I could remember, except for one particularly nasty chant which
stuck in my mind
for ever after.
In the fading light of half-time, the floodlights came filtering through in a
blue and ghostly shimmer. It was then I had one of those strange feelings. A
premonition? A journalist's hunch?
I was there as a paying spectator but journalists are a bit like policemen -
once a journalist, always a journalist. I remember consciously asking myself
if, in the event of something happening here today, I had taken in enough of
the atmosphere to write
about it.
So I quietly absorbed the vibrations of the scene around me. As the game neared
its end, Celtic were leading 1-0 and that seemed like the final score. I
decided to leave shortly before the end and was outside the ground just in time
to hear the almighty r
oar which almost certainly meant one thing only - Rangers had equalised with
the last kick of the match.
The mist which had dimmed the glorious horizon and lost us the crescent moon
also magnified that roar of ecstasy.
It was the moment when disaster struck. Rangers fans already descending
Stairway 13 turned back, seeking to glimpse their unexpected moment of triumph.
In the cross-currents of congestion, the crowd collapsed like a pack of cards.
In those circumstances, death comes quietly, so much so that most people were
home by their television sets before they knew anything had happened.
That the tragedy of Ibrox had claimed 66 lives in the arena where we had spent
the previous two hours - and that we had managed to walk away from it in total
ignorance - was a bewilderment which stunned us into silence.
At 4.40 that afternoon, the world had still seemed a place for the exuberance
of life. It took only seconds for the hush and the horror of death to descend.
</TEXT>
