<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000098</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000098</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Family mourns brother lost at match</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651587</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE brother of Mr John Buchanan, a father-of-three killed on Stairway 13, told
this week of the long-term effects his brother's death has had on the family,
Iain Wilson writes.
Mr Billy Buchanan was 21 when his brother John, then 31, was killed. He said:
``I do not think my mother has ever recovered from what happened that day.''
Of his own feelings, he said: ``I am fine.'' However, he said this time of year
was a particularly emotional one for his family, whose thoughts were with John.
The brothers had attended the game separately, mixing with their own friends.
Billy, who was on Stairway 12, left 10 minutes before the end.
``At the time, I was living in Springburn,'' Billy said. ``I left before
Rangers scored. I did not know anything had happened until I was at home and my
wife said she had heard something on television.
``I went round to my parents' house. We were told later that John was involved.
It is something I do not like talking about. I stayed with my parents all that
night, then visited his wife and children the next day.''
Mr Buchanan, a plater now living in Cumbernauld, said he had lost contact with
his late brother's children.
He welcomed Rangers' recently announced plan for a memorial to the victims.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000099</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000099</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The early exit that may have saved his life</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651588</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TRAGEDY brushed Donald McInnes and the hundreds like him who left Ibrox
minutes, even seconds, before the fateful goal that led to death. Like many
others, he still wonders what would have happened to him had he stayed on.
The 19-year-old's home was just a five-minute walk from the stadium. It was
from there that he first heard the sirens.
A sixth sense told him that something dreadful was happening, perhaps a fire.
Thoughts then turned to the friends he had left behind on Stairway 13. Such
were the times, he thought that running, pitched battles had erupted in and
around the stadium.
Mr McInness left his McLellan Street flat and headed back to the ground where,
unknown to him, a colleague from the Rolls-Royce plant at Hillington lay dead.
He said: ``They always opened the gates 15 minutes from the end. With three
minutes to go, I remember saying goodbye to my friends and leaving with others
to escape Celtic's celebrations at the final whistle.
``I was about 100 yards away, walking down Edmiston Drive, when I heard a roar
and thought the game was over. At home, I heard on TV that Rangers had
equalised. There was no mention of a disaster.
``Then I heard the sirens. They were everywhere, coming from every direction.
``I walked back to Ibrox. People were milling about but no-one knew anything
about what was happening. That's my abiding memory - hundreds of people not
knowing what was going on.
``At Harrison Drive, I was stopped, pushed back by supporters who were coming
out the gates. They kept saying, `Don't go back, don't go in there.' At the
same time, the police were trying to get in.
``I remember it was black. There were no cordons. I remember the police,
running, in their black coats, and ambulancemen with their little haversacks
and dark suits.
``Then came the snippets; there had been an accident. No-one spoke of a
disaster. I tried to get in to find my pals. I had to find them, that was my
main concern. But I couldn't get in.''
He waited what seemed an eternity, like many others standing on garden walls in
Harrison Drive, hoping to catch a glimpse of his friends. Back home, a
broadcast spoke of deaths and, hours later, he finally tracked down his
friends. It wasn't until the nex
t day that the scale of the disaster became known.
Mr McInness, of Mosspark Drive, Glasgow, is now 44, is married with two
children aged 15 and 11, and is still with Rolls-Royce, as a turner.
He said of the disaster: ``I try not to dwell on it, but even now I sometimes
think `what if I'd stayed on?' I just put it down to luck that I didn't.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000100</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000100</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bradford, Heysel, and the horrific lesson of Hillsborough</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEITH SINCLAIR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651589</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THREE more recent football stadium disasters, probably etched indelibly in the
memories of all sports fans, were at the City Ground in Bradford, the Heysel
Stadium in Brussels, and Hillsborough in Sheffield.
The omnipresence of television cameras at major sporting events has ensured
that thoughts of each one conjure up vivid and horrific images - of people
fleeing a massive wooden stand ablaze at Bradford, of mindless fans rioting on
the terraces of the Heyse
l Stadium and of the contorted faces of supporters being squashed and
suffocated against a perimeter fence at Hillsborough.
The fire at Bradford City's Valley Parade ground on May 11, 1985, resulted in
the deaths of 56 people.
A judicial inquiry chaired by Mr Justice Popplewell heard that it was almost
certainly started by a lighted cigarette dropped accidentally through a gap
underneath the seating in part of the main stand, where debris had collected
for at least 17 years.
The fire spread with devastating speed to engulf the wooden stand - built in
1909 - where about 4000 people had been among a crowd watching a match between
Bradford City and Lincoln City.
The Bradford football fire inquest returned verdicts of death by misadventure
in July 1985 on all 56 victims of the tragedy and agreed with the interim
Popplewell report that the cause was a dropped cigarette end, cigar butt or
lighted match.
Tough measures to enforce safety standards at sports grounds - including the
requirement of safety certificates to be issued by local authorities for stands
accommodating more than 500 people - came into operation at the beginning of
1989 as part of Gover
nment action taken in the wake of the Bradford fire.
Just 18 days after the fire, 38 people were killed and 454 were injured in the
Heysel Stadium disaster in Brussels on May 29, 1985, when rioting erupted
before the European Cup final between Liverpool and the Italian champions,
Juventus.
The tragedy, which came as violence in English football had started to
escalate, occurred when two sets of rival fans found themselves beside each
other on the terraces at the north end of the stadium.
Accounts varied of what happened but bottles and lumps of concrete started to
fly, mainly from Liverpool fans, an hour before the match was due to start.
As the Juventus fans fled the hail of projectiles, the wall of one section of
the terrace collapsed and the English fans later broke down and moved across a
fence, charging at the Italian fans.
The Italian section in front of the charging English cascaded down the terrace,
like ``a swirling river of bodies'', according to one witness, and scores of
people were crushed to death.
In the immediate aftermath of the disaster, few people had any doubt that the
Liverpool fans were to blame but inadequate ticket allocation was also cited as
a factor.
In addition, blame was apportioned to the state of the stadium. A report by the
Institution of Civil Engineers said the 38 people would not have died had the
``crumbling and decrepit stadium been kept in a state of decent repair''.
The report also said the local authority-owned stadium broke all European
safety rules and ignored the lessons of Ibrox Park, where 66 people died in
``very similar circumstances'' in 1971.
It said that many people would have survived if the 55-year-old crush barriers
at Heysel had been replaced.
The Belgian Government issued safety guidelines for sports grounds one year
after the riots. It called for immediate action to improve the construction of
stadiums, to segregate rival supporters, and to better co-ordinate police
forces.
UEFA, European football's governing body, quickly took punitive action against
English football teams in the wake of the disaster, imposing an unprecedented
ban from European competition.
Britain's worst sporting tragedy occured at Sheffield Wednesday's Hillsborough
ground on April 15, 1989, when 95 people died at an FA Cup semi-final between
Liverpool and Nottingham Forest.
Many of the victims were crushed against fencing in the Leppings Lane end of
the stadium - which had been reserved for Liverpool fans - as latecomers surged
in from the back.
The death toll rose to 96 four years after the tragedy, in March 1993, when
Tony Bland, a 22-year-old Liverpool fan, died in hospital after his parents won
a court ruling allowing life-support systems to be switched off.
Lord Justice Taylor, who chaired a wide-ranging investigation into the tragedy,
said the immediate cause of the disaster was the failure to cut off access to
the already overfull central pens at the Leppings Lane end of the ground when
police opened an em
ergency exit to relieve the crush outside.
In a damning indictment, he also criticised South Yorkshire police and the
Sheffield Wednesday club and said no attempt was made to steer away from the
crowded pens the fans pouring into the stadium, no safe maximum capacities had
been laid down, and ther
e was no effective monitoring of crowd density.
Barriers in the pens were inadequate, with one collapsing, and a ``lack of
vigilant monitoring caused a sluggish reaction and response when the crush
occurred''.
The Taylor report, published in January 1990, also pointed to old grounds, poor
facilities, the ``scourge'' of hooliganism, and ``poor leadership'' as features
which ``disfigured'' football.
It said ``vision and imagination'' was required to achieve what Lord Justice
Taylor called a new ethos for the sport.
His main recommendation to improve safety and combat hooliganism was the
introduction of all-seater stadiums at every football league ground.
Lord Justice Taylor said there was no panacea to achieve total safety and cure
behaviour problems at football matches but added that he was satisfied that
``seating does more to achieve those objectives than any other single
measure''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000101</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000101</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sense of shock and disbelief that lingers with supporters</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD R FINDLAY QC Vice-chairman, Rangers FC</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651590</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WITH just over five minutes of the game remaining, my two friends and I decided
that we had had enough. Rangers were not going to score if they played all day.
Losing to Celtic was a bad way to start the year but at least it was only
one-nil.
We trudged rather than walked back to the car and, as we drove off towards
Dundee, we did not even bother to switch on the radio. Silence and grief always
seem appropriate companions.
Eventually, the sense of solitude got to me and I turned on the news. To our
communal delight, the gloom was instantly lifted. Somehow Colin Stein had
managed to equalise. The game had ended in a draw.
The euphoria was short-lived. I had to tell my two companions to be quiet.
There was more news from Ibrox - the like of which I had never heard before and
hope never to hear again.
There had been some kind of major accident at the stadium. People were dead.
Throughout the whole journey home, there were constant bulletins, each bringing
graver news. The death toll steadily rose. I can still remember the
overwhelming sense of shock an
d disbelief. After all, it was only a game. None of us could think of anything
worthy of saying. At times silence and grief are necessary companions.
It was January 2, 1971, and by five minutes I had failed to witness the Ibrox
Disaster and the death of 66 of my fellow Rangers supporters.
The next day revealed that, after the equaliser, some of the crowd leaving by
stairway 13 had turned and tried to return to the ground. In the resultant
crush, people tripped and fell, barriers collapsed, and the tragedy gathered
its own momentum. I will
always remember the horrific but deeply moving photographs of the dead lying in
a row beside the pitch. It could not be true, but it was.
Rangers were represented at the funerals of all those who died.
However, this sharing of grief was not enough. The Rangers board knew that such
an event must never be allowed to happen again. Football had to leave the dark
ages which were taken for granted by so many in the game. Ibrox was to be
changed once and for a
ll. The old terraces would go and be replaced by a modern, safe, all-seated
stadium.
The main driving force was the late Willie Waddell, who travelled Europe in
search of a model for the new Ibrox. When he visited the Westfalionstadion in
Dortmund, he found his inspiration and so the work of reconstruction began.
When I joined the Rangers
board, I was privileged to get to know ``The Deedle''. A man of great strength
of character and kindness, his love of football, but more particularly Rangers
FC, made a lasting impression on me.
The prospect of a seated stadium nowadays does not in any way seem unusual.
Indeed, it is the norm. Yet all these years ago it was an innovation of
staggering proportions. This was long before the events at Bradford and
Hillsborough and the Taylor Report
which introduced compulsory new safety standards - and seats. Rangers found
their plans being met with opposition and ridicule.
Supporters did not want to sit at matches. You could provide seats but no-one
would use them. People liked being out in the wind and rain. Rangers persisted
and gradually the new stadium emerged and grew into the magnificent venue it
now is. Not that it w
as easy.
Rangers found, as many have since, that the cost of building a ground and
having a successful team can be mutually exclusive. After completion of one of
the phases, I remember that one of the jokes doing the rounds was that the club
was to sue the archite
cts as they had built the stand facing the pitch. There was a fire at Ibrox and
when the cry of ``Save the Cups'' went up, everyone ran to the canteen.
The vision of Waddell and his colleagues went beyond simply providing a safe
environment. It was about treating people with respect and in a civilised
manner - providing a degree of comfort and cover from the weather, food that
was edible, and toilets tha
t did not cause offence. The image of supporters standing in the pouring rain,
munching on a soggy pie, drinking cold Bovril, and running the risk of being
urinated upon, seems virtually barbaric. Yet, not so long ago, that was
Scottish football.
Other events brought dramatic changes to our national game.
The Scottish Cup Final of 1980 between Rangers and Celtic ended with a riot on
the pitch (involving the supporters, it must be stressed) and police horses
charging the rival factions. Drunkenness was blamed and this led to the
Criminal Justice (Scotland)
Act 1980, banning alcohol from grounds and making it an offence to attempt to
get into a football match while under the influence of drink.
Football had indeed changed - irrevocably - but for the better. Rangers had led
the way and yet the real tragedy is that many more lives had to be lost south
of the Border before others would follow that lead. Would they have done so but
for the Taylor Re
port? Eventually, I suspect, but clubs and administrators were far too
complacent. The notion that football supporters would turn up in vast numbers
and tolerate whatever conditions were provided for them, was clung on to by
many. Safety was taken too muc
h for granted. Comfort was expensive to provide.
Twenty-five years on, those who paid such a price on that awful day would not
recognise the place where they died nor the game which cost them their lives.
Modern stadiums are safe, comfortable, civilised places. Supporters, too, have
changed. The old loy
alties, the choruses and songs may still be there, but the vast majority of
fans are intolerant of trouble, drunkenness, racist chants, and the like. Treat
people like pigs and they will behave as such. Treat them with respect and they
will react accordin
gly.
The ceremony of the Loving Cup is performed at Ibrox at the first home game of
every new year. The directors of Rangers and the visiting team gather in the
Blue Room and drink the health of the reigning sovereign in memory of the men
who died in a disaste
r at Holditch Colliery in the Potteries. After that tragedy, Rangers played a
friendly against Stoke City to raise money for their families. The president of
Stoke presented the cup to the Ibrox club. In recent years, it has become the
tradition to rememb
er those who died that January day.
Twenty-five years has for me passed very quickly. Not so, I suspect, those left
behind with the memory of their loved ones leaving for a football match, never
to return. Their memory is always with those of us who love this club of which
I am but an insig
nificant party. I hope they will think it fitting that the magnificent Ibrox
Stadium started by Willie Waddell and his colleagues, and soon to be completed
by my friend and chairman, David Murray, stands as a permanent memorial to them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000102</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000102</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651591</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
`Three seconds
to live' under
pile of bodies
JIM Harris was told by doctors he would have been dead in another three seconds
and that the haemorrhaging he suffered was seen only in corpses.
The 18-year-old apprentice mechanic spent more than an hour trapped, crushed,
and suffocating between the dead bodies below and people piled six high above
him.
Injuries included a fractured pelvis, crushed ribs, fractures to both legs, a
dislocated ankle, and haemorrhaging from his eyes and ears.
However, the teenager felt no pain and, soon after his arrival at the Southern
General Hospital, he walked out. Hours later, he turned up at his home in
Lenzie, with no idea of how he had got there.
Today, Mr Harris is a 43-year-old fireman, married with three children. He is
appreciative of life and has put the disaster in perspective, although he often
thinks of a friend, just 16, who did not survive.
Mr Harris, now of Muirside Avenue, Kirkintilloch, had gone to the match after
winning two tickets in a supporters' club ballot.
He had tried to leave early and had reached the top of Stairway 13, overlooking
the exit, when there was a roar for the Rangers' equaliser.
There was a tremendous crush as people in front of him tried to return to the
terracing. Unbearable pressure followed, then people began to fall.
He was swept downwards, halted only by a wall of bodies.
Others fell on top of him and he lost consciousness - but not before a
near-death experience: ``They talk about life flashing in front of you. It is
true. It was like a quick re-run of a movie,'' he said.
When he came to, his arms were pinned and breathing was near impossible but he
heard a policeman say: ``This one's still alive.''
To this day, Mr Harris has nurtured an ambition to meet the sergeant who
battled for more than an hour to save his life. The unidentified officer, after
grabbing his hair and trying to pull him clear, ensured he would not suffocate
by pulling countless bo
dies away.
He cannot explain why he wandered away from hospital and only recalls turning
up at his home, which was filled with worried relatives, at about 11pm.
``My father was out at the coal bunker when I appeared like an apparition,
looking like someone out of a Dracula movie. There was blood coming from my
eyes and ears.
``A GP was called and he was horrified. He took one look, and my pulse, before
sending me to Stobhill Hospital, where I spent about eight weeks.
Mr Harris said he had seen some horrific sights as a fireman but nothing that
compared with the scale of the Ibrox tragedy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000103</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000103</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Stairway warning</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Iain Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651592</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE jury at the fatal accident inquiry produced a probable cause for the 66
deaths, Iain Wilson writes.
They warned that more deaths or injuries could be expected on the stairway if
it was left in its present form and a closely packed crowd of people was
allowed to descend.
That finding, after a seven-day inquiry held in Glasgow in February, 1971, was
the nearest the jury came to accepting a recommendation by counsel for
relatives of the deceased that blame for the disaster should be placed on the
Rangers board.
Mr Charles Macarthur QC suggested that the Rangers directors had been engaged
in a game of ``pass the parcel'' after three accidents on the same stairway.
In his closing speech, Mr Macarthur told the jury of four men and three women
that some of the blame must lie at the door of Rangers because no-one seemed to
have done anything about suggestions made about the stairway after an accident
in 1969, the third
in eight years.
Mr W R Grieve QC, representing Rangers, said the club had no desire to shirk
responsibilities regarding provision for spectators at Ibrox. He said directors
were determined that there would not be a repeat of the accident.
He urged the jury to consider the evidence in its proper perspective. It did
not require much imagination to find the effective cause of the disaster.
Someone must have fallen.
Sir Allan Walker QC, the sheriff who presided at the inquiry, told the jury he
did not feel they should make any reference to fault or negligence in their
verdict. However, they might feel they had a duty to prevent such a tragedy
happening again.
The jury recommended that a reduction of numbers using the stairway was a
matter of expert advice. They added that similar advice should be sought on
methods of exit from all football grounds.
They found the accident probably occurred because one or more persons fell or
collapsed on the stairway when those descending were packed closely together -
and were being pushed downwards by the pressure of those above and behind them.
That downward pressure forced others to fall or collapse on to those who had
fallen first. As the pressure continued, more and more people were heaped upon
those who had fallen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000104</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000104</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Clubs united after the saddest day</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651593</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish sports media was about to hail events at Ibrox on January 2, 1971,
as one of the most sporting Old Firm matches, both on and off the field, for
years. Only two arrests - both for drunkenness - were recorded from a crowd of
80,000 and the matc
h itself, handled well by referee Bill Anderson, was almost incident free.
The game, which had been played in a good spirit on a bone-hard pitch, was
heading for a no-scoring draw but, with a minute left, a Bobby Lennox shot came
off the bar and little Jimmy Johnstone was first to react, heading the ball
home to give Celtic the
lead.
Thousands of Rangers fans, thinking that the game was lost, began heading for
the exits but, with just 15 seconds remaining, Rangers were awarded a free kick
for a foul by Celtic full-back Jim Craig. Dave Smith sent the ball into the
penalty area and, as
it bobbed about, Colin Stein stepped in to score the equaliser.
Rangers fans who were on their way down the steep stairs turned and tried to
make their way back up to join in the celebrations - and the tragedy began.
Twenty-five years on, people are still affected by what happened, including the
club captains of that era, Rangers' John Greig and Billy McNeill, of Celtic,
who missed playing in the fateful match, because of injury.
Greig, who is now public relations executive of Rangers, said: ``I have been
involved with Rangers for around 35 years and, irrespective of everything I
have been through, it is the saddest day I can remember - undoubtedly the most
traumatic day in my car
eer. It is something I would never want to go through again and something I
hope nobody ever has to experience again. The sheer enormity of the disaster
gutted everyone at the club.
``I remember a few days afterwards we had a meeting in the dressing room and
Willie Waddell wanted every funeral covered. Everyone at the club had to muck
in.
``I also remember visiting the homes of fans who had lost their lives.
``It is something you never forget and there was an unreal atmosphere about
Ibrox for a long time afterwards. Not one of us connected with the club was
unaffected.''
Billy McNeill said: ``I was injured but watched the match. Obviously we didn't
know anything had happened, for on the final whistle we all headed to the
dressing room. I remember our club doctor, John Fitzimmons, coming in and
taking Neilly Mochan and Jim
my Steel away. It was then we realised something was wrong but we were kept in
the dressing room and the first we heard of the enormity of what had happened
was on the radio on the team bus taking us back to Parkhead.
``It was a real dismal journey back to our ground, although a short one. We
were all shocked by what we had heard.
``I don't think Neilly Mochan ever got over it, because he was heavily involved
in trying to help those poor people who were caught up in the accident. Years
later, Neilly still talked to me about that terrible day.
``In the weeks that followed, there was a strong unity between the clubs - a
combined effort to do all that we could. Of course, the Rangers lads were
affected much more, because they had met some of the people who had lost their
lives, even knew some of
them.
``I can well remember the very moving service at Glasgow Cathedral some time
afterwards - we participated in things like that.''
The teams that day were:
RANGERS - Neef, Jardine, Matheson, Greig, McKinnon, Jackson, Henderson, Conn,
Johnstone, Smith, Stein. Substitute: MacDonald.
CELTIC - Williams, Craig, Gemmell, Brogan, Connelly, Hay, Johnstone, Hood,
Wallace, Callaghan, Lennox. Substitute: Macari.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000105</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000105</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Young policeman thought a brawl had broken out</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES FREEMAN Home Affairs Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651594</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS Gordon McLelland stood on Stairway 13 in the immediate aftermath of the
tragedy, a fog of disbelief, a feeling of total unreality, descended.
He was only 19, with a meagre 10 months' service with City of Glasgow Police.
Yet he had just witnessed and been involved in one of the most appalling
tragedies to be visited on the city.
Now 44 and a uniformed sergeant with Strathclyde Police, with 20 of his 25
years' service in the CID, Mr McLelland still has vivid memories of January 2,
1971.
One of the strongest impressions that remains with him was that people were
fighting, lashing out at each other. What he was witnessing was in fact people
fighting for their lives, faces contorted in panic rather than in anger.
Also vividly etched in his mind's eye is the attempt to reach over railings and
extract people who were obviously being crushed, only to watch them die in
front of his eyes.
He was one of many officers inside Ibrox that fateful day with the specific
task of monitoring the spectators leaving the ground via Stairway 13.
His position, which he recollects clearly, was on a grassed area to the left of
the stairway. He was in place 15 minutes before the final whistle was due.
Shortly before this, spectators began leaving, pouring down the stairway.
Everything was normal until the roar went up from inside the ground. Mr
McLelland knows with hindsight exactly what happened but in these few seconds
he was aware only that somethin
g terribly wrong was taking place and that there was a clear impression of
fighting.
``It was very difficult at first to take it in,'' he said. ``The stairway was
packed with people of all ages and there was no immediate reason for fighting.
There was total chaos. My immediate reaction was to run to a marked police
vehicle which was parke
d in Cairnlea Drive. I shouted to the officers in the vehicle to radio for
immediate assistance and then ran back to the stairway.
``I realised that many people were trapped about a third of the way up. Many of
them had fallen. The sheer pressure of hundreds of people further up, who
obviously had no idea what had happened below them, meant that more and more
people were being crushe
d where they stood.
``By this time, there were numerous other police officers at the stairway.
Along with members of the crowd, we were trying to pull people free.
``I recall actually getting one young boy, probably about 16, out of the crush
and it was obvious he had stopped breathing. I had been involved in competitive
swimming and lifesaving competitions so I had been trained in resuscitation
techniques. I starte
d mouth-to-mouth resuscitation and external heart massage as I had been taught.
``I remember thinking at the time that I should keep on doing so until a doctor
or a qualified person pronounced the casualty to be dead.
``I kept on doing so until a doctor reached me and told me it was hopeless,
that the boy was dead.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000106</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000106</DOCID>
