<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000108</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000108</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>EU nothing like Hitler's plan</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651597</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DAVID Rowan Henderson characterises the European Union as the kind of hegemony
planned by Hitler and other European Fascists (December 23).
But what allowed these Fascists to come to power? It was the breakdown of the
European financial system - in which Britain willingly participated - due in
turn to the complete absence of any common financial policy.
To this were added the crippling reparations demanded of Germany by the Allies
after the First World War, hardly a united European policy itself.
Then came the starvation, the social unrest; and only then the fundamentalist
politicians of the left and the right became believable.
A union of European trade and finance would have made it impossible for an
opportunist ex-corporal to put a pistol to the world's head. But he was able to
step straight into the vacuum left in Europe by the collapse of the
Austro-Hungarian Empire.
Mr Henderson alludes to his war service. I hope he will forgive me for pointing
out that he suffered greatly at the hands of the Japanese in the course of
this. But he has put this behind him and knows that the blame does not lie with
the Japanese people,
in whose culture, I believe, he is interested.
Strange that he is unable to reach the same accommodation with his nearer
European neighbours.
J H Brindle,
16 Toberonochy,
Isle of Luing,
Oban.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Having trouble with carols</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651598</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROFESSOR Steve Bruce has proved that Scrooge is still alive and as ill as ever
(December 23).
At a time when there are more Christian believers in the world than at any time
in the history of our faith he says that there are not many of us.
Certainly he claims to be speaking for Scotland, but the fact that 14% of
Scottish adults were sitting in pews on an unheralded Sunday in 1994 is far
from being the whole story.
He adds, without the slightest evidence, that perhaps a further 20% believe in
a personal God. That figure could just as easily be 60%. That would get much
closer, with the 14%, to the 80% who have been reported as claiming belief in
God.
He has trouble with carols. He's not alone on that. The bleak midwinter, though
true of Scotland this year, is not true of all Christians' Christmases. But
Jesus Christ is.
That he was born and lived and died and was raised from death is my belief. It
is also well attested by contemporary records. It is therefore the one truth
about my world that transcends all the hype of modern media and even Professor
Bruce's Scrooge-like
opinions.
I remain one of those clergymen who hope that his annual visit to Church might
prompt a more enduring response. What I'm not is poor.
My riches are my convictions about the Christ who, for me and millions like me,
demonstrated in his own person that love did come down at Christmas, love all
lovely, love divine; and that, praise be, we are all the better for that love.
Professor Bruce is entitled to take his atheism seriously. He is not entitled
to assume that any particular percentage of his fellow-citizens join him in
voting for Scrooge.
He overstates his weight. One look at the sheer enjoyment, faith, and love on
the faces of the people I greeted at our midnight celebration on Christmas Eve
might jolt his dyspeptic unbelief into an infectious faith.
Such a faith would be suitable for children, yes; but also for those adults who
still want to learn how to love.
Perhaps Professsor Bruce would do us a service by composing a new, more honest
carol. I would be interested to read it, and even to sing it, provided that it
honours the Child in the Manger.
Rev Maxwell Craig,
Scottish Churches House,
Dunblane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000110</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000110</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Misplaced blame for declining numbers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651599</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONCE again a minister of the Church of Scotland, the Rev Ivor Gibson, seeks to
lay the blame for the decline in membership outwith the life of the church
itself, saying: ``There is an appalling ignorance of the Christian message
thanks largely to the fail
ure of Religious Education in schools, the collapse of Sunday school, and the
lack of church going'' (December 27).
It may well be the task of Sunday school to make Christians, and it might be
more effective in this task if it stopped recruiting young people who have not
yet worked out their own faith and using them as Sunday school teachers because
no-one else wants t
he responsibility.
It most certainly is the task of church members to bring people to the church,
and hopefully into the faith of the church. They might be more effective in
this if they stopped thinking faith was a private and personal matter.
It is not, and has never been, the task of Religious Education to make
Christians. Religious Education seeks to help pupils find meaning and purpose
in life, and to understand the contribution of the various religions to this
search.
This does not mean indoctrination or evangelism within the classroom, but an
open educational search. It seeks to equip pupils with the tools for the task
and the knowledge and understanding to help in the search.
Pupils are very aware of the valuable contribution that Christianity makes to
this search. They are aware of the words and the challenges of Jesus and the
claims of the church. Sadly they are also aware of the lives of many Christians
whom they meet in th
eir day-to-day lives. So often the two do not correspond.
Christianity for many of them seems to say one thing and the actions of
Christians another. Once these two are in harmony, the church might play a more
active role in the search for meaning and purpose in the lives of young people.
Rev T R Taylor,
Principal Teacher Religious Education,
8 Moray Place, Kirkintilloch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000111</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000111</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tory survival Time may be running out</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651600</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government which already boasts a thin majority over all other parties is
likely to see it shrink further; and could find itself a minority
administration early next year. Actuaries and other statisticians having been
making confident predictions to t
hat effect, and there seems little reason to doubt their accuracy. The
end-of-term lectures to their colleagues from Dr Mawhinney and Mr Heseltine are
justified in their own terms: parties which insist on public quarrels and
formal splits on important vot
es invite rejection. In spite of an improving economic performance nationally,
that rejection has been firmly fixed on the Tories. It is their own fault, but
has been made even more threatening for them by the simultaneous regard public
opinion still best
ows on Mr Blair. That might not have many short-term implications for a
Government with a secure majority but Mr Major, though he stacked up an
impressive popular vote in 1992, did not manage to translate it into an
unassailable lead in seats.
The electoral arithmetic is relentless. The Tories have not won a by-elecion
since 1989, and no majority, no matter how large, seems to confer a degree of
protection. One by-election is now pending in a Tory-held seat (because of the
former member's death
) and one is threatened (because a sitting member may be facing bankruptcy):
early in the new year Mr Major could be grappling with as small a majority as
Harold Wilson in 1964 but without the favourable electoral trend which allowed
Wilson to go to the c
ountry in the confident expectation of the victory he duly received in 1966.
The experience of the 64 Wilson administration shows that it is possible to
retain office with a small majority; and Mr Callaghan managed, while in a
minority, to hang on to powe
r for months by cleverly manipulating the small parties which are also a
feature of the present Parliament. Time may indeed be running out for the
Tories but their minority, should it materialise, will be under all other
parties combined: their present ma
jority over Labour by itself is a comfortable 55.
The Government has the advantage of retaining the political initiative and Mr
Forsyth's Christmas message to Scots shows how that can be used in commendable
ways which are bound to evoke support across a wide spectrum of political
opinion. It can also be
used in more narrowly partisan ways, through the budgetary mechanism, for
example, to enhance disposable incomes, which outcome ought also to be within
its grasp through reduced interest rates. But these moves need time to shift
opinion and there is littl
e evidence from opinion surveys that they can still actually do so, since
opinion seems to have set in a mould unfavourable to Tory hopes. They may,
after all, have the time to test the permanence of that mould both from the
problem the small parties pres
ent to an Opposition trying to unite them in the same parliamentary lobby, and
from the fact that the Ulster Unionists retain their Conservative identity, and
are there to be wooed. The memory of Lord Carson remains green for both
groupings, and with it i
s the fact that a Labour Government would be far more hostile to the Unionists'
ambitions. The question is whether the Unionists might ask too high a price for
the national interest to bear. But then Governments will pay a lot to ensure
their own survival
.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000112</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000112</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Getting the picture SNP moves to assist film industry</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651601</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish National Party has been accused, with some justification, of
exploiting the Braveheart factor in using the popularity of the Mel Gibson
quasi-historical movie epic to stir up patriotic fervour for the nationalist
cause. None the less audience
reaction to the film is rather different in Manchester from the response in
Motherwell and it has probably done the cause no harm. So it is appropriate
that the SNP should return the compliment by proposing moves to assist the
indigenous film industry. T
hat there is nothing radical or astonishing about those proposals should not
surprise us. This is familiar footage and the few crucial steps that are needed
to prevent our film industry being forever described as ``fledgling'' are well
known. The chief an
d most frequently requested move is for tax incentives for investors in film to
parallel those available in Ireland - in contrast to the present situation
where, as the chairman of the Scottish Film Council outlined in Wednesday's
Herald, investors in fil
m are positively discriminated against by comparison with manufacturing
industry.
The competition between Scottish development agencies and those in Ireland for
inward investment from overseas industry has been fiercely contested and
well-documented. It makes no sense whatsoever for the enticement of film making
to Scotland, together w
ith the cash it generates, to be so clearly disadvantaged. Movie-making is set
to overtake the aircraft industry as America's largest foreign currency earner.
There would be a deafening political outcry if Scotland was seen to be fighting
with one arm tie
d behind its back with a jet assembly plant at stake. The level of increase in
Government support for the film industry which would be required to make a
significant difference to its ability to function as a revenue earner is not
large - and the cost imp
lications of tax breaks are nil if film-makers are currently failing to come
here because of the absence of them. Hollywood movies are fantastically
expensive to make and the regular use of Scotland as a location for major
movies would indisputably bring
a great deal of money into the country. That is before any consideration is
made for the impact on the tourist industry and the general promotion of
Scotland overseas that comes as a by-product of appearing on the big screen.
But in common with all branch
es of the media at the end of the twentieth century, there are various scales
of operation in cash terms and a small budget does not mean a reduction in
quality, just a different style of product. As Shallow Grave proved, a
low-budget movie can still have
panache, and has less to do at the box office before it begins to repay its
backers handsomely.
Beyond cash generation, of course, there is the question of jobs. Research
published this month by the Scottish Arts Council has shown that we cannot take
the attitude that artistic endeavours operate at the periphery of the
employment statistics. An anal
ysis of the 1991 census showed that the cultural industries employed as many
people as oil and gas extraction or insurance. Scotland's share of national
employment in film production, distribution, and exhibition is an eminently
improvable 4% in an indust
ry that is concentrated in and around London, but the quality of the freelance
workforce dividing its time between television, advertisements, and movie
making has often been remarked upon. The erratic nature of the work reflects
the fragmented state of t
he industry, yet it is still possible for some young talents to make the
transition from cheap, fast television to the feature film in a remarkably
short space of time. The SNP's suggestion that the various agencies that
sustain film-making pool their res
ources under one banner can only make that road an easier one to travel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000113</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000113</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Questions after five long nights of the big freeze</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Brian Wilson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651602</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHRISTMAS with the family on the far west of Lewis; a few inches of the white
stuff, lying deep and crisp and even. Snow, sands, and scenery...... A week
ago, it might have sounded idyllic. Next year, I suspect that it will be
difficult to market.
Lewis, I should explain to BBC reporters and the geographically challenged, is
the one in the top left corner of the map. Shetland is up at the top. Our own
outpost in the parish of Uig is marginally closer to Hawick than to Lerwick.
I make this point because it does become a little irritating, as one sits there
by candle-light, to hear ``Shetland and the Western Isles'' linked together as
if they were adjacent suburbs. For reasons which I will come to in a moment, it
is important to
understand that they are not.
The idyll started to crumble last Saturday evening, at some point between
Grandstand and the National Lottery. It was a chilly evening with a moderate
wind blowing. A rapid flurry of snow coated the ground. Nothing serious, but
definitely ominous.
``I suppose the electricity will go off any time now,'' my wife observed. And
verily, the lights flickered and died. The festive television schedules were
rendered redundant. That most generous offer to the little ones - ``why don't
you go and watch a vid
eo'' - was seized from our grasp. And slowly, it started to grow cold.
Now the point of geography. As the days went by, we would hear a lot about 30ft
drifts in Shetland and ``the worst conditions since the Second World War''.
These images have been used by Hydro-Electric's PR people as if they applied to
all the affected ar
eas, hundreds of miles away. In the interests of accuracy, it should be pointed
out that they did not.
I'm not sure what the urban perception of Hebridean living is these days, but I
assure you that it is as much dependent on electricity as anyone else's. Peat
fires and solid fuel stoves are fine, but unless there is power to circulate
the water, the radia
tors quickly cool.
So the four us huddled up in bed until Christmas Eve dawned. I was on the phone
bright and early to the Hydro-Electric information line. A recorded message
told me that they were aware of the loss of supply in a long list of places and
it was expected tha
t ``power will be restored by around mid-day''.
Experience rendered me sceptical of this reassurance, so I accepted the
invitation to stay on the line until a live voice appeared. Its opening gambit
was, as usual, to ask for a postcode, presumably in order to determine whether
or not I was an imposter
pretending to be the victim of a power cut.
Brief cross-examination of a reluctant witness elicited the more realistic
information that (a) they had no idea what the source of the cuts was; (b) they
therefore had no idea of when power would be restored, and (c) a helicopter was
not due to go out lo
oking for lines down until an hour later. This seemed to place the recorded
message in proper perspective.
In fact, the power cut lasted until 1pm yesterday - five long nights later.
After the first 24 hours, Hydro-Electric gave up on predictions about when it
would come back on. By that time, there were genuinely difficult conditions to
work in and I bow to n
obody in my respect for the linesmen and engineers who habitually battle in
atrocious weather to maintain the supply to remote places.
I am, however, less impressed about their employers, the privatised
Hydro-Electric plc, successors to Tom Johnston's great creation, the North of
Scotland Hydro-Electric Board. And it's not just because of their foolish habit
of giving out misinformation
when people need to know what is actually going on.
The fact is that, in many further-flung parts of the Hydro-Electric area -
including the ones hardest hit over the past week - power cuts are extremely
common and do not require extreme weather conditions to precipitate them. Hence
my wife's prescient res
ponse, the moment snow started to fall.
Rightly or wrongly, this is widely attributed to there being fewer locally
based staff since privatisation and an inadequate programme of renewals and
investment. What is undeniable is that the nature of Hydro-Electric plc, as
opposed to its public servic
e predecessor, has changed dramatically.
It is an under-recognised fact that the electricity industry as a whole paid
more to the Treasury in profits before privatisation than it has done since in
taxation. But I doubt if the Hydro Board was expected to make a positive
contribution to that figur
e. Its social remit was recognised.
Last year, in contrast, Hydro-Electric plc made profits of #168.7 for its
shareholders. Increasingly, they see themselves as a national and international
player in generation and distribution, who happen to be based in the North of
Scotland for historical
reasons.
Fair enough. But someone's first priority has to be the pensioners sitting
without electricity for five days, or the small telecom business which cannot
handle the frequency of power cuts. I welcome the fact that Hydro-Electric's
chairman has promised dis
cussions on these issues once the immediate problems are resolved.
I hope they lead to a clear-cut recognition that continuity of electricity
supply, within the bounds of what is humanly possible, is a first-world right
which has been entrusted to a private company in the Highlands and Islands of
Scotland. It cannot be a
variable extra, dependent on how business is going elsewhere.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Earlier plan for a new canal</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651603</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE proposal by the Institute of Engineers and Shipbuilders in Scotland for a
#650m new canal across Central Scotland has been under consideration before
(December 26).
F Mort, in his book, Dumbartonshire (1920) - yes, the title was spelt with an M
- describes plans for a Forth-Clyde Ship Canal. One scheme proposed a line
following the existing canal.
The other suggested beginning at Grangemouth on the Forth passing south of
Stirling and continuing up the Forth valley for several miles.
Coming round the south-west face of the Campsies it followed the Endrick valley
and would enter Loch Lomond near Balmaha.
There were to be two exits to the open seas. One was by means of a canal to be
cut between Tarbet and Arrochar to give access to Loch Long. The other exit
would consist of a canal from Balloch to Dumbarton.
In 1920, at a depth of 36 feet, the estimated cost was #20m.
Harry Worsley,
14 Morar Crescent,
Bishopbriggs,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000115</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000115</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Coins or notes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651604</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
READING Mr Skeoch's letter, I was reminded of some hazards of reducing coin
size. On returning from a holiday in the USA and checking my US currency I
found that I had a Susan B Anthony dollar.
The Susan B Anthony dollar is not very common and that which I have is the only
one I have seen. The possible reason for its unpopularity is that, unlike the
old cartwheel silver dollar, it is easily mistaken for a quarter.
I wonder how many people have lost 75 cents in such errors.
Earlier in the year I purchased two #2 celebration coins from the Post Office.
I then saw in a newspaper advertisement that I could have bought two such
mint-condition coins from an address in England post-free.
Can you purchase coin from the Mint in bulk at a discount, and if so why should
anyone want to pass that saving on to me? These coins are legal tender and it
is not as if they were antique coins selling above their face value.
There is an old saying that if it sounds too good to be true it probably is.
What is the catch?
Chris Parton,
40 Bellshill Road,
Uddingston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Angels of Mercy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651605</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR recent coverage of the Princess of Wales was interesting. I should like to
add that it is time someone pointed out to her that a lot of ordinary women
could also do the Angel of Mercy act that she is so fond of carrying out in
hospitals. It doesn't r
eally require a great deal from one.
What does require a great deal from one is cleaning up after a patient who has
defecated and soiled himself in bed. Let's see her put her fair hand to that
sort of activity.
Jane I Phillips,
Melbourne, Shore Road,
Innellan, by Dunoon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bluenoses</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651606</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BENEDICT Brogan in an otherwise excellent article states that Nova Scotia was
ceded by the French to Britain in 1707 under the Treaty of Utrecht (December
23). In fact the Peace of Utrecht was the name of several treaties following
the Utrecht Congress, 1
713-14.
They were concluded at Rastatt in 1714, thus ending the War of the Spanish
Succession and it was there that Nova Scotia became British territory.
Incidentally, I once heard that the American and Canadian nickname for a Nova
Scotian is ``bluenose'', but I have no idea whether this refers to the climate
or has some other deeper meaning.
David MacPherson,
51 Cresswell Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A defeat for Wallace</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651607</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WAS saddened to read that Glasgow District Council has refused a request to
name streets in a new housing development at Robroyston after William Wallace,
despite the fact that it is adjacent to a monument marking the spot where he
was betrayed.
The council claims that several city thoroughfares bear his name and that a
Glasgow streetfinder lists 11 such streets.
Readers in Rutherglen, Paisley, Clydebank, Johnstone, Blantyre, and Renfrew
must have been left with the impression that the new Glasgow city boundaries
have been extended to include them because six of the streets are in their
areas.
Since the list also includes four Wallacewells (Crescent, Place, Quadrant, and
Road in Balornock), there is only one city thoroughfare called simply Wallace,
that is Wallace Street in Kingston.
The district council's logic is even more questionable given that there are
many more than 11 streets in Glasgow alone with Victoria in them and that
nearly all the streets in Croftfoot begin or end in ``croft''.
A few years ago, in the face of fierce opposition, Glasgow District Council
renamed a city centre square after another nation's freedom-fighter, Nelson
Mandela. Surely it is not too late to commemorate one of our own nation's
freedom-fighters, William Wal
lace.
Colin D G Pennycook,
42 Aytoun Road,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>New York thrill</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651608</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEW York's mayor Rudolph Giullani would have to be crazy to change the system
of hailing cabs in the street (December 27).
The suicidal practice of launching oneself at a cab from wherever one happens
to be standing is one of the thrills of New York.
The thing that did throw me during a visit there a few months ago was the
response, in unintelligible accents, of many drivers when I asked to be taken
somewhere, ``Do you know where it is?''
Harry Diamond,
27f Greenholme Court,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000120</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000120</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Threepenny rush</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651609</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I ENJOYED Frank McGroarty's article on jam jars as currency during the early
decades of the century (December 16). Up to the late forties and early fifties,
the jam jar and bleach bottle still had a monetary value of one halfpenny.
Admission price to La Scala in Airdrie was threepence. The Saturday matinee was
known as the threepenny rush. The whole of Airdrie reverberated to clinking
glass as hordes of working-class weans converged on the cinema next door to a
wee sweetie shop whic
h paid money for jam jars.
Some confectioners operated a kind of scam that was enthusiastically abetted by
young toffee junkies. To buy a bar of toffee, threepence and an E-coupon
snipped from the ration book were necessary, but the use of money for toffee
was by-passed by giving t
wo E-coupons.
To me it was almost mystical, a process that transmuted the base metals of
glass and paper into gold of sweets and hours of entertainment. Even now in my
50s, I still wince when discarding a jeelie jaur.
Jim Cook,
66 Thrushbush Road,
Airdrie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000121</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000121</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Not consulted</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651610</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister and the Archbishop of Canterbury were consulted by the Queen
prior to her letters to the Duke and Duchess of Rothesay (otherwise the Prince
and Princess of Wales) encouraging early divorce.
Does not the absence of consultation with any representative of the Scottish
Establishment - neither layman nor cleric - alert us to the true perception in
London - both Palace and Downing Street - of Scotland's role and import in the
Union?
Neil Bowman,
Newhouse of Balgavies,
Balgavies, Forfar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000122</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000122</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>HOUSING MARKET Nationwide forecasts modest upturn</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS STONE, City Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>21</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651611</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Nationwide Building Society has followed up the Halifax in forecasting an
improvement in the housing market next year. It does not suggest, as did the
Halifax, that 1997 could see a mini-boom, writes CHRIS STONE.
Reporting a ``modest'' fall of 2.5% in the Nationwide House Price Index in 1995
with a slight firming in the underlying trends in house prices since the low
point reached in the summer, Brian Davis, Nationwide's chief executive,
commented: ``Although stil
l tentative, there have been some signs in recent months that the market has at
least stabilised.''
He said the underlying trend in house prices already noted is one factor. In
addition survey evidence from estate agents has been cautiously optimistic
recently and ``this is in accord with our own reading of recent mortgage
lending data, which suggests t
hat the decline in market activity during the first half of 1995 has been
halted.''
Stronger growth in personal incomes, helped by recently announced tax cuts and
a very favourable interest rate environment should provide the conditions
necessary to support an improvement in the market during 1996.
``We believe an increase in transactions of about 10% is possible, and this is
likely to be translated into a modest rise in house prices, of about 3%,'' said
Mr Davis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000123</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000123</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The play's the thing, it's in the fine print</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mark Fisher</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651612</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A COUPLE of months ago I wrote an article on these pages drawing attention to
the dearth of new Scottish plays. I was looking in particular at the autumn
season when no more than three or four original Scottish pieces got anywhere
near the professional st
age. And looking back now across 1995 as a whole, the question is less a matter
of whether a play was any good as whether it was on at all.
Scottish playwrights are a lively and vocal lot, but through no fault of their
own, it seems they're more likely to be known by reputation than by the names
of their plays. You might possibly have heard of David Greig, David Harrower
and Mike Cullen, but
could you also say which of them was responsible for One Way Street, Knives in
Hens and The Collection in 1995?
If John Clifford, Sue Glover and Chris Hannan are three of our leading
playwrights, how can we explain that none of them had original works staged in
Scotland during the year? And if you've heard people banging on about Iain
Heggie, do you find it accepta
ble that to see his first full-length play in five years - An Experienced Woman
Gives Advice with Siobhan Redmond heading up an excellent cast - you had to
travel to Manchester's Royal Exchange for the privilege?
With this in mind, 1995 was a surprisingly good year for the publication of
Scottish scripts. Making it into print is tremendously important both for the
individual playwright and the cultural awareness of society at large. The
printed word has a kind of
authority that the ephemeral world of the stage lacks; a script says this is
the real and valuable work of a real theatre artist, a thing of substance,
worthy of proper consideration. It can reach people who couldn't get to see it
in performance; it can r
each foreign nations and future generations. The play's the thing, of course,
live in front of our eyes, but the script is rather more durable. It has
cultural clout.
All the same, the market for playscripts is an uncertain one. You might take
Irvine Welsh or A.L Kennedy to bed with you, but how many people settle down
with a good John Byrne? A script is a functional thing, more commonly studied
in schools than slipped
in between your airport novels and your bonk-busters. Theatre Scotland
magazine, which I have edited for the past three years, uses a Trojan horse
approach - lure them in with a David Mamet interview or a Robbie Coltrane
feature, then catch them unawares
with a John Binnie romance or a Stuart Paterson fable. It's a trick that has
enabled Theatre Scotland to publish 15 plays since 1992, a figure unmatched
since the days of John Calder's publications and those of the Scottish Society
of Playwrights in the
1970s.
Call it coincidence, but 1995 was relatively healthy all round for Scottish
play publication. The year began with Methuen's Made in Scotland, an anthology
of four plays selected by me and Ian Brown of the Traverse Theatre. Recognition
for Sue Glover's Bon
dagers, Simon Donald's The Life of Stuff, Mike Cullen's The Cut and Duncan
McLean's Julie Allardyce was more than justified. All but McLean's play have
enjoyed success within and without Scotland and are in the process of being
rewritten for film by the a
uthors. McLean, of course, is celebrated among the bright new wave of Scottish
novelists, but his roots, going back to his days with the Merry Mac Fun Co, lie
equally in performance.
Methuen, under new publisher Michael Earley, is keeping a keen eye on Scottish
playwrights. It published Iain Heggie's An Experienced Woman Gives Advice to
coincide with the play's Manchester run, and picked up on David Harrower's
professional debut, Kniv
es in Hens, in time for its Traverse Theatre transfer to London. Earley has
also expressed interest in Tom McGrath's Scots translation of Stones and Ashes,
the Quebecois play by Daniel Danis that was the highlight of the Traverse's
autumn season.
Of the other London publishers, Oberon maintained its loyalty to Robert David
MacDonald, the Citizens' Theatre's resident polyglot, printing his translations
of Schiller's The Robbers (seen at London's Gate Theatre) and Don Carlos (seen
at the Edinburgh F
estival and in Glasgow). Meanwhile, Faber and Faber not only brought out a
collected edition of the plays of Sharman Macdonald, including her best known
piece, When I was a Girl I used to Scream and Shout, but also was honoured by
having it shortlisted fo
r the McVitie's Prize.
It's heartening to find that back at home passion and commitment are as
fashionable commodities as strict commercial sense. On the west coast the small
publishing house Dualchas has been turning out a slow but steady stream of
oddball writers, sometimes n
ovelists, sometimes playwrights, mainly unclassifiable and all with a lively
sense of performance. ``They're not following traditional narrative styles,
they're more theatrical or dramatic,'' agrees Morag Ramsay of Dualchas whose
most recent release, Hels
inki (Not the Town) by F.N O'Gafferty, is a curious collection of urban
Glaswegian stories and dialogues, not written for the stage but as often as not
looking just like a script.
``Why should there be a strict dividing line?'' says Ramsay. ``We've got a
project for next May with a new author who has written the missing pages of
Gogol's diary. We're going to try and stage it as a play as well. We're trying
to bring all the expressi
ve arts together because they can support each other. We're not doing it for
profit. There's no question that we're doing it for any business reasons. We're
doing it for the content - stuff that we think is worth publishing.''
Over in the east, operating out of Old Grindles Bookshop in Spittal Street,
Diehard Publishers has recently expanded its list to encompass playwrights,
among them John Cargill Thompson, Joy Hendry and Owen Dudley Edwards. ``We
started off as a general pub
lisher and the drama side took off more than the rest,'' says Diehard's Ian
King who has his own binding machine which gives him great flexibility in the
size of his print runs. ``When I was young the problem was that all the scripts
in the library were 5
0 years out of date and, stuck in Dunfermline, you ended up writing like
Bernard Shaw because that's what you got thrust upon you. I wanted to get away
from that syndrome of everybody writing old-fashioned plays. We'll be doing
these scripts five or six t
imes a year.''
King admits that play publishing is something of a kamikaze field, although his
most popular titles have sold out and even returned a small profit. Like
Ramsay, he's prepared to do it for the love of it how else could you account
for the six months of met
iculous proof-reading he's just put in to his next release, the early plays of
George Buchanan, a contemporary of John Knox, whose output was entirely in
Latin? He's not expecting a best seller.
For all this activity, though, I'm well aware that I'd never write an article
trumpeting about the number of plays published by English writers. Scotland's a
considerably smaller country, of course, but we're still talking about a pretty
feeble number of
publications. That's not a reflection on the publishers, who can hardly be said
to be raking in the money after all, it's more an indictment of a theatre
system that for one reason or another is not giving adequate voice to its
playwrights.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000124</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000124</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>TRANSPORT Stagecoach makes track for Docklands</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kirsty Dorsey</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>23</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651613</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOLLOWING its victory in the battle for South West Trains, bus giant Stagecoach
has confirmed its appetite for further railway acquisitions, writes KRISTY
DORSEY.
A spokesman for the Perth-based company said yesterday that Stagecoach was
considering making a bid for London's Docklands Light Railway (DLR), which runs
driverless trains in the east of the City's financial district. ``All I can say
is Stagecoach has ex
pressed a preliminary interest (in the franchise),'' the spokesman said.
An earlier statement from DLR said consultation on the future of the line had
prompted ``significant interest'' from potential bidders. The formal
competition for the franchise is set to begin early next year, and the
successful bidder is expected to be i
dentified in the autumn.
Company chairman Brian Souter has said that Stagecoach intends to bid for all
available franchises and is particularly interested in the London commuter
services, which makes a DLR bid seem all the more likely.
Stagecoach shares reached a record high yesterday, extending gains made since
the successful South West Trains bid. The stock closed up 12p at 352p, its
sixth day of gains since closing at 282p on December 18.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000125</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000125</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Having trouble with carols</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651614</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PROFESSOR Steve Bruce has proved that Scrooge is still alive and as ill as ever
(December 23).
At a time when there are more Christian believers in the world than at any time
in the history of our faith he says that there are not many of us.
Certainly he claims to be speaking for Scotland, but the fact that 14% of
Scottish adults were sitting in pews on an unheralded Sunday in 1994 is far
from being the whole story.
He adds, without the slightest evidence, that perhaps a further 20% believe in
a personal God. That figure could just as easily be 60%. That would get much
closer, with the 14%, to the 80% who have been reported as claiming belief in
God.
He has trouble with carols. He's not alone on that. The bleak midwinter, though
true of Scotland this year, is not true of all Christians' Christmases. But
Jesus Christ is.
That he was born and lived and died and was raised from death is my belief. It
is also well attested by contemporary records. It is therefore the one truth
about my world that transcends all the hype of modern media and even Professor
Bruce's Scrooge-like
opinions.
I remain one of those clergymen who hope that his annual visit to Church might
prompt a more enduring response. What I'm not is poor.
My riches are my convictions about the Christ who, for me and millions like me,
demonstrated in his own person that love did come down at Christmas, love all
lovely, love divine; and that, praise be, we are all the better for that love.
Professor Bruce is entitled to take his atheism seriously. He is not entitled
to assume that any particular percentage of his fellow-citizens join him in
voting for Scrooge.
He overstates his weight. One look at the sheer enjoyment, faith, and love on
the faces of the people I greeted at our midnight celebration on Christmas Eve
might jolt his dyspeptic unbelief into an infectious faith.
Such a faith would be suitable for children, yes; but also for those adults who
still want to learn how to love.
Perhaps Professsor Bruce would do us a service by composing a new, more honest
carol. I would be interested to read it, and even to sing it, provided that it
honours the Child in the Manger.
Rev Maxwell Craig,
Scottish Churches House,
Dunblane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000126</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000126</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tourism director defiant in job row</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651615</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A QUANGO director has vowed he will not quit his job, despite being barred by a
sheriff from holding company directorships.
Hotelier Martin Hill, of Coul House Hotel, Strathpeffer, Ross-shire, is a
director of the newly-appointed Highlands of Scotland Tourist Board. At a
hearing at Dingwall Sheriff Court in October, Sheriff James Fraser banned him
from holding a company direct
orship for two years.
Along with Inverness businessman Alastair Gardner and former Black Isle
resident Ned Wayne, Mr Hill accepted responsibility for inadequate book-keeping
and records as directors of a failed tourist booking agency, Hi-Line.
A breach of the Companies Act involving an #11,000 car loan was also brought to
light in the Department of Trade and Industry case.
Hi-Line went into liquidation owing #358,000.
Although it was stressed during the action that there had been no question of
dishonesty on the part of the three men, the soon-to-be wound up Ross and
Cromarty Tourist Board advised Mr Hill to quit the post after the court ruling,
despite previously back
ing his application.
Ross and Cromarty Tourist Board chairman Ian McCrae said: ``He quite flatly
refused to resign when the board asked me to go and see him. He said he had
done nothing wrong and, of course, he was within his rights.
``But, to put it bluntly, I do not like it. This has caused a great deal of
irritation.
``My personal opinion is, and I do not care what the circumstances are, the way
forward should have been for him to resign from both Ross and Cromarty and the
new board.''
The HSTB takes power next April after the national reorganisation of tourist
boards.
The new board's chairman, hotelier Nicol Manson, said there were no plans to
take Mr Hill out of the unpaid post.
He said: ``Just because Mr Hill is barred from being a director of a limited
company, a company limited by guarantee, does not mean he should not be a
director of the Highlands of Scotland Tourist Board, which is a statutory body.
``They are not alike, and there is no comparison - it's as simple as that.''
Mr Hill, 53, confirmed he had been asked to resign by Ross and Cromarty Tourist
Board.
He said: ``I do not think I have done anything to be ashamed of. It is
ridiculous for anyone to say there is a need for me to resign from a public
body.
``I know my reputation has been dented but I feel we were made scapegoats.''
The Scottish Tourist Board's depute director of visitor services said: ``From
the legal position, everything is OK, but as for the moral question, I do not
think the STB can comment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951229-000127</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951229-000127</DOCID>
<DATE>951229</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Misplaced blame for declining numbers</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651616</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ONCE again a minister of the Church of Scotland, the Rev Ivor Gibson, seeks to
lay the blame for the decline in membership outwith the life of the church
itself, saying: ``There is an appalling ignorance of the Christian message
thanks largely to the fail
ure of Religious Education in schools, the collapse of Sunday school, and the
lack of church going'' (December 27).
It may well be the task of Sunday school to make Christians, and it might be
more effective in this task if it stopped recruiting young people who have not
yet worked out their own faith and using them as Sunday school teachers because
no-one else wants t
he responsibility.
It most certainly is the task of church members to bring people to the church,
and hopefully into the faith of the church. They might be more effective in
this if they stopped thinking faith was a private and personal matter.
It is not, and has never been, the task of Religious Education to make
Christians. Religious Education seeks to help pupils find meaning and purpose
in life, and to understand the contribution of the various religions to this
search.
This does not mean indoctrination or evangelism within the classroom, but an
open educational search. It seeks to equip pupils with the tools for the task
and the knowledge and understanding to help in the search.
Pupils are very aware of the valuable contribution that Christianity makes to
this search. They are aware of the words and the challenges of Jesus and the
claims of the church. Sadly they are also aware of the lives of many Christians
whom they meet in th
eir day-to-day lives. So often the two do not correspond.
Christianity for many of them seems to say one thing and the actions of
Christians another. Once these two are in harmony, the church might play a more
active role in the search for meaning and purpose in the lives of young people.
Rev T R Taylor,
Principal Teacher Religious Education,
8 Moray Place, Kirkintilloch.
