<HEADLINE>Problems caused by poverty of the pulpit</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>974651617</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I WAS saddened and angered to read Robert Wilson's statement that retiring
clerics should move away from the district in which they served (December 26).
Mr Wilson clearly does not understand the problems caused by the poverty of the
pulpit. The cleric's stipend and retirement pension are so low that he is
likely to be dependent on the earnings of his wife and children in order to
avoid destitution.
In my family's case where we lived on quitting the tied house on my father's
retirement from the ministry depended upon where I and my brother worked.
Furthermore, my father's stipend was so low that we were not able to apply for
posts away from home as our earnings were needed in order to provide for the
immediate needs of our parents as well as for ourselves. We had to act as
carers from a very early
age.
Not only is it un-Christian to dump people when they are perceived to be no
longer useful but it is also very hurtful.
Should not church members put enough in the plate in order to finance a
properly paid clergy? Only when this is done can clergy and their families have
the opportunity of choosing where they shall live.
Margaret M H Lyth,
26 Gardenside Street,
Uddingston.
</TEXT>
